<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-HomerunKid     06-09 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Homerun Kid,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coaches Won't Let Young Slugger Hit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Little League slugger Mike Curran has
hit six homeruns in his last 10 games. Now none of the opposing
teams will pitch to him, raising questions of less-than-adult
sportsmanship, his coaches say.
   Curran, 12, has a batting average of .888 and plays for the
league's top team, the Orioles. Harvey Katzen, one of Curran's
coaches, says the decision by the league's other coaches to
consistently walk the hot hitter fails to set a good example for
the players. Curran has been walked 12 times in his last four games.
   ``What are you teaching the kids? When they encounter a
difficult situation in life, they should avoid it?'' Katzen said.
   Curran's father, James P. Curran, said the general decision to
keep walking his son is unfair.
   ``The Little League should be for the kids, not the managers,''
he said. ``He's being punished because he is good.''
   The Middlesex News reported Thursday that the opposing coaches
have continued to intentionally walk the slugger despite a
league-wide advisory issued last week discouraging use of the
tactic.
   But the young player is taking it in stride.
   ``When they walk me, I just think about getting them back when I
pitch,'' he said. ``It's a joke really.''
   Curran has pitched two no-hitters this season.
</TEXT>
