<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Phantom-LA     06-09 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phantom-LA,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hit Broadway Musical Comes to LA in May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' which swept
seven Tony Awards including Best Musical, will make its debut here
next May, says the show's British producer.
   ``We'll run the show as long as the Los Angeles public wants it
there,'' producer Cameron Mackintosh said from London Wednesday.
   The latest creation by British musical whiz Andrew Lloyd Webber
tells the story of a disfigured man in a mask who abducts the prima
donna of the Paris Opera House to the city sewers below.
   The show, which is scheduled to preview May 18 at the Los
Angeles County Music Center, will move to the Ahmanson Theater as
the fourth and final show of the 1988-89 Ahmanson season, and could
be booked for an extended run.
   The local ``Phantom'' will a new production with a budget
between $7 million and $8 million, Mackintosh said. Harold Prince,
who directed the New York version, will direct the Los Angeles, he
said.
</TEXT>
