<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-InteriorMoney     06-09 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interior Money,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Measure Calls For Spending 10 Times Reagan Request On Land
Acquisition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee is recommending
continuation of bans on federal oil lease sales off the coasts of
California and New England and renewal of one covering part of
Florida's coast.
   The stance was taken Wednesday by the Appropriations interior
subcommittee as it gave voice-vote approval to a $9.7 billion
spending package for the Interior Department and the U.S. Forest
Service for the year beginning Oct. 1.
   The legislation would continue the bans that Congress has been
placing yearly on leasing oil and gas tracts in northern California
and along the Georges Bank in the Atlantic.
   It would also reinstate a leasing ban for southwest Florida
waters that had been imposed by Congress through September 1987.
   Chairman Sidney Yates, D-Ill., said he thought the proposed
bans, lasting through Sept. 30, 1989, would be endorsed by the full
committee at a vote scheduled for next week.
   The subcommittee bill, giving the department $400 million more
than it is receiving this year, would boost spending by the
National Park Service to $950 million, an increase of $50 million
over current levels.
   The legislation would provide $170 million to acquire land for
wildlife refuges and other open-space uses. That is more than 10
times the $15 million requested by the Reagan administration.
   Under the spending plan, the U.S. Forest Service would get $1.8
billion, a $100 million increase. Construction of logging roads
would be set at $166 million, down from the current $196 million.
   For the second straight year, the Tongass National Forest in
Alaska would get less than the $50 million annual appropriation it
is supposed to receive under a temporarily suspended federal law.
   The huge forest, which conservationists say is being
overharvested by commercial timbering, would get $31 million, $12
million below this year's level and $22 million under what the
administration sought for fiscal 1989.
</TEXT>
