<HEAD>Spielberg's Amblin Productions Gets Into Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burned but not shy after its unsuccessful
venture with ``Amazing Stories'' two years ago, Steven Spielberg's
Amblin Entertainment is ready to plunge into television in a big
way.
   Amblin has organized a new television division to be headed by
Carole M. Kirschner, the company announced Wednesday. She had been
director of comedy development at CBS, where she worked on such
shows as ``Designing Women,'' ``Frank's Place'' and ``Coming of
Age.''
   Amblin's new television division will concentrate on developing
TV series programming, particularly half-hour comedies and
hour-long concepts.
   Spielberg's company is most noted for its motion pictures, which
include the monster hit ``E.T. - The Extraterrestrial,'' ``The
Color Purple,'' and ``The Money Pit.''
   His first venture into television since founding Amblin was
``Amazing Stories'' for NBC two years ago. It was a critical and a
ratings failure.
