<DOCNO> AP880609-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     06-09 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush To Take The Offensive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, trying to
recapture lost ground in public opinion polls, is revamping his
campaign tactics and will seek to take the offensive in the weeks
ahead, campaign advisers say.
   Part of Bush's new post-primary strategy will include trying to
paint Democrat Michael Dukakis as an ultra-liberal ``to the left of
(Walter) Mondale,'' said campaign official Ed Rogers, referring to
the 1984 Democratic presidential candidate.
   ``The guy (Dukakis) is a wimp. The guy opposes every major
weapons system there is. He is for the nuclear freeze, he is
against more aircraft carriers, he is for pulling troops out of
South Korea. He's a Sandinista lover. He'll blast our allies and
say nothing bad about the Sandinistas or Castro,'' Rogers said.
   But other Bush advisers, and prominent Republican leaders,
caution that such attacks could go too far.
   ``You don't become president by only diminishing your opponent.
That, in fact, enlarges your opponent,'' said Rep. Lynn Martin,
R-Ill., national co-chair of Bush's presidential campaign.
   John Sears, a Washington lawyer and political consultant who
managed Ronald Reagan's unsuccessful 1976 presidential bid, agreed.
   ``He isn't that far back in the polls to be desperate,'' Sears
said. ``Attacks on Dukakis at this point could come back in his
face. He should be out there making positive points about what this
administration has accomplished and not let the agenda be
constructed by the Democrats.''
   Bush, changing gears with the Tuesday's end of the primary
season, was embarking today on a series of appearances aimed at
building up party unity and broadening his base of support outside
the traditional GOP constituencies.
   The vice president was flying to his adopted hometown of
Houston, where he will meet with a group of Hispanics and address
the Texas state Republican convention.
   On Friday, he'll travel to Denver for the first in a series of
what the GOP has billed ``Unity '88'' conferences. Bush will be
joined there by three vanquished Republican White House hopefuls _
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, Rep. Jack Kemp and television
evangelist Pat Robertson.
   Meanwhile, Reagan on Tuesday promised to do ``everything I can''
to help Bush win in November and said Bush shouldn't worry about
his underdog status in the polls.
   ``I'd say, `George, wait until you and I get out there on the
trail and start pinning him (Dukakis) down on the things he claims,
which we know are not true,''' Reagan said during a
question-and-answer session with regional reporters.
   Reagan said Bush had ``a part of everything we've accomplished
in this administration.''
   The president appeared unconcerned about recent attempts by Bush
to distance himself from the administration's policies.
   In particular, Reagan was asked to respond to comments the vice
president made about the Soviet Union and human rights issues,
which seemed at odds with Reagan's more positive assessments voiced
at the Moscow summit.
   ``No, he's being as careful as we all must be,'' Reagan said.
   Bush advisers said that candidate's post-primary strategy will
focus on Dukakis' record as governor of Massachusetts and will
stress both his lack of foreign policy experience and his
opposition to weapons systems.
   A Republican party official knowledgeable about the Bush
campaign's general election strategy said that Bush was unlikely to
break with Reagan over any heavyweight issues such as the 1981 tax
cuts, the easing of government regulation of business or the
military buildup.
   ``I don't think Bush is going to give a `stop the bombing'
statement like Hubert Humphrey, when he broke with Lyndon Johnson
over Vietnam,'' said the official, who spoke only on condition of
anonymity.
   In fact, this official said, the Bush campaign may be spending
too much time engaging in discussions of the candidate's obstacles
to election this fall. ``There may be too much
temperature-taking,'' he said.
   Bush will be partly constrained in his activities until after he
formally receives the GOP nomination in August by a shortage of
funds.
   The campaign is within just $1 million of the federal
pre-convention $27 million spending limit and had to lay off dozens
of campaign workers. But aides said Bush would take advantage of
other fund-raising events _ including today's Texas GOP convention
and Friday's unity dinner in Denver.
   ``We can raise money for the Republican National Committee, for
Republican candidates, for the unity conferences, for state
parties,'' said Bush spokesman Stephen Hart.
</TEXT>
