<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     06-09 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Endorsement For Dukakis _ Finally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo finally endorsed
Michael Dukakis for the Democratic presidential nomination, but
insists his support was ``never relevant.''
   In the early stages of the campaign, many Democrats had hoped
that Cuomo might emerge as the nominee. Cuomo repeatedly said he
wasn't running, but refused to flatly rule out a draft until less
than two months ago.
   Cuomo gave his backing to Dukakis on Wednesday, a day after the
Massachusetts governor wrapped up the nomination in the final four
primaries of the season.
   Cuomo's public endorsement of Dukakis came only after prodding
by reporters at the governor's news conference. When Cuomo revealed
that he had talked to Dukakis on Wednesday morning, reporters asked
about an endorsement, and Cuomo brushed the question aside.
   ``For months, I said I was for whoever comes out of the primary
process first ... so that was a fait accompli as soon as the
primaries were over,'' said Cuomo.
   Pressed on the point, he said, ``It's an empty question. ... My
endorsement was never relevant.''
   ``Why can't you bring yourself to say that you endorse him?''
one reporter finally asked.
   ``I endorse him! I endorse him! I endorse him!'' Cuomo burst out
in response. ``There, three times I endorsed him.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dukakis Picks Up Gephardt Endorsement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis has gained the support
of Rep. Richard Gephardt, a former rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   Dukakis, who stopped briefly at Lambert St. Louis Airport on
Wednesday, told a small group of supporters and local politicians
that he was happy to have the Missouri congressman's endorsement.
   ``I will not forget his support,'' Dukakis said.
   Gephardt asked every Democrat who had stood with him before to
stand with him once more as he throws his support to Dukakis.
   ``Together we can regain America's true strength, reclaim
America's true legacy, and restore America's true promise,''
Gephardt said. ``That is the vision Mike Dukakis and I share. That
is the fight we now wage together.''
   Dukakis staffers released a list of Missouri delegates who they
say are switching support to Dukakis. At least 27 of Gephardt's
remaining 42 delegates in Missouri have now committed to Dukakis,
according to Gephardt aide Joyce Aboussie.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dukakis Kin Celebrate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of Michael Dukakis from the
island of Mytilene on Wednesday hailed his success in wrapping up
the Democratic presidential nomination as ``a great achievement for
us and for Greece.''
   In Pelopi, home of the Dukakis family before they migrated to
the United States, the village council already has renamed the main
street after him.
   They also erected a pair of signs on the dirt road leading to
Pelopi announcing in Greek and English: ``Welcome to the home town
of Michael Dukakis.''
   ``Michael's progress is a great achievement for us and for
Greece. He deserves to become president. ... I think he could write
a golden page in Greek history,'' Mrs. Cleopatra Stephanidou, a
second cousin of the Massachussetts governor, said in a telephone
interview from Mytilene.
   Costas Stephanou, president of the Pelopi village council and a
distant family relative, said by telephone: ``This is really a
great achievement. I'm convinced he can become president.''
   Stephanou said residents of Pelopi, a village of just over 600
people, have been closely following primary election results for
weeks, hoping that Dukakis would wrap up the nomination.
</TEXT>
