<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     06-09 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Pushing Hard For Vice Presidential Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says the vice presidency is a
great job and anyone who thinks he wouldn't want it should think
again.
   While Jackson didn't come out and say he wants the post, he used
glowing terms Wednesday to characterize it as ``a position of great
leadership and great responsibility.''
   ``You understand my background?'' the Baptist minster who was
born illegitimately to a poor teen-age girl in South Carolina asked
reporters Wednesday.
   ``The vice presidency is not quite the top, but it's a long way
from where I started,'' he added, speaking on the day after he
suffered a final round of primary losses to Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson arrived Wednesday night at the posh La Costa resort near
San Diego. He had no activities scheduled today except an afternoon
meeting with aides.
   Jackson has been saying for some time that he deserves to be
considered for the No. 2 spot on the ticket. After Dukakis won
enough delegates for the nomination, Jackson took it one step
further.
   ``Consideration means an offer,'' he said. ``If in fact, the
offer is made, at that time I'll make a judgment but I've earned
that option.''
   He told reporters he has a good resume for the job.
   ``If the issue is we need someone from the South _ I'm from the
South,'' he said. ``Someone who can mobilize masses of Democrats _
I've done that. Someone not limited to regional appeal but has
national appeal _ I've won primaries'' across the nation.
   On the day after Dukakis beat him resoundingly in the last four
primary contests Jackson was asked if he were conceding the
nomination.
   ``Of course not,'' he said. ``The nominee will be determined by
the convention in Atlanta.''
   However, he extended congratulations to Dukakis on Tuesday night
after the Massachusetts governor won primaries in California, New
Jersey, New Mexico and Montana.
   Jackson said he will be contacting all the so-called super
delegates and at-large delegates, even those who have announced
support for Dukakis.
   ``These delegates are by definition not committed until they
vote. Their votes are fluid. We will compete in every state and in
every congressional district for their support,'' he said.
   Jackson announced a busy schedule for the weeks leading up to
the convention.
   He will hold strategy meetings with advisers regarding the
convention and a series of meetings with interest groups, beginning
next week with civil rights leaders in Chicago.
   Jackson also plans speaking appearances, a voter registration
drive, and a strategy to woo more delegates to his side.
   Between now and the convention, Jackson said, he wants to press
Dukakis and the Democrats to come around to his positions on issues
and on delegate selection rules that he considers unfair.
   He indicated he expects to have such changes apply not only to
future conventions but to be put in place this year to help him
garner the added delegate strength he believes he has earned.
   He cited Pennsylvania and New Jersey where the winner of each
district gets all that district's delegates, rather than having
them distributed proportionately according to the popular vote. For
Jackson that resulted in far fewer delegates than he would have
received if they were chosen proportionately.
   He said he had spoken Wednesday morning to Democratic Party
chairman Paul Kirk and was confident they could work out ``some
remedy.''
</TEXT>
