<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-StalloneGuard     06-09 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Stallone Guard,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodyguard Foils Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A part-time bodyguard for actor Sylvester
Stallone foiled a bank robbery after he spotted a suspicious
customer while driving by the bank.
   Skystone-Eagle Lambert, 34, was off duty Monday from his regular
job as a patrolman for the Santa Monica Police Department when he
noticed a bicyclist wearing a heavy black jacket, despite
temperatures in the high 60s.
   Lambert watched the man park his mountain bike in an alley
behind the First Interstate Bank of California in Gardena, 12 miles
south of downtown Los Angeles.
   ``We are trained to spot suspicious circumstances,'' Lambert
said. ``It's my police instinct.''
   Lambert followed his suspicions as the bicyclist got in line.
Lambert quietly warned bank officials about a possible robbery.
   The man handed a teller a note reading, ``Don't scream, I have a
gun, give me all your money or I will blow your head off,'' police
said.
   The teller handed the robber an undisclosed amount of cash, then
shouted ``We've been robbed!'' as the bicyclist ran out the front
door.
   Lambert ran out a back door. By the time the robber ran to his
bike, Lambert was waiting with a 9mm semi-automatic pistol leveled
at the suspect.
   The off-duty officer held the man until police arrived. Raymond
Jackson, 21, was booked for investigation of bank robbery and held
for the FBI, police said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-CatastrophicQ&A     06-09 0944</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Catastrophic Q&A,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How the New Program Will Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Catastrophic Health Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some questions and answers about the
House-Senate compromise catastrophic health insurance bill.
   Q: What's the purpose behind this legislation?
   A: To insure America's 32 million Medicare beneficaries _ most
of them elderly _ against financial ruin from a particular illness
or series of illnesses.
   Q: How does it do this?
   A: By setting a limit on the amount of money people covered by
Medicare will have to pay out of their pockets. Above that limit,
the government picks up the costs.
   Q: How is it financed?
   A: By the Medicare beneficiaries themselves.
   Q. How?
   A: Through a combination of flat monthly premiums on all
Medicare recipients and an additional supplemental premium that
works like an income tax surcharge _ it assesses those who can
afford to pay more.
   Q: But it's only the elderly who have to pay the higher tax?
   A: The elderly and about 3 million disabled people under age 65
who are covered by Medicare. The tax would be imposed if they have
enough taxable income to pay income taxes.
   Q: There are about 29 million elderly people. You mean their
taxes are being raised?
   A: Estimates are that about 60 percent of the people over 65
don't have enough income to pay income taxes and therefore will pay
only the higher flat monthly premium.
   Q: How much is that?
   A: In the first year of the plan, 1989, it is $4 a month. By
1993, the ``catastrophic'' monthly premium will be $10.20.
   Q: What about the tax for the other 40 percent?
   A: It varies according to income. For example, it starts at
$22.50 a year per $150 of federal income tax liability in 1989 and
rises to $42 a year per $150 of tax liability in 1993.
   Q: How much money does a person have to make before having to
pay the supplemental premium?
   A: The estimates are that individuals with incomes below $10,000
a year would not be subject to the supplemental premium _ or tax
surcharge if that is what you prefer to call it.
   Q: What do they get for their money?
   A: Medicare will pay full charges for 365 days hospitalization a
year instead of 60 days, as the law presently provides. There is a
one day deductible of $564 in 1989.
   Q: I have to pay that deductible every time I go in the hospital
now. Does that change?
   A: Yes. No matter how many times you are hospitalized from 1989
on, or for how many total days, you only pay one deductible a year.
   Q: How about doctor bills?
   A: Medicare will pay all ``reasonable and proper'' charges after
you pay out $1,370 from your own pocket in any given year.
   Q: That doesn't sound like an improvement. I only have to pay a
$75 deductible now before Medicare kicks in.
   A: That's true, but under the new plan Medicare still will pay
80 percent of your ``reasonable and proper'' charges after the $75
deductible. Under the expansion, the $75 you pay up front and your
20 percent share will count toward your $1,370 annual ``cap.''
After that, Medicare pays 100 percent of ``reasonable and proper''
charges.
   Q: ``Reasonable and proper'' _ that sounds like some kind of
loophole.
   A: It is important to understand what that means so you won't be
surprised by a big bill Medicare won't pay. Medicare has a set fee
schedule for every kind of treatment provided by doctors, and your
doctor knows what that fee is. However, many think it is too low
and charge their customers more than what the government thinks is
``reasonable and proper.'' If your doctor is one of those, it is
between you and him or her to settle up on the amount Medicare
won't pay. An increasing number of doctors accept Medicare as
payment in full and the government is trying to push even more to
do so.
   Q: Didn't I hear something about a new prescription drug benefit?
   A: Yes; there will be a general prescription drug benefit for
the first time since Medicare was set up 23 years ago. Medicare
will pay half of outpatient drug costs, after a $600 annual
deductible, starting in 1991. Medicare pays 60 percent the
following year and 80 percent in 1993 and thereafter.
   Q: Anything else new?
   A: Effective in 1990, Medicare will pay for a mammogram every
other year for women 65 and older and at various intervals for
younger women covered by Medicare.
   Q: I hear this bill does nothing for people who have to go into
nursing homes.
   A: That's correct, if you're talking long-term custodial care,
the sort of situation in which an elderly person too frail to live
alone _ but not necessarily needing hospitalization _ goes to a
nursing home.
   Q: What other kind is there?
   A. What is called skilled nursing home care where a person needs
special care to recuperate from a serious illness.
   Q: What does this bill do in that area?
   A: Expands the number of days covered from 100 days to 150 days
per year. And the person covered no longer will have to spend at
least three days in a hospital before becoming eligible.
   Q: Anything else?
   A: Yes. Instead of having to pay $67.50 per day for each day
beyond 20 days out of his own pocket, as is the case now, after
1989 the person will have to pay $20.50 a day for the first eight
days and the next 142 days are free.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-HouseHomeCareRollCall 3Takes   06-09 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-House Home Care Roll Call, 3 Takes,</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the 243-169 roll call Wednesday by
which the House blocked consideration of a home health care bill
proposed by Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla.
   A ``yes'' vote is in favor of considering the bill, and there
were 169 ``yes'' votes.
   Voting yes were 145 Democrats and 24 Republicans.
   Voting no were 99 Democrats and 144 Republicans.
   Y is a yes vote. N is a no vote. X denotes those not voting.
   There are three vacancies in the 435-member House.
