<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Vonnegut     06-09 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Vonnegut,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vonnegut Says Play Not A Political Statement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 20 years after ``Happy Birthday, Wanda
June'' opened off-Broadway, author Kurt Vonnegut says he's glad the
play is no longer seen as a political statement.
   ``When the play opened, there were strong divisions about the
Vietnam War,'' said Vonnegut, 65. ``It was a confusing time. Today
it stands as a play and not a political statement, and I much
prefer it that way.''
   Last year, director Joe Abramo told Vonnegut the Rocky Mountain
Theater Guild planned to stage ``Wanda June'' in Denver. It was
scheduled to open today at the University of Denver.
   ``I envisioned him coming here to do some kind of workshop,''
Abramo said. ``He told me he had been on the road for many years
and was staying away from that. But he was happy that someone was
doing the play.''
   In ``Wanda June,'' a swaggering adventurer and male supremacist
named Harold Ryan returns from eight years in the Amazon rain
forest, having missed the 1960s altogether. His wife, Penelope,
believing Harold was dead, had formed a romantic attachment with a
pacifist.
   When Harold's roughneck values clash with her new love's
peacemongering, Penelope is forced to confront her feelings for
each man.
   The original production of ``Wanda June'' received mixed reviews
and was closed early because of an actors strike.
   ``It had the life it deserved,'' Vonnegut said. ``Novelists
aren't good playwrights anyway.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
