<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Ray Blanton, who served two
years in federal prison in a liquor license conspiracy case and is
now seeking a congressional seat, plans to marry for the second
time, an aide said.
   Blanton, 58, is to marry Karen Flynt of Washington, a former
staff member of the Appalachian Regional Commission, said Charlie
Burns, Blanton's campaign treasurer.
   Burns said Wednesday he did not know when or where the wedding
would be, but the Nashville Banner reported the ceremony would be
today in Washington.
   Blanton and his first wife, Betty, divorced in April.
   The ex-governor is running for the Democratic nomination for the
seat of U.S. Rep. Ed Jones, a Democrat who is retiring.
   Blanton served the prison term for his 1981 conviction on
charges of mail fraud, extortion and conspiracy in connection with
the issuance of 12 liquor licenses to his friends. A U.S. Supreme
Court ruling led to a judge's vacating of the mail fraud charges.
Blanton is appealing the other charges.
