<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ArabSummit     06-09 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arab Summit,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Asks For Support For Uprising; Arab Summit Does Not Respond</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat asked Arab
leaders for more support for Palestinian protests in Israeli-held
territories, and Jordan's King Hussein blamed the United States for
the Middle East deadlock.
   Despite Arafat's plea Wednesday, delegates from 20 nations at
the Arab League summit did not immediately extend new financial aid
for the uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Summit sources said Arab leaders were discussing financial
support for the uprising in the range of $300 million to $400
million to compensate for loss of income caused by strikes.
   But nothing had been done about by Wednesday evening.
   The three-day summit opened Tuesday to discuss ways of backing
the 6-month-old Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, in which more than 200 Palestinians have died.
   Hussein, speaking behind closed doors to the leaders of the
Palestine Liberation Organization and the Arab nations, endorsed
some aspects of Secretary of State George P. Shultz's Middle East
peace plan.
   But he accused the United States of dragging its feet on a
Middle East peace settlement.
   ``The United States has no Middle East policy other than support
for Israel,'' Hussein said.
   Hussein, who lost the West Bank to Israel in the 1967 war, urged
Arab states to keep up the pressure on Israel by encouraging and
subsidizing the continuing Palestinian revolt in the occupied
territories.
   The king renewed his endorsement of the PLO as the Palestinians'
``sole legitimate representative'' and said he would not be
involved in any peace process that did not include PLO
participation.
   Aides distributed copies of his speech to reporters.
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi meanwhile angered some
delegates by telling Arab leaders who collaborate with the United
States that they undermine the Arab cause and should ``go to
hell.'' He did not refer to any leaders by name.
   Gadhafi wore a white glove on his right hand, and one Libyan
delegate said the glove was intended to ``avoid contact with a hand
that shook that of (Israeli Foreign Minister) Shimon Peres.''
   Morocco's King Hassan II received Peres, then prime minister, in
July 1986.
   Hussein also said in his speech that if Arab leaders make the
establishment of a Palestinian state a condition for a peace
conference, then ``we shall not differ with them on that.''
   But he cautioned that such a stand, which conflicts sharply with
American and Israeli positions, may end hope for convening an
international Middle East peace conference.
   Egypt was not invited to the summit. It was suspended from the
Arab League in 1979 after agreeing to the Camp David peace accord
with Israel.
</TEXT>
