<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-USMissiles Bjt   06-09 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Missiles, Bjt,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Missile Base All Ready For The Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cumbersome launchers and the
cruise missiles are lined up inside this U.S. Air Force base, the
anti-nuclear protesters remain outside _ and everybody is waiting
for the Soviet inspectors.
   ``They could do it today, I'm ready to go,'' said Col. William
E. Jones, an ebullient Tennessean who is the commander at Greenham
Common, 50 miles west of London.
   ``I have 29 launchers, I have 101 missiles. Everything I have is
for display,'' he said Wednesday.
   In the background, photographers milled round a 55-foot missile
launcher _ on show for the first time.
   U.S. military authorities lifted the veil at Greenham Common and
two other intermediate-range nuclear missile bases, at Florennes,
Belgium, and Mutlangen, a Pershing II missile base in West Germany,
ahead of the Soviet visits.
   The teams of up to 10 inspectors are due to arrive at 16 hours
notice sometime in July or August, implementing the first step of
the superpower accord to eliminate by 1991 the 2,700 land-based
intermediate range missiles both sides have deployed in Europe.
   The initial checks under the agreement ratified June 1 are to
inspect the missiles before they are dismantled.
   While Soviet inspectors visit 12 bases in five West European
countries and 14 in the United States, American teams have a
reciprocal right to check 133 sites in Eastern Europe.
   During the Greenham display, the launchers, which are scheduled
for destruction along with their missiles, trundled out of giant
bunkers ringed by four layers of rolled barbed wire _ then roared
through muddy lanes, showing off their paces.
   On the perimeter fence, a favorite target of protesters, hung a
banner with the slogan, ``Bread Not Bombs.'' A solitary woman
protester tried to climb the fence, but jumped back and disappeared.
   Outside a nearby gate, a dishevelled half-dozen group of women
protesters sat round a camp fire, a broken baby carriage and other
litter in the background.
   Women protesters have camped at Greenham since 1981 _ two years
before the cruise missiles arrived.
   On Wednesday, they said that they, or others, will still be
living in the tent and plastic camps here long after the missiles
have gone _ ever-suspicious that cruise missiles will simply be
replaced by something just as deadly.
   ``The Americans have a history of reneging on agreements,'' said
a young woman in her 20s, a former clerk who identified herself as
Xak Aroo.
   ``So they're going to take out the cruise _ it's no big deal. We
object to Americans being here anyway.''
   Inside the base, preparations have included fullscale rehearsals
_ mock inspections with Pentagon officials playing the part of
Soviet inspectors.
   ``The first group played very belligerent _ out of sorts Soviets
_ and we had to deal with that,'' said Lt. Col. Michael McCarney.
   ``The second group were what we expect _ very professional, very
businesslike Soviets and we found that ... you really could do the
inspection in two to three hours.''
   McCarney, project director for the inspection arrangements, said
he does not expect suspicion to cloud each Soviet visit.
   ``I think they are as anxious as we are to make this thing
work,'' he said.
   The fine print of the agreement means that the longest Soviet
teams can stay on any one inspection visit is 4{ days.
   The visitors will fly to Greenham and remain at the base _ or go
under escort to the second cruise base in Britain, at Molesworth,
near Cambridge, where 24 missiles are deployed.
   McCarney said he's laying on a few extra touches _ miniature
bottles of vodka and videos. He's also been collecting Sears,
Roebuck department store catalogues because, he said, that's what
Soviets who inspected a facility in San Diego recently took home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
