<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Down, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0403,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>C-130 Transport Crashes On Training Exercise, Killing All 6 Aboard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with authorities reporting six
deaths; quotes, complete IDs of victims; picks up 11th graf pvs,
`Bates said a ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GRM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military transport plane crashed and
burned in a fireball Wednesday near the Greenville airport, killing
the six Air National Guardsmen aboard, authorities and witnesses
said.
   The aircraft, a big four-engine turboprop C-130 used to
transport troops and equipment, crashed about a mile north of the
airport around 2:40 p.m.
   ``I went down there but you couldn't get close to it,'' said
Reggie Kellems, whose family owns the field where the plane
crashed. ``No one could have come out that thing _ and didn't.''
   The aircraft was assigned to the 189th Tactical Airlift Group of
the Arkansas Air National Guard and was on a training mission, said
Maj. Jim Bates, public affairs officer at Little Rock Air Force
Base.
   ``They had been with us for some time doing touch-and-go
training landings,'' said Richard Brewer, air traffic manager at
the northeast Mississippi airport. ``The plane was in the pattern
and the first we knew something was wrong was when it impacted.''
   Witnesses said the plane appeared to veer to its left as it was
landing and crashed into a clearing near the runway. Military
authorities sealed off the area shortly after the accident.
   ``When I saw it, it was a just a big fireball,'' said Kellems.
   Another witness said the plane appeared ``to nose straight into
the ground'' and the tail and six or seven feet of the body of the
plane were the only sections left intact.
   Four bodies were recovered by late Wednesday and the remains of
the two others were believed under the wreckage, said Col. Dennis
Wood, another spokesman for the base.
   A spokeswoman for the Air Force Base, Airman 1st Class Deborah
Doyle, identified the dead as:
   Maj. Andries R. Zwaan, 39, a pilot with the 189th Tactical Air
Lift Group at the Arkansas Air National Guard based in Little Rock;
Staff Sgt. David Bingham, 24, a member of the 181st Tactical Air
Lift Squadron at Hensley Field in Texas; 2nd Lt. Mark R. Brandt,
24, of the 180th Tactical Air Lift Squadron at Rosecrans Municipal
Airport at St. Joseph, Mo.; 2nd Lt. Thomas D. Leece, 28, whose home
unit is the 934th Tactical Airlift Group of Minneapolis, Minn.; and
Master Sgts. Edwin J. Smith Jr., 35, and Danny W. Holland, 39, both
assigned to the 189th.
   Bates said a board of officers will investigate the accident.
   Bates also said it is not unusual for members of the Arkansas
Air National Guard to be on training missions out of state.
   The most recent crash of a C-130 stationed at Little Rock was in
March 1985, when a crash near Fort Hood, Texas, killed six crewmen.
   Prior to that, seven airmen were killed when a C-130 exploded
and crashed near Judsonia, Ark., on May 12, 1982, due to mechanical
failure.
   Officials said that prior to the 1982 crash, human error was to
blame for five crashes and mechanical malfunctions were responsible
for two crashes.
   Bates said the Air National Guard has nine C-130s in Arkansas.
</TEXT>
