<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel Bjt   06-09 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, Bjt,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Calls General Strike To Mark Six Months Of Arab Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO underground leaders ordered Palestinians in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip to observe a general strike today to
mark six months of rebellion against Israel's 21-year occupation.
   Meanwhile, the Arab mayor of the West Bank town El Bireh, who
was stabbed in the heart in an assassination attempt, called on
other Israeli-appointed mayors to defy demands by Palestinian
militants that they step down.
   ``Justice is on my side because I'm serving the people,'' Hassan
Tawil, 74, told Israel television from his hospital bed Wednesday,
a day after he was stabbed outside his office.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said Arab militants have stepped
up attacks on Palestinian officials in the past three weeks and
offered the officials more protection, though telling Israel radio
``most can take care of themselves.''
   In two clashes near the West Bank city of Nablus on Wednesday,
troops shot and wounded four Palestinians, hospital officials said.
The army confirmed the shootings in the Balata refugee camp and the
nearby village Beit Fourik, but put the number of wounded at three.
   An Israeli driver suffered minor injuries when assailants threw
a firebomb at his car near the West Bank village Beit Ur Et Tahta,
the army said. Soldiers later clamped a curfew on the village.
   In a new leaflet issued this week, the United Leadership of the
Uprising, led by the Palestine Liberation Organization, ordered
Palestinians to shutter their stores and stay away from their jobs
today.
   Since the anti-occupation unrest began Dec. 8 in the lands
Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East war, 202 Palestinians and two
Israelis have been killed. More than 5,000 Arabs have been wounded
or injured and 5,000 are in jail.
   Tawil was reported in stable condition Wednesday night at
Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital.
   In his first interview since the stabbing, he said he was
determined to stay on the job.
   ``They (the leaders of the uprising) should come and talk to us
and explain how to work. If we are against the people, we will go.
But I think we are helping the people. This is a message for
everybody,'' he said.
   Tawil also described the attack for the first time. He said a
stranger approached him, demanded a passport, and then stabbed him.
   Tawil was appointed mayor of El Bireh, a town of 10,000 about
nine miles north of Jerusalem, in 1986.
   About a dozen mayors and 85 village council leaders appointed by
Israel serve in the West Bank. The municipalities and village
councils provide local services and serve as a buffer between
residents and Israeli military authorities.
   ``In the past three weeks, most of the firebombs and other
violence have been directed against other Arabs,'' Rabin told
Israel army radio during a tour of the Gaza Strip.
   In other developments, the head of Israel's military
intelligence, Maj. Gen. Amnon Shahak, said the Arab summit in
Algiers would have little influence on the uprising.
   ``I don't think (PLO chief Yasser) Arafat is waiting for Arab
summit decisions to run the struggle here,'' Shahak told Israel
television. ``What will happen (with the uprising) depends very
much on the residents themselves, on decisions they'll adopt
together with the PLO leadership.''
   Arafat had asked Arab leaders at the summit to help fund the
uprising.
</TEXT>
