<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Gandhi,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Premier Says Fundamentalist Afghan Regime Would Threaten
Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India
said southern Asia will be threatened if fundamentalist Moslems
take power in Afghanistan.
   ``We see the biggest danger in Afghanistan of a fanatical,
fundamentalist government, which would be the worst possible
situation for our region,'' Gandhi told reporters Wednesday at the
end of a three-day visit to West Germany.
   Gandhi called for strict adherence to the Geneva accords, under
which Soviet troops are being pulled out of Afghanistan after
helping the Marxist government fight U.S.-backed Moslem rebels for
nine years.
   ``We would like the Afghans to dictate their own future. We
would like a non-aligned Afghanistan, and one that is not fanatical
and fundamentalist,'' Gandhi said.
   Asked what India would do if fundamentalists did come to power
in Afghanistan, Gandhi said: ``We do not contemplate taking any
action.''
   Gandhi also accused Pakistan of not cooperating fully with the
Afghanistan accords, but he did not elaborate.
   Pakistan, the United States, the Soviet Union and Afghanistan
signed the accords in April. The Afghan guerrillas have operated
out of bases in neighboring Pakistan.
   Gandhi criticized Pakistan for allegedly helping Indian Sikh
militants who have been staging terrorist attacks in India's Punjab
state.
   ``Pakistan today is perhaps the largest supporter of terrorism
in the world,'' he said.
   Gandhi also said India has no intention of building a nuclear
bomb, but that he would have to ``look again at our options'' if
Pakistan did develop a nuclear weapon.
   ``We have demonstrated our will not to make nuclear weapons,
although we have that capability, and we will do everything not to
go down that road,'' Gandhi said.
</TEXT>
