<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-09 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>VA Finds No Conclusive Evidence of Agent Orange Health Effects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Veteran's Administration says there is a
``growing scientific consensus'' that the herbicide Agent Orange
cannot be conclusively blamed for cancer and other illnesses among
Vietnam veterans.
   Thomas E. Harvey, the VA deputy administrator, told the House
Committee on Veterans' Affairs on Wednesday studies have
demonstrated no basis for the nation to compensate Vietnam veterans
based on their exposure to Agent Orange.
   He said none of the numerous studies on dioxin, the contaminant
in Agent Orange, has established that the chemical causes cancers
or illness among veterans or birth defects in their children.
   But he told the panel further research is needed as a result of
one study that showed an ``inconclusive'' association between
herbicide exposure and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a type of cancer.
   Harvey said the VA's Agent Orange Registry has now recorded the
results of physical examinations of 220,000 Vietnam veterans and
``still does not show any unusual health patterns'' among them.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>S&L Deposits Still Rising Despite Publicity From Bailouts,</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Closings
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposits at savings and loans institutions
increased by $1.2 billion in April despite growing publicity about
federal bailouts and closings of troubled thrifts.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board reported Wednesday that April's
report was the seventh consecutive monthly increase and brought
deposits at the nation's 3,113 federally insured S&Ls to $962.4
billion.
   ``The steady deposit gains continue to indicate consumer
confidence in thrifts as a secure haven for funds,'' the bank board
said in a statement.
   The April deposit growth was less than the $4.3 billion increase
reported in March, but bank board economist James Barth said
deposit receipts normally decline in April as people pay their
federal income taxes.
   Net deposits during the first four months of this year totaled
$16.3 billion. Last year, there were $14.3 billion in net
withdrawals in the same period.
   So far this year, 37 institutions have been closed or, with
government assistance, merged into other S&Ls.
</TEXT>
