<HEAD>NASA Finalizes Accord on International Effort for Manned Space</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Station
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Aeronautics and Space
Administration has completed negotiations with Canada, Europe and
Japan for cooperation on the space station, which it called ``the
largest international scientific and technological venture ever
undertaken.''
   The United States will provide the overall space station
framework and operating subsystems, committing $16 billion, NASA
said in a statement Wednesday.
   Canada will spend $1 billion for a mobile servicing system;
Japan, $2 billion for an experiment module; and the European Space
Agency, $4.2 billion for a laboratory and an unmanned free-flying
platform.
   The current timetable calls for the station to be in orbit and
manned by late 1996.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bill Paves Way for Building Interstate Coal Pipeline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second House panel will consider legislation
designed to begin construction of an interstate coal pipeline now
that the House Interior Committee has approved the measure.
   The bill, approved 25-13 on Wednesday and sent to the House
Public Works and Transportation Committee, would grant a coal
pipeline company the power of eminent domain to enable it to
condemn land needed for the facility.
   The legislation, similar to a bill defeated by the House in
1983, is being pushed by coal companies as an alternative to what
they say are excessively high rates charged by railroads to haul
coal.
   Earlier this year, the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee approved a version of the bill, which is awaiting action
by the full Senate.
