<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO     06-09 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Europe To Be Main Topic For North Atlantic Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States plans to urge its Western
European allies to use economic assistance to Eastern Europe as a
lever to bring about political reforms in the Soviet satellites, a
U.S. official said.
   The 16 NATO foreign ministers meeting here today and Friday plan
to focus on the outlook for Eastern Europe in light of Mikhail S.
Gobachev's push for reforms in the Soviet Union.
   Lord Carrington, the NATO secretary-general, said the alliance
has a great interest in the new Soviet policy of political and
economic change ``and what effect it will have on us.''
   The Council of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization holds its
semiannual spring assembly in Madrid on Thursday and Friday.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
``Eastern Europe will be a testing ground for Gorbachev's
reforms.'' The official added that the United States will urge its
European allies not to aid Eastern European countries unless they
undertake substantial political reforms.
   The United States has been ``making the point all along that
economic reform is not going to work unless there is political
reform as well,'' the official said.
   The United States will be represented by Secretary of State
George P. Shultz; Alton Keel Jr, U.S. ambassador to NATO; and
Roseanne Ridgeway, the assistant secretary of state for European
affairs.
   No formal communique will be issued when the meeting ends
Friday, but Carrington said he would read a brief statement.
   East European nations in the Warsaw Pact, the Soviet bloc's
counterpart of NATO, are Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East Germany,
Hungary, Poland, Romania and the Soviet Union.
   Carrington said the NATO ministers would also discuss arms
control and how NATO members divide up the cost of Western defense.
That includes transferring 72 U.S. F-16 fighter-bombers from Spain
to Italy, acceding to a Spanish demand that the fighter wing leave
its soil.
   The Council's meeting in Madrid is the first in Spain since it
joined NATO in May 1982.
   Spain is not integrated into the NATO military command in
accordance with a March 1986 referendum in which Spaniards also
voted to remain in NATO only on condition that U.S. military
presence in Spain be substantially reduced.
   The American official said the United States planned to tell its
allies it feels it is carrying the financial burden of NATO's
defense.
   He said Congress will probably seek a reduction in the 325,000
U.S. troops stationed in Europe unless this burden is more
equitably distributed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
