<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Hepatitis     06-09 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Hepatitis,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Ministry Says Shanghai Hepatitis Epidemic Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-month epidemic of hepatitis in Shanghai
has ended after more than 300,000 people contracted the disease and
30 died, an official newspaper said today.
   The China Daily quoted a Public Health Ministry official as
saying the daily average incidence of hepatitis A in China's
largest city has returned to a normal level of about 90 cases.
   The 311,938 cases were recorded between Jan. 19 and May 26, the
official said, adding that the epidemic began to wane in late March
and April after patients were put in isolation and restrictions
were put on the production and sale of clams, believed to be the
cause of the outbreak.
   The report said the spread of hepatitis had also been brought
under control in neighboring Jiangsu Province, after afflicting
70,453 people through May 10.
   In March, health officials also announced that 122,000 people
were infected and 650 had died in an 18-month epidemic of non-A,
non-B type hepatitis in the western region of Xinjiang.
   Hepatitis is caused by a virus transmitted in food and water and
is characterized by nausea, vomiting and fever.
</TEXT>
