<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AbominableSnowman     06-09 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abominable Snowman,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeti Yet To Materialize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seven-week hunt for the Abominable Snowman in
the wilds of Tibet yielded strange footprints in the snow and the
remains of two skinned sheep but no proof that the mythical apeman
exists.
   A six-man expedition explored the 23,237-foot Menglungtse
summit, where British explorer Eric Shipton took his famous
photograph of a four-toed footprint in 1951.
   Since Shipton's photograph, there have been scores of alleged
sightings of a fearsome hairy beast, known both as Yeti and the
Abominable Snowman, with the characteristics of Neanderthal Man.
   But Chris Bonington, 53, leader of the expedition, told a news
conference Wednesday ``there's certainly not any conclusive
evidence one way or another'' that the legendary apeman exists.
   In a London radio interview, Bonington said the team's main
evidence consists of the skins of two mountain sheep known as
bharals that were found at 17,000 feet.
   The skins seemed to have been ripped cleanly off the sheep in a
manner inconsistent with any of its known predators.
   Bonington said Tibetans pass through the area where the skins
were found, but not at this time of year. In addition, the Tibetans
would have taken the skins because of their value, he said.
   He said one member of his team also found a ``very, very good,
very clearly distinct line of tracks that seemed to be of a biped.''
   The team is waiting for the film to be developed.
   Adding to the mystery was the sighting by British Broadcasting
Corp. film producer John Davidson of a dark figure at about 1,000
feet.
   ``My first impression was that it was probably a bear,''
Bonington said. But it didn't act like one.
   Finally, team members said they could not explain what happened
to ski poles that vanished after Andy Fanshawe, 25, and Alan
Hinkes, 34, buried them under a heavy pile of rocks.
   The team has turned over its evidence to London's Natural
History Museum for scientific tests.
</TEXT>
