<HEAD>Police Seeking Three More Red Army Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today stepped up a search for
at least three members of the Japanese Red Army terrorist group
after the deportation of another member suspected of plotting to
disrupt the Olympics.
   Hiroshi Sensui, 51, was deported Wednesday after his arrest at a
Manila clinic where he had undergone plastic surgery.
   Japanese officials said Sensui was serving a life sentence for
murder and robbery until he was freed in 1977 in exchange for
hostages aboard a Japan Air Lines jet hijacked in Bangladesh.
   Morishi Aoki, an official at the Japanese Embassy, said two
other members of the leftist terrorist group were believed living
in the Philippines. A third, Noruyo Zasaki, lives in Singapore but
regularly visits here, Aoki said.
   Immigration Commissioner Miriam Defensor-Santiago told foreign
reporters Wednesday that her department was redoubling its efforts
to track down Red Army members ``so we can make similiar arrests.''
   She said intelligence agencies believed Sensui and other Red
Army members were plotting attacks on the Olympics in Seoul, South
Korea, from a base in Manila.
   Another member, Osamu Maruoka, told police last November that
the Japanese Red Army had a ``sleeper agent'' in the Philippines,
police said.
   Police said Sensui entered the Philippines in 1984 under the
name Noboru Yamaguchi, married a Filipino woman and introduced
himself as a businessman.
   The couple lived in suburban Paranaque until last November, when
they moved to a hotel in Manila's Chinatown district. Police had
begun searching for Sensui but lost track of him until he surfaced
Tuesday in the Makati Medical Center.
