<HEAD>Rival Guerrilla Factions Clash In Beirut Camps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian guerrilla factions battled
each other in two Beirut refugee camps during the night, leaving
two dead and 10 wounded, police said today.
   Guerrillas from Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction, the main
component in the Palestine Liberation Organization, fought a
breakway Syrian-backed faction, the Fatah-Uprising led by Col.
Saeed Mousa, police reported.
   The two groups battled with howitzers, mortars, rocket-propelled
grenades and machine guns in the Bourj el-Barajneh and Chatilla
camps, police reported.
   Mousa's gunners deployed in mountains overlooking Beirut shelled
Arafat's followers with howitzers.
   The fighting ended at daybreak after a cease-fire worked out by
several Palestinian factions took effect.
   Mousa broke from the PLO in 1983 and set up his headquarters in
Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   Fatah and Mousa's faction have clashed repeatedly in recent
weeks, despite moves by Arafat, the PLO chairman, and Syrian
President Hafez Assad to reconcile after a five-year feud.
