<HEAD>Singer-Songwriter Laura Nyro Returns After 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman behind some of the biggest hits of the
Fifth Dimension, singer-songwriter Laura Nyro, is returning to the
concert stage after 10 years.
   Why?
   ``I quit smoking last summer,'' she told the Daily News. ``It
made my instrument very rich and stable. Also, whenever you quit
any addiction, your life is new again. You feel if you can free
yourself that way, you can do almost anything.''
   Nyro, 41, said her summer tour, which begins tonight in suburban
Rochester, is dedicated to the animal rights movement. She also
plans to record an album for Columbia Records to add to her others,
including ``Eli and the Thirteenth Confession,'' ``New York
Tendaberry'' and ``Gonna Take a Miracle.''
   Nyro was 17 years old when Peter, Paul and Mary popularized her
song, ``And When I Die.'' Other hits she has penned include
``Stoned Soul Picnic'' and ``Up, Up and Away,'' made famous by the
Fifth Dimension.
