<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     06-09 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Set Record High; Dollar Gains Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key indicator closed at
a record high today, and the U.S. dollar gained slightly against
the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues ended the day at
28,072.02, up 159.37 points or 0.57 percent, surpassing its
previous record close of 27,996.24 set Monday. On Wednesday, the
index slipped 54.67 points.
   ``The overnight surge on Wall Street gave Tokyo stocks a
boost,'' said a stock analyst with a major Tokyo securities house,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The New York Stock Exchange's Dow Jones industrial average rose
48.36 points to close at 2,102.95 Wednesday.
   It was the first time the Nikkei index has closed above the
28,000 mark.
   The analyst said apprehensions among some investors that the
market was rising too high promoted profit-taking that eased share
prices a little during the afternoon session.
   The Nikkei index ended the morning session at 28,148.77, its
highest level ever.
   Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 2.6
billion shares, up from 1.8 billion shares traded Wednesday. It was
the heaviest volume this year, and near the market's record of 2.83
billion shares set in March 1987.
   Prominent among gainers were steel stocks and issues related to
domestic demand, including real estate and construction. Textile,
non-ferrous metals and machineries lost ground.
   In the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
125.43 yen, up 0.11 yen from Wednesday's close. It opened the day
at 125.55 yen, but never moved higher, ranging between 125.40 and
125.55 yen.
   ``Trading was quiet and the dollar moved very little, with a
lack of incentives to direct the market,'' said a currency dealer
at a major commercial bank in Tokyo.
   Many participants sat out the day's trading, awaiting the
release of U.S. trade figures for April, due out next week, the
dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
