<HEAD>Man Charged With Manslaughter In Death Of Woman Scared By Jet Ski</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORCROSS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 36-year-old jet skier has been charged
with manslaughter in the death of a woman who officials say was
literally scared to death when he zoomed by within inches of her on
Lake Lanier.
   Barbara Reyes, 40, of Norcross, who had a history of heart
trouble, was floating on an inflatable raft during an outing the
weekend before Memorial Day when she died.
   Gwinnett County Police arrested Adrian Stanoiu, 36, of Norcross,
on a misdemeanor involuntary manslaughter charge Wednesday. If
convicted, Stanoiu could face a year in jail. He was released on
$550 bond.
   According to police, Mrs. Reyes was enjoying a Sunday outing
with her husband and some friends at Lanier Park Beach near Buford
when Stanoiu began riding a motorized jet ski close to shore, where
several people were swimming and Mrs. Reyes was rafting.
   Her husband, Fermin Reyes, told police the skier refused to
leave when he tried to warn him away. His wife panicked when the
skier came within 6 inches of her raft, and she began paddling
frantically toward shore.
   She collapsed in a few inches of water and died shortly
afterward. An autopsy revealed the cause of death to have been a
cardiac arrhythmia brought on by fright, said Coroner Randy Simpson.
