<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RoseService     06-09 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rose Service,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadway Honors Memory of Veteran Actor George Rose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two-time Tony winner George Rose, slain last
month at his Caribbean vacation home, was remembered by his friends
from the Broadway stage as a Renaissance figure, friend and teacher.
   Actress Betty Buckley, a co-star of Rose in ``The Mystery of
Edwin Drood,'' moved many in the audience to tears when she sang
``They Can't Take That Away from Me'' at Wednesday's service at the
Shubert Theater.
   ``It reminds me of George, a time when things were gentler, more
elegant,'' she said in explaining her choice. ``George Rose was a
teacher of mine. He was the epitome of elegance and high standards.
I can only aspire to his standards.''
   Producer Joseph Papp, who worked with Rose on ``Drood,'' called
him ``a Renaissance figure, and it was all presented on the stage.''
   Rose won his second Tony for his role as the chairman in
``Drood''; his first was as Eliza Doolittle's father in a revival
of ``My Fair Lady.''
   Judy Kaye, who won a Tony on Sunday for ``The Phantom of the
Opera,'' called Rose ``one of the best actors who ever walked the
planet.''
   Others who appeared to sing or just reminisce included Jack
Gilford; Rupert Holmes, who composed ``Drood''; Maureen McGovern,
who played Rose's daughter for a year in ``The Pirates of
Penzance''; and Howard McGillan, who was in ``Drood'' and now is in
``Anything Goes.''
   Rose, 68, was born in England but lived since 1961 in New York,
nearly always working on Broadway. He was killed May 4 by his
adopted son and three people in the Dominican Republic, authorities
there said.
</TEXT>
