<HEAD>Iraq Claims Planes Hit Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with x grafs to UPDATE with Iran claiming it shot down
jet. PICKS up 5th graf, `It did ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said today its warplanes hit a ship
off Iran's Persian Gulf coast during the night, and Iran said its
interceptors shot down an Iraqi jet in a dogfight over the waterway.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said one civilian was killed and six wounded when Iraq
planes bombed a village near Sardasht in northwestern Azerbaijan
province Wednesday.
   The agency said the French-built Iraqi Mirage F-1 was shot down
and exploded over the gulf.
   There was no confirmation from Baghdad. But the official Iraqi
News Agency reported that Iraqi helicopter gunships shot down an
Iranian Bell 214 helicopter today over the northern sector of the
gulf war battlefront.
   Baghdad Radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a military
communique as saying Iraq fighter-bombers carried out the
``accurate and effective'' shipping raid Wednesday night.
   It did not identify the vessel and there was no immediate
independent confirmation of the attack from shipping sources.
   The official radio said the attack was carried out as part of
Iraq's campaign to choke off Iran's vital oil exports on which
Tehran depends to bankroll its war effort.
   The two countries have been at war for nearly eight years.
   The Iraqis claimed to have hit another ship in the tanker
holding area near Iran's Kharg Island oil terminal June 4. But
there has been no independent confirmation of that attack either.
   The last confirmed Iraqi air strike against shipping in the gulf
was May 16 when fighter-bombers attacked the 112,445-ton Iranian
tanker Bisoton.
   The Bisoton was formerly the Norwegian-owned Mia Margrethe,
which was hit by two Iranian gunboats in the southern gulf last
June 26 and set on fire.
   About 500 merchant ships have been attacked by both sides in the
so-called ``tanker war'' that began in early 1984. More than 300
seamen have been killed.
