<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica     06-09 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks Return to Work After Anti-Apartheid Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks returned to work and
school today after more than 2 million stayed away for three days
to protest curbs on anti-apartheid activity and legislative
proposals to limit the right to strike.
   Organizers called the nation's longest and largest general
strike a success, and the white minority government's manpower
minister said he might delay action on the proposed labor
legislation.
   Employers estimated that the strike cost the economy $250
million.
   Downtown Johannesburg, which had been relatively deserted, was
bustling again. For the first time this week, fleets of mini-bus
taxis arrived carrying workers from the huge black township of
Soweto.
   In Durban, the port city where the strike was most effective,
transport companies said ridership on commuter trains and buses
remained 20 percent below normal. Officials suggested some blacks
feared it was unsafe to return to work because commuter buses had
been stoned and firebombed during the strike.
   Police said three men were stabbed to death by other blacks
during the night at Riverview in Natal province. There was an
unconfirmed report that a fourth man was killed there today when a
mine in his possession exploded.
   Eight other killings were reported earlier this week in Natal,
where groups supporting and opposing the protest clashed. Two
people were killed in unrest elsewhere during the strike.
   Black labor federations, backed by prominent clergymen,
organized the strike to protest restrictions put on anti-apartheid
groups Feb. 24 and proposed legislation that would limit the right
of unions to strike.
   Today's editions of the financial newspaper Business Day quoted
Manpower Minister Pieter du Plessis as saying he planned to send a
formal invitation to black labor leaders to meet with him.
   Du Plessis also offered to suspend action on certain clauses of
the labor bill if the unions could convince him this was warranted,
Business Day said.
   To anti-apartheid activists, the protest was a success because
it took place without overt help from the restricted opposition
groups.
   ``The stayaway is an indication of the determination of the
people to oppose the apartheid government,'' said the Rev. Frank
Chikane, general secretary of the South African Council of
Churches. ``It means the February restrictions have not suppressed
the spirit of resistance.''
   Security forces maintained a relatively low profile during the
protest and government officials made virtually no public
statements about it, but employers threatened to reduce work forces
and move toward mechanization if political strikes continue.
   Black miners virtually ignored the strike and kept the nation's
most lucrative industry operating almost normally despite support
for the protest by the National Union of Mineworkers leadership.
   Mining produces 80 percent of South Africa's export earnings.
   Including the near-total boycott of urban black schools, the
number of participants each day appeared to have exceeded 2 million
_ the number of people who stayed home June 16, 1986 to protest the
nationwide state of emergency imposed four days earlier.
   President P.W. Botha declared the emergency to combat a black
uprising against apartheid, the racial policy that preserves power
for South Africa's 5 million whites and denies the 26 million
blacks a voice in national affairs.
   It is expected to be renewed this week for a third year. The
state of emergency gives police sweeping powers of detention
without trial, imposes press restrictions and outlaws several forms
of peaceful protest.
   Police told news media this week it was illegal under emergency
regulations to report on the extent of a general strike.
   Such reports were carried by pro-government newspapers and the
state-run broadcasting company, along with other media, but many
accounts were worded cautiously and avoided positive assessments of
the strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0526 06-09 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0526,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabs Shut Down Occupied Lands in General Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, `An 18-year-old ...,' to
UPDATE with report of rubber bullet injuries. PICKS up 5th graf,
`An Israeli ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians today shut down the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip with a general strike to mark six months of
rebellion. Hospital officials said Israeli soldiers shot and killed
a 17-year-old Arab in a clash.
   Meanwhile, Israeli physicians accused the army of causing
paralyzing injuries by using powerful high-speed bullets to
disperse demonstrators.
   Seventeen-year-old Ahmed Hassan Hawari died after he was shot in
the head during a confrontation with troops in Sebastiya, near
Nablus in the West Bank, said officials at Ittihad hospital in
Nablus.
   An 18-year-old youth and a 12-year-old girl were shot and
wounded when soldiers fired at protesters in the West Bank town of
Tulkarem, officials at the Tulkarem and Nablus hospitals said. Both
were shot in the legs.
   Another seven Tulkarem residents were treated for cuts inflicted
by rubber bullets, the hospital official said.
   An Israeli military spokesman said the army was checking the
reports.
   Since the anti-occupation unrest began Dec. 8 in the lands
Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East war, 203 Palestinians and two
Israelis have been killed. More than 5,000 Arabs have been wounded
or injured and 5,000 are in jail.
   Underground leaders of the Palestine Liberation Organization
ordered today's general strike. Stores were closed, workers stayed
home, public transportation was paralyzed and many children stayed
home from school.
   Men with kafiyeh headresses wrapped around their faces went into
schools in the West Bank and encouraged children to leave classes
and demonstrate, Israeli army radio said.
   An underground leaflet calling for the general strike urged
children to stay out of schools, which have opened in recent weeks
after a four-month shutdown ordered by Israeli military authorities.
   The army clamped curfews on about 110,000 Palestinians in
villages or refugee camps. They included the Jabaliya refugee camp
in Gaza, which has been under curfew for a week, and the West Bank
village of Janiya and Beit Ur Et Tahta, where attackers hurled
firebombs at two Israeli vehicles overnight.
   Two army officers suffered minor injuries when their jeep was
hit by a firebomb and set ablaze in Janiya, the army said.
   Six Israeli doctors said in a report on military action in the
Gaza Strip that the army should not disperse protesters with
high-velocity bullets of the type used in the M-16 automatic rifle.
   The report said such bullets produced 13 paraplegics and two
quadaplegics and caused 20 cases of serious internal injuries.
   It also accused the army of misusing tear gas by firing into
enclosed areas, failing to keep proper records of injuries and
failing to carry out autopsies in unexplained deaths.
   In some cases, the army transferred seriously injured people to
Israeli hospitals to interrogate them, thereby exposing them to
increased risk, the report charged.
   A military spokesman denied most of the charges in the medical
report and said the army never gives out information about the
types of ammunition it uses.
   ``Transfer to hospitals in Israel is done solely in order to
give the patient better treatment that is not available in Gaza
hospitals,'' the spokesman said on condition of anonymity. ``It is
done for only humanitarian reasons.''
   He said the army frequently does not conduct autopsies because
Arab families oppose them and regularly take away and bury the
bodies of relatives before autopsies can be performed.
   The team of doctors, organized by left-wing Parliament member
Dedi Zucker, said it could not determine whether tear gas causes
miscarriages. Palestinian women have charged they suffered
miscarriages after being exposed to tear gas in enclosed spaces.
   The physicians did report that a 35-year-old pregnant woman's
fetus died after troops twice accidentally fired tear gas into her
home.
   Two elderly women suffered a heart attack and a paralyzing
stroke after being exposed to tear gas in a closed area, the report
said.
   ``We deny altogether that the army uses tear gas incorrectly or
that it causes miscarriage,'' said the army spokesman, who said the
tear gas was tested for side effects. But he said ``there may be
specific cases where for example tear gas penetrate a home by
accident.''
   The report, described as a preliminary study, was based on
interviews with Arab physicians and medical officers for the army's
administration in the Gaza Strip.
</TEXT>
