<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-09 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in moderate European trading
early today. Gold bullion fell.
   The dollar benefited from statements Wednesday by central
bankers meeting in Chicago indicating support for stabilizing the
currency.
   Profit-taking put some pressure on the dollar in the first hours
of European trading today, but it was holding steady at generally
higher levels.
   Traders said they did not expect any big currency swings, given
market uncertainty over next Tuesday's report on the U.S. trade
deficit in April.
   Here are selected midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared
with late Wednesday:
   _1.7219 West German marks, up from 1.7183
   _1.4370 Swiss francs, up from 1.4350
   _5.8105 French francs, up from 5.7923
   _1.9336 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9250
   _1,279.20 Italian lire, up from 1,273.50
   _1.2225 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2220
   The dollar rose against the British pound, which slipped to
$1.8120 from Wednesday's $1.8175.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 125.43 Japanese yen, marginally
up from 125.32 yen on Wednesday. In London trading later today, the
dollar fetched 125.30 yen.
   London's main bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $455 a troy ounce, down from $458 late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold traded at a bid of $454.90, down from $458.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $456.59, down
from $458.98.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $7 a troy ounce,
down from $7.15.
