<1ST_LINE>r a PM-O'HareInvestigation     06-09 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O'Hare Investigation,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Inspectors Launch Probe of O'Hare Controller Errors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three mistakes in two days by air traffic
controllers at O'Hare International Airport prompted federal safety
officials to begin an investigation of the system for directing
planes in the area, officials said.
   Officials at the National Transportation Safety Board were
alarmed because controllers made two errors Monday and one Tuesday,
raising to 20 the number of mistakes they've made at the nation's
second busiest airport this year, said Mike Benson, an agency
spokesman.
   ``The significant increase in operational errors, from 12 in all
of last year to 20 already this year, set off concern for us,''
Benson said Wednesday.
   Benson said four investigators would arrive in Chicago, possibly
today. Their investigation initially will focus on controllers in
O'Hare's radar room, where most of the mistakes have been made,
Benson said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration plans to send three safety
specialists to assist and ``allow the FAA to take immediate action
if any discrepancies are uncovered,'' FAA Administrator T. Allan
McArtor said.
   The FAA also said it has assigned eight additional air-traffic
controllers to help overworked controllers at O'Hare during the
busy summer season, The Washington Post reported today.
   Controllers in the radar room are in charge of routing air
traffic in a 30-mile radius of O'Hare, while controllers in the
tower primarily direct landings and takeoffs, Benson said.
   Last year, controllers in O'Hare's radar room made nine of the
12 operational errors, he said. This year, the radar room has been
responsible for 15 of the 20 mistakes, including the three this
week, Benson said.
   Monday's first error involved a United Airlines jetliner bound
for Ontario, Calif., and a Lear jet, Benson said.
   After take-off, radar records showed that the Boeing 727,
carrying 128 passengers, came within 1,200 feet of the other plane,
said Dan Sheehy, a United spokesman.
   Such incidents are not classified as near-collisions unless the
aircraft come within less than 500 feet of each other.
   Sheehy said the United pilot did not file a near-collision
report, but the company was investigating the incident.
   ``Our captain did not take any evasive action because there was
no reason to _ there was enough separation between the planes,''
Sheehy said.
   But the pilot of the Lear Jet filed a near-collision report,
said agency spokesman Mort Edelstein.
   Later Monday, radar room controllers were blamed for an error
involving United Flight 608, a Boeing 727 bound for Washington, and
a Cessna 172 airplane, said Sheehy and Benson.
   Tuesday's error involved an American Airlines DC-10 and a Midway
Airlines Boeing 737, Benson said. He said he could provide no other
details.
   The NTSB team will begin by investigating the three errors and
then interview the controllers involved in this year's other
mistakes, he said.
   Then they will interview a cross-section of controllers and
examine programs that influence their job performance, such as
training, quality assurance and amount of overtime worked.
   The National Air Traffic Controllers Association, based in
Washington, said O'Hare, like other airports nationwide, is plagued
by short staffing and overworked controllers.
   ``We would welcome any type of outside oversight right now,''
said John Thornton, the group's national coordinator. ``Around the
country we're seeing short staffs, equipment problems and sometimes
an insensitivity on the part of the FAA to resolve these problems.''
   During the past several years, the FAA's air-traffic control
operations at O'Hare have been scrutinized by the safety board and
Congess because of the airport's congested skies and a shortage of
fully trained controllers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
