<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Motown     06-09 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Motown,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MCA, Investment Group Reportedly Will Buy Motown Records for $61
Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motown Records, which exploded onto the music
scene 20 years ago with a string of hits by Smokey Robinson, the
Supremes and others, is about to be sold for $61 million, a
newspaper reported today.
   A tentative agreement calls for MCA to pay 20 percent of the
purchase price, with the investment group Boston Ventures Limited
Partnership putting up the balance, according to the Los Angeles
Times.
   MCA would retain distribution rights to Motown's recordings for
10 years, the newspaper said.
   Motown, founded by auto worker-turned-songwriter Berry Gordy Jr.
in Detroit, is of the most prestigious record labels in the music
industry but has had less success in recent years.
   Motown introduced such black artists to the music world as
Robinson, the Supremes, Stevie Wonder, Marvin Gaye, the
Temptations, Gladys Knight and the Pips and the Jackson 5, which
featured Michael Jackson.
   In 1966, Motown had 22 Top-20 hits, but stars like Jackson and
Diana Ross, originally with the Supremes, have since moved on.
   The company, which moved to Los Angeles in 1971, had only two
gold albums _ at least 500,000 copies sold _ in 1987. In the latest
Billboard magazine, only one Motown album is ranked in the Top 200,
Wonder's ``Characters, in 125th place.
   Not included in the proposed sale are Motown's music publisher,
Jobete Music, which owns the rights to nearly all of the company's
hit records, and Motown Productions, a TV and film production unit.
   MCA nearly bought Motown early in 1987, but the deal fell
through. Gordy reportedly changed his mind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
