<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Kidnap,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Freed After Six Months As Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REGGIO DI CALABRIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers freed a 30-year-old
building contractor they had held for six months after his family
paid a ransom of $2.4 million, Italian news agencies reported today.
   Oreste Villa was released late Wednesday, police said. He had
been held in tiny tents and cabins in the Aspromonte mountains of
southern Italy.
   Villa was kidnapped Nov. 24 while driving to his home near Como
in northern Italy's Lombardy region. Police said he was taken by
truck to the Calabria peninsula, at the toe of the Italian boot.
   Villa's father, Arialdo Villa, was quoted by the ANSA news
agency as saying that his son was held in six or seven different
hideouts, always small huts or tents. ANSA said Villa told police
that he had one foot chained to a post at all times.
   Villa was reported exhausted but in fair condition. He was
staying at a hotel with his father before returning to Como.
   ``The only problem is that his legs hurt from the cold of the
long months and long walks in the snow,'' his father was quoted as
saying.
   Police said Villa was released near Santa Cristina d'Aspromonte,
a small mountain town about 50 miles outside the provincial capital
Reggio di Calabria. He walked for several hours before coming upon
a police patrol.
   Police began a massive search for the captors, whose identities
and exact number were not immediately known.
</TEXT>
