<2ND_LINE>PM-Elementary Rape,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3 Miami Beach Fifth-Graders Accused Of Raping Classmates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three fifth-graders accused of raping
other boys in the school bathroom told police they were mimicking
things they had seen on cable television, authorities said.
   The three boys, ages 10, 11 and 12, were arrested Wednesday on
one count of each of sexual battery.
   ``They indicated they saw risque movies late at night on
cable,'' said police Sgt. James Mazer.
   The boys and the alleged victims are in the same class at Ida M.
Fisher Elementary School. Principal Paulette Martin alerted police
about the alleged attacks, which occurred during school hours
between January and April, Mazer said.
   ``We're talking perhaps six to nine victims, but we're really
not sure yet,'' said police spokesman Tom Hoolahan. ``We do know
that the victims are isolated within one group within the school.''
   The three alleged offenders were ``older looking and stronger''
and apparently coerced their victims, Mazer said. The three acted
as a group and also individually, he said.
   ``We get victims as young as three months, but I don't remember
ever hearing of such young offenders,'' said Mazer.
   The two older boys have been placed in state custody, although
the 11-year-old already was under state custody for unrelated
battery charges, Mazer said. The youngest of the accused was
released to his parents' custody.
   ``I'm shocked because my son goes to that school,'' Victoria
Hernandez said. ``My son is only 8 years old and I'm afraid now for
him and for all the children there in the school. It's terrible.''
   ``They're not doing their job,'' said another parent, Victoria
Gomez. ``They're not watching the children the way they should be
watched.''
   James Fleming, assistant superintendent of Dade County schools,
said the school had the same security other public schools have.
</TEXT>
