<2ND_LINE>PM-Kiss and Ride,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Munich Testing Kissing Zone to Prevent Traffic Jams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bavarian capital of Munich has
set up a ``Kiss and Ride'' zone near a busy subway station to
prevent parting couples from causing traffic jams, a city offical
said today.
   The head of Munich's public transport system, Dieter Lippert,
said a ``test Kiss and Ride area'' has been set up near the Olympic
Stadium Center subway station, where men and women often drop off
their partners to catch the subway to work.
   ``The kissing especially held up rush-hour traffic ... and cars
often barely avoided accidents because of it,'' Lippert told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview.
   Lippert, who heads the city's subway, bus and streetcar system,
said that a side strip of road near the station is being clearly
marked with signs for ``Kiss and Ride'' passengers.
   If the test proves successful, more such zones may be set up
along busy Munich streets where couples drop off their partners, he
said.
   ``I don't think they'll turn into necking zones,'' Lippert said.
``The drivers usually don't get that carried away.''
