<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amish-Photographs     06-09 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amish-Photographs,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Amish Inmate Photographed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amish convict must submit to an ID
photograph despite objections on religious grounds, a federal
appeals court has ruled.
   The 8th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals on Wednesday upheld a
lower court ruling in the case of Andy Slabaugh of Canton, Minn.,
who was charged in 1986 with offering an IRS agent a $500 bribe.
   Federal marshals were required to photograph him at the time of
prisoner processing.
   Slabaugh, however, cited the biblical commandment against the
making of graven images and argued that his appearance was
distinctive enough to make a photo unnecessary _ he has one arm and
wears a long beard and plain Amish dress.
   The picture-taking was delayed until the court could hold a
hearing. Before the hearing could be held, he pleaded guilty and
was placed on three years' probation.
   A U.S. District Court later ruled that the government had a
compelling public-safety interest that overrode Slabaugh's right to
free exercise of religion.
   The appeals court affirmed the ruling but said that because
Slabaugh had pleaded guilty, the lower court needed only to find
that the photograph had a ``reasonable relationship'' to the
purposes of the probation law.
   Scott Tilsen, a public defender who represented Slabaugh, said
he will appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
