<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSEducation 1stLd-Writethru a0434 06-09 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Education, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0434,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Education Efforts Stymied By Bureaucracy, Congress Told</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 9 grafs on AIDS hotline calls; picks up 3rd graf,
Regrettably, perhaps.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal health official said today that
national distribution of a pamphlet on AIDS has dramatically
increased calls to AIDS hotlines, but he acknowledged that not all
of them are giving callers the same answers.
   Dr. James Mason, director of the Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta, said calls on the centers' Spanish-language hotline have
risen from about 20 a day before May 26, when the mass mailing
began, to almost 6,000 a day now.
   One day last week, there were 17,000 calls on all the centers'
hotlines, compared to about 6,000 a day before the mailing to 107
million U.S. households, he said.
   Meanwhile, a congressional report released Wednesday said
``substantial misconceptions'' remain about AIDS, and witnesses
told a panel that efforts to educate the public are often bogged
down in red tape.
   Mason, interviewed on ``CBS This Morning,'' said it is
understandable that callers to the ``literally hundreds'' of
hotlines around the country are getting different answers on some
aspects of the disease.
   ``We need to do everything we can to standardize those answers,
and we're doing that, but that you're getting a few different
answers is not really surprising,'' Mason said.
   He said the CDC has put out a list of 30 standard questions and
answers about the disease, but it does not cover every conceivable
situation that callers might raise.
   Mason said hotlines run by state health agencies and most
community hotlines are reliable. But if callers ``want to be
sure,'' he said, they should call federal or state government
hotlines.
   A Philadelphia city official, testifying before Congress, said
bureaucracy has become ``a major enemy'' of cities trying to fight
the AIDS epidemic, and singer Dionne Warwick said the AIDS
information pamphlet distributed by the federal government to every
household is no panacea.
   ``Regrettably, perhaps the most important people that we need to
reach to stem the spread did not receive these brochures, or if
they did, simply ignored them and never read them,'' Miss Warwick
told the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee at a hearing
Wednesday.
   Miss Warwick has begun a foundation to award grants to community
groups for AIDS education programs, especially those targeted at
minorities that are disproportionately affected by the disease.
   A study released at the hearing by the congressional Office of
Technology Assessment found that ``the general population continues
to hold substantial misconceptions'' about how the AIDS virus is
transmitted.
   These include believing one can become infected by donating
blood or by working near someone with the virus, the study said.
   Still, OTA said education through the mass media can change
behavior, as shown in campaigns to stop people from smoking. The
agency also noted that ``dramatic behavioral change has occurred
among homosexual males in response to the AIDS epidemic.''
   David Fair, executive assistant to the health commissioner for
AIDS programs in Philadelphia, told the panel that three AIDS
testing and counseling centers have not yet opened because $800,000
in federal money the city expected to receive last September has
become entangled in bureaucracy.
   The problem, he said, lies in Philadelphia's reliance on the
state government, which distributes the federal money to cities.
   ``They hold up, they play that kind of politics even though it's
an AIDS situation?'' committee chairman John Glenn, D-Ohio, asked.
   ``Absolutely,'' Fair replied. ``The reference that I use when
talking to state legislators is that AIDS is not a weatherization
project. They need to treat it a little bit differently.''
   Asked by Glenn whether the Pennsylvania case was common, Alan
Hinman of the federal Center for Prevention Services, said, ``Not
every state has problems getting funds out, but there are problems,
yes.''
   Gary Noble, deputy director for AIDS at the federal Centers for
Disease Control, said the agency is re-examining the criteria for
distributing money to large cities, where acquired immune
deficiency syndrome is most prevalent.
   CDC staff levels present another problem, Michael Zimmerman of
the General Accounting Office said.
   The staff assigned by CDC to manage its AIDS education efforts
``appears to be insufficient to monitor state and local health
departments and advise them on how to develop and operate effective
AIDS education programs,'' he said.
   AIDS, a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune
system, is spread most often through sexual contact, needles shared
by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from
infected pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
