<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FraternitySuspension     06-09 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fraternity Suspension,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Orders 3-Year Suspension After Member Seriously Burned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VALPARAISO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Valparaiso University fraternity has
been suspended for at least three years for a ritual May 16 in
which a senior was burned in a hot mixture of peanut butter and
excrement.
   University President Robert V. Schnabel, in a statement
Wednesday withdrawing campus recognition from Sigma Phi Epsilon,
called the matter a ``deplorable and unfortunate incident.''
   Steven R. Jenny, 23, was stripped of his clothes and four
gallons of peanut butter, urine and feces were poured on him in a
fraternity ritual known as lavaliering.
   The senior suffered burns on his back, buttocks, abdomen and
groin. He was hospitalized for two days but refused to press
charges against the 30 or so people involved in the incident in the
fraternity house parking lot.
   The ritual is performed when a fraternity member gives a
lavalier, or necklace, to a woman.
   During the suspension, the fraternity house may be kept open for
seniors, but they cannot hold fraternity activities and the group's
sign will be removed from the house, said Daryll Hersemann, vice
president of student affairs.
   ``The university has determined that its regulations have been
broken and that the moral and ethical standards and agreements
which it expects all members of its community to adhere to have
been seriously violated,'' Schnabel said.
   Students at the university have gone home for the summer.
Fraternity president Glen Mutscher could not be reached for comment
about the suspension.
   David Gring, whose term as chapter president ended in December,
said he was left ``speechless'' by the penalty. ``I didn't think it
would be three years. I don't know how the rest of the alumni will
react,'' he said.
</TEXT>
