<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presbyterians     06-09 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presbyterians,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Will Consider Proposal for National Health Standard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Society and individuals alike have a moral
obligation to promote good health, and the government should
establish a ``national health standard,'' says a proposed policy
before the nation's largest Presbyterian group.
   The report on health costs and policies was one of a number of
papers on the agenda today as 630 delegates to the annual meeting
of the 3-million-member Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) began two days
of committee meetings.
   Central America, denominational finances, pornography and
political and social involvement also will be discussed in meetings
through Saturday, when the delegates, or commissioners, assemble to
act on committee recommendations.
   On Wednesday, the first full day of the 200th General Assembly,
the Rev. C. Kenneth Hall, 63, was elected moderator, or chief
spokesman, of the denomination. Hall, pastor of the 640-member Hill
United Presbyterian Church in Butler, Pa., defeated four other
candidates on the first ballot.
   Health care is a ``crisis of economics with serious moral
import,'' according to the paper prepared by the church's Advisory
Council on Church and Society.
   ``We are killing ourselves needlessly with substance abuse,
highway accidents, violence and suicide,'' the paper says, ``and
our health is undermined and continually threatened by pollution of
our environment by chemical toxins, nuclear and industrial waste,
and ocean dumping of garbage.''
   The paper calls on Congress to define by 1990 a National Health
Standard of ``adequate, quality health care, including prevention
and health promotion; acute care; chronic care; long-term
institutional care; rehabilitive care, and care for catastrophic
illness.''
   Congress should then require all employers, public and private,
to provide their employees and their dependents with insurance that
meets the standard, the paper says.
   The paper says individuals have ``a public and private duty to
value and care for his or her own health and the health of the
community.''
   Hall said his unusual first-ballot win reflected delegates'
concern over the loss of 300,000 members since 1983, when the
denomination was formed by merging the United Presbyterian Church
in the United States of America and the Presbyterian Church in the
United States, the Southern stream.
   He said his victory gave him a mandate to concentrate on
evangelism and healing. Hall selected 50-year-old Ruth Montoya of
Arvada, Colo., as vice moderator.
</TEXT>
