<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PassthePlatter     06-09 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pass the Platter,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restaurant to Stop Re-serving Food to Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKENMUTH, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a restaurant are having
a food fight with the Health Department over when, exactly,
leftovers become leftovers.
   Saginaw County health officials have ordered the Bavarian Inn to
stop serving food left on its platters to employees.
   ``As of (Tuesday), everything is going down the drain like they
say it has to,'' said Don Keller, the restaurant's marketing and
sales director. The restaurant faced revocation of its license if
it didn't comply.
   The owners admitted to health inspectors during an inspection in
April that they re-served food to employees, a violation of state
law, officials said.
   Keller said the law is not properly written for family-style
restaurants such as the Bavarian Inn where food is served on
platters that diners pass around the table.
   ``We agree it would be revolting to take food off someone else's
plate,'' Keller said. ``But we are saying it isn't served until it
goes on the customer's plate. The health department is saying, once
it leaves the kitchen, it is served.''
   ``We are quietly trying to figure out some way this good food
can be used again,'' Keller said.
</TEXT>
