<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hutton-Broker     06-09 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hutton-Broker,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broker Pleads Guilty To Hutton Money Laundering Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former E.F. Hutton broker has pleaded
guilty to taking part in a money-laundering scheme at the firm's
local branch.
   Brain J. Lareau, 46, of Jamestown pleaded guilty Wednesday to
violating the Social Security Act and money-laundering. Lareau, who
worked at the branch from 1980 to 1985, admitted laundering
$183,950 from August 1982 to October 1984.
   Lareau, and another former broker, Stephen S. Fusco, who has
since died, helped clients hide about $1.5 million in cash from the
Internal Revenue Service and Securities Exchange Commission,
according to authorities.
   According to court documents, Lareau created a fictitious
account with a fake Social Security number and used it to conceal a
customer's money. Fusco was accused of helping organized crime
figures launder illegal profits.
   Lareau could receive up to six years in prison and $6,000 in
fines at sentencing July 22. Under a plea bargain, prosecutors will
recommend no more than six months in prison.
   E.F. Hutton & Co. Inc. pleaded guilty May 16 to money-laundering
and conspiracy and was fined $1.01 million, the largest fine ever
imposed in a money-laundering case.
   Hutton was acquired last year by Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc.
The company now is known as Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
</TEXT>
