statement about space aliens and the CIA during a live broadcast
has been placed on three years' probation.
   Gary Stollman, 34, pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor count of
false imprisonment in the Aug. 19 incident. A felony charge was
dismissed. He was sentenced Tuesday by Los Angeles County Superior
Court Judge Jack B. Tso.
   KNBC went off the air soon after Stollman walked on to the set
in Burbank and ordered Horowitz to read a statement. The consumer
reporter was shaken but unhurt during the incident seen by
thousands of viewers.
   ``I didn't think it would benefit anyone to put Gary in the
general prison population,'' Horowitz said of the sentence. ``I'm
satisfied that Gary will get the treatment he needs.''
   ``The positive side of te Gary Stollman case is that for three
years I was standing on a soap box screaming about lookalike toy
guns,'' Horowitz said. ``What Gary Stollman did was focus attention
on an issue that would have gotten no attention if this hadn't
happened.''
   Since the episode, he noted, several cities and states,
including California, have moved to ban toy guns
   Stollman's father, Max Stollman, is a former reporter for KNBC.
