<2ND_LINE>PM-Wright-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Asks Ethics Committee For Chance To Appear</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 3 grafs new with Wright quote. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, The
committee.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright said today he is
``supremely confident'' allegations against him will be put to rest
once the House ethics committee hears his answer to charges he
violated conflict-of-interest rules through a book contract and
lobbying for oil companies.
   Wright, D-Texas, said he was filing a brief with the committee
today and was preparing a narrative to release to the public, but
he had not yet been asked to appear before the panel.
   ``I am supremely confident, when all of it is seen out on the
table in the sunlight it will be abolutely clear to everyone'' that
no rules were violated, Wright told reporters.
   The committee today holds its second meeting to review the case
against Wright and set the scope of its inquiry. Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., who filed the complaint against Wright, has also
asked the panel to hire an independent counsel for the probe.
   Gingrich, a political foe of the speaker, charged that Wright
had a financial stake when he lobbied U.S. and foreign officials on
behalf of oil companies, and when he accepted an unusually
lucrative royalty contract from a friend and campaign contractor
who published his last book.
   Common Cause, a non-profit group which pushes for tighter
government ethics standards, also has called for an ethics
investigation.
   ``I believe I can put all the allegations to rest,'' said
Wright. ``If the committee will give priority into looking at each
and every (charge) .... it will discover I have violated no rule
and certainly violated no commonly accepted ethical standard.''
   ``I would like for it to be done at the earliest possible
time,'' he said. However, the ethics committee had not yet asked
him to appear, he said.
   Wright, chairman of next month's Democratic National Convention,
was asked if the party was concerned that his troubles might hurt
chances of regaining the White House in the fall.
   ``I haven't heard that concern expressed,'' he said, adding that
anyone who was so concerned should come and see him. The speaker
and other Democratic leaders have said Wright is a victim of a GOP
effort to distract attention from ethical lapses in the Reagan
administration.
   Privately, Wright's aides said they were frustrated with the
slow pace of the ethics committee probe.
   The committee held its first meeting on the case a week ago.
   Since that meeting, it has been reported that Wright's book, a
collection of his stories and sayings, was completed with the help
of one of his Capitol Hill staff, who took a taxpayer-financed trip
to Texas to do some of the work.
   Gingrich subsequently conceded that one of his aides helped him
with a book.
   Wright is working on another book with help from one of his
assistants, but the aide says this work is being done in his spare
time.
   The ethics committee, officially called the Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, is the only House panel with equal
representation of the two parties, with six Democrats and six
Republicans.
</TEXT>
