<HEAD>Costa Rican President Cautions Against Military Move To Oust
Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias said today that
Central American leaders oppose the use of military force to oust
Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``My conviction is that only through persuasion'' can Noreiga be
removed, Arias said at the Statehouse after a meeting with Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis, the likely Democratic presidential nominee.
   Noriega, under indictment in the United States on drug charges,
has held on to power in the Panama despite U.S. sanctions and
protests at home.
   ``I don't think any Latin American country would be in favor of
a military solution, of military pressure, of economic sanctions,''
said Arias, who won the Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts to bring
peace to Central America.
   ``They hurt the Panamanian people, not necessarily the
government. ... We must reach a diplomatic solution and we would
never be in favor of military pressure.''
   Arias met with Dukakis before attending the Harvard University
commencement, at which he was to deliver a speech and receive an
honorary degree.
   ``Twenty-nine years ago I tried to get into Harvard and I wasn't
accepted. Now they are giving me an honorary degree,'' Arias joked.
