<HEAD>Reagan May Hold News Conference in Toronto June 21</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will deliver a speech and
probably hold a news conference in Toronto on June 21 following the
close of the annual, seven-nation economic summit, it was announced
today.
   Reagan will fly to Toronto on June 19 for three days of talks
with the leaders of Canada, Britain, France, West Germany, Italy
and Japan.
   At the close of the meetings on June 21, the president probably
will hold a news conference, as he has in the past, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   In addition, Reagan will address a joint dinner of the Empire
Club and the Canadian Club, which Fitzwater described as being
dedicated to the free flow of ideas between the United States and
Canada. Fitzwater said Reagan will return to Washington late in the
evening.
   To set the stage for the summit, Reagan will deliver a speech on
Monday at the State Department before an audience of the Atlantic
Council.
