<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Strike     06-09 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Strike,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Calls Strike To Protest Religion Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition groups announced an
eight-hour nationwide strike for Sunday to a law making Islam the
state religion of Bangladesh.
   In separate announcements late Wednesday, the three major
political opposition alliances and the fundamentalist
Jamaat-e-Islami called for the general strike to protest the
measure, which opponents fear will lead to imposition of harsh
Islamic law.
   The eight-party alliance led by Sheik Hasina also said it would
hold a rally against the law Saturday in Dhaka, and the seven-party
coalition headed by Khaleda Zia is conducting a weeklong protest
against the measure.
   Parliament passed the bill Tuesday by a 254-0 vote after 15
opposition lawmakers walked out in protest. President Hussain
Muhammad Ershad's Jatiya Party holds 252 seats in the 300-member
assembly and was joined by two independents.
   Within minutes of the passage, thousands of people took to the
streets of the capital to protest the bill.
   Since then, at least 30 people have been injured in clashes with
police and 25 people arrested. Demonstrators also have damaged
about 35 vehicles, most of them state-owned.
   The bill amends the constitution by inserting the sentence:
``The religion of the republic is Islam, but other religions may be
practiced in peace and harmony.''
   A senior member of the Jatiya Party said today that Ershad
probably would sign the bill Saturday.
   Bangladesh is 87 percent Moslem, but opponents include women,
opposition politicians, students, labor groups and members of the
minority Christian, Hindu and Buddhist religions.
   The government denies the measure will lead to Islamic law,
saying it has no plans to change the Anglo-Saxon based civil law in
Bangladesh.
   Ershad also defended the law Wednesday in a speech near
Faridpur, 60 miles southwest of Dhaka.
   ``The law has foiled conspiracies against our religion (Islam)
and nipped the attack on our distinctive identity and
sovereignty,'' Ershad said without elaborating.
</TEXT>
