<HEAD>Fiery Pileup Kills Six After Smoke Blinds Drivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke from a burning field
obscured drivers' vision, causing a fiery 11-vehicle pileup that
killed four people and injured six, state police said.
   ``Drivers weren't able to see further than about 10 feet'' as
they entered the smoke over Interstate 40, Cpl. Walter Willis said
Thursday.
   Seven tractor-trailers, three cars and a pickup truck were
involved in the crash Wednesday night, he said.
   Five of the injured were treated at hospitals and released. A
sixth person suffered burns and a fractured ankle and knee and
underwent surgery, officials said.
   Willis said the fire along the highway may have been started by
lightning.
