<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ArabSummit 1stLd-Writethru a0472 06-09 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arab Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0654</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Persian Gulf states agreeing
to finance uprising, other details. Trims. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil-rich Persian Gulf states have
agreed to give the Palestine Liberation Organization a massive
subsidy to finance the six-month-old uprising in the
Israeli-occupied territories, the PLO said today.
   Sources in other delegations at the Arab Summit said the amount
may exceed $100 million per year.
   Earlier, Saudi Arabia and North Yemen called on the Arab states
at the summit take Egypt back into the Arab League but were
rebuffed by the summit host, Algeria, officials said. The league
expelled Egypt after it signed a peace accord with Israel in 1979.
   The summit, due to close later in the day, was called primarily
to discuss the Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip. More than 200 Palestinians have died since the uprising
began Dec. 8. Two Israelis also have died.
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat initially asked the summit to provide
$600 million a year. He said the revolt cost the PLO more than $50
million a month in relief, compensation for wages lost by striking
Palestinians and medical expenses of injured rioters.
   The requested sum was reduced following negotiations among an
eight-member committee of delegation chiefs convened to seek
agreement on the subsidies as well as payments to Jordan and Syria
for costs stemming from the uprising.
   The committee included delegates from Algeria, Syria, Jordan,
the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the PLO.
   PLO spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif denied news reports the summit
had rebuffed PLO demands for financial support for the uprising,
the most serious challenge to Israel since it captured the West
Bank and Gaza during the 1967 Middle East war.
   Delegation sources said the gulf states turned down Arafat's
initial request, claiming funds were limited by instability in the
world oil market and the effects of the Iran-Iraq war on oil
exports.
   They said the PLO later agreed to cut its request to $300
million to $400 million, but delegates of the gulf states said even
that was too much.
   There was no mention of Egypt during the first two days of the
summit, but Saudi Foreign Minister Saud Al-Faisal raised the issue
late Wednesday as a ministerial committee was drafting the summit's
final communique.
   Al-Faisal argued that since a majority of the Arab nations have
restored diplomatic ties with Egypt, it was ``counter-productive''
to keep the largest and most powerful Arab nation outside the Arab
League.
   Summit delegates, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Algeria and the moderate pro-Egyptian majority in the 21-member
league reached a compromise that would pave the way for Egypt's
possible readmission to the league at its next regular summit
scheduled for November in Riyad, Saudi Arabia.
   But Libya and Syria maintained their uncompromising opposition
to Egypt's readmission, the sources said.
   After intense backstage discussions, Algeria and Saudi Arabia
agreed to postpone the issue until the Riyad summit, they said. In
a compromise, Algeria agreed not to object to a proposal to be
presented at Riyad inviting Egyptian Hosni Mubarak to join the
meeting.
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi and Syrian President Hafez
Assad said they would continue to oppose the readmission of Egypt
for ``betraying the Arab cause.''
   Gadhafi angered some delegates by telling Arab leaders who
collaborate with the United States that they undermine the Arab
cause and should ``go to hell.'' He did not refer to any leaders by
name.
   Gadhafi wore a white glove on his right hand, and one Libyan
delegate said the glove was intended to ``avoid contact with a hand
that shook that of (Israeli Foreign Minister) Shimon Peres.''
   Morocco's King Hassan II received Peres, then prime minister, in
July 1986.
</TEXT>
