<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ShuttleBoosters 2ndLd-Writethru a0578 06-09 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Boosters, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0578,710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 4 grafs to take into account plans to reopen plant;
picks up 5th graf pvs: Together, the</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Denies Aid to Blast-Shattered Nevada Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House space committee is
criticizing the Reagan administration for refusing federal aid for
the explosion-damaged Nevada town which makes a vital component of
the fuel that powers the nation's rockets and the space shuttle
booster.
   Rep. Robert Roe, D-N.J., asks how the townspeople of Henderson,
Nev. can be expected to drop their opposition to making the
volatile chemical ammonium perchlorate there at the same time the
federal goverment turns down a request for disaster assistance.
   One of the town's two ammonium perchlorate plants, operated by
Pacific Engineering and Production Company, exploded on May 4,
killing two people, injuring hundreds and causing $73 million in
damage. The second plant, operated by Kerr-McGee Corporation, was
shut down after the explosion, reopened briefly and closed again
after Gov. Richard Bryan threatened to sue on grounds that the
facility was a safety hazard.
   A few hours after a hearing by Roe's investigations subcommittee
of the House Science and Technology Committee ended Wednesday,
Kerr-McGee announced in Henderson that differences with the Clark
County Fire Department had been ironed out and that the company
plans to resume production of ammonium perchlorate next week. The
fire department had found some safety violations and threatened
action.
   Together, the two plants were the only U.S. source of the
chemical, which is also used in dozens of rockets such as the
Trident, Peacekeeper, Minuteman, Titan and Delta.
   On Wednesday, the Federal Emergency Management Agency rejected a
request from Bryan for disaster relief for Henderson.
   ``Why in God's name would we not give them aid?'' Roe asked.
``It's extraordinary to me that here we are looking for the
cooperation that we need desperately now with the good authorities
in Nevada and we are coming back and saying `Too bad, you can
rebuild your own libraries, rebuild your own schools, we want to
get the most production out of this facility, but we're not going
to do anything to help you.'''
   Richard Truly, the head of NASA's space shuttle program,
responded that while the probleble of producing 40
million pounds of a major solid rocket fuel component called
ammonium perchlorate. Kerr-McGee can produce 36 million pounds.
   The Las Vegas Review-Journal reported Wednesday that the Pacific
Engineering plant had been cited by the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration for 123 health and safety violations since
1974. Company spokeswoman Connie Richardson declined to comment on
the report.
   Truly told the House committee that NASA has four sets of
booster rockets on hand and if the fuel shortage continues next
year some flights will have to be dropped.
   He said Morton Thiokol, which builds the rockets, ``will be in a
position'' in mid-June to direct Pacific Engineering to build a new
facility capable of producing 30 million pounds of fuel a year.
That, he said, could be accomplished within six months to eight
months, with some added time for testing.
   The money for the plant, Truly said, would come from a 5 cents
per pound surcharge on the fuel. The same method might be used to
expand Kerr-McGee's facility.
   ``Our first and foremost effort,'' Truly said, ``must be to
safely but as quickly as we possibly can, to get Kerr-McGee
production back in place. We must rebuild our lost capability and
we have moved out to do so.''
   The committee was told that demand for ammonium perchlorate
would rise from 37.8 million pounds this year to more than 60
million pounds in 1989. The bulk of the fuel would be used by NASA,
the Army, Navy and Air Force and the rest for commercial, export
and other uses.
   Truly also said NASA was weighing options for fixing and using
six sets of booster rockets remaining from before the Challenger
accident in January 1986. Those rockets have the same flaws in the
joints that doomed the Challenger.
   ``We are seriously thinking about how those boosters would be
used,'' Truly said. ``It would be very premature as to what options
we may have.''
   Each set of shuttle boosters uses 1.7 million pounds of ammonium
perchlorate.
</TEXT>
