<HEAD>Newman Denies Promising Deli Owner A Share In Food Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Paul Newman today denied
promising stock or profits from his food business to a Westport
delicatessen owner.
   The 63-year-old president and founder of Newman's Own Inc.
testified that the idea for the company's salad dressing, its
recipe, label and packaging were his.
   A few other people were involved, Newman said, but he insisted
that deli owner Julius Gold was not among them.
   Gold has alleged that an attorney for Newman promised him 8
percent of the stock from Newman's food company in return for
helping Newman's Own.
   Gold has said he contributed 30 months' effort to Newman's
company and believed that his ``judgment and perseverance ... led
to the success of this corporation.''
   Newman's Own, whose products include spaghetti sauce, lemonade
and popcorn, has donated $15 million to charity since 1982 and
helped create a camp for seriously ill children in northeastern
Connecticut, which opened last week.
   Newman joked on the stand that he declined requests from state
Democrats that he run for the U.S. Senate because he wanted to be
the ``Salad King of New England.''
