<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--CryFreedom     06-09 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cry Freedom,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attenborough Film To Screen Next Month In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Cry Freedom,'' a film about
the death in detention of black consciousness founder Steven Biko,
will be shown in South African theaters next month, the
distributors said Thursday.
   The Richard Attenborough film, nominated for three Academy
Awards, was to have been shown in South African theaters in April,
but the distributors, United International Pictures, withdrew it
because of fears of prosecution.
   The film is based on a book by Donald Woods, a white South
African newspaper editor who fled the country after Biko's death in
1977.
   Woods is a ``banned'' person in South Africa and cannot be
quoted, but the film was passed without cuts by the government's
censorship body, the Publication Appeals Board.
   The movie uses direct quotes from Woods, and the distributors
had placed advertisements in South African newspapers quoting him.
   Peter Dignan, United International spokesman in Johannesburg,
said he was given orders from London to place the film in 30
cinemas nationwide on July 29.
</TEXT>
