<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0574 06-09 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0574,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He'll Search `Far And Wide' For Right Running Mate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 3rd graf to show Kitty Dukakis released bgng ``Dukakis
attended...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis met today with Costa
Rican president Oscar Arias and said the United States must
``develop a new relationship based on respect'' with Latin American
leaders. His presidential campaign focused on choosing a running
mate.
   Dukakis praised Arias' peace plan for Central America and said
the U.S. government should consult frequently with leaders of the
troubled region. Arias sidestepped a question about endorsing the
certain Democratic nominee, saying only that he would be a ``good
friend of whoever you decide to elect in November.''
   Dukakis attended the Harvard University commencement, where
Arias was to give the main address, and was at wife Kitty's side as
she was released from Massachusetts General Hospital. Mrs. Dukakis
is recovering from spinal surgery a week ago.
   On Wednesday, Dukakis placed Paul Brountas, his senior adviser
and friend since law school, in charge of his vice presidential
selection process.
   ``He was the guy with the ideas,'' Brountas said of the
Massachusetts governor. ``We talked about timing, how to go about
developing the process, getting moving, how we're going to do it.''
   Dukakis stopped in St. Louis along the way to receive the public
backing of a defeated rival, Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. Two other
rivals also clambered aboard the Dukakis bandwagon _ Sen. Paul
Simon, D-Ill., and former Gov. Bruce Babbitt of Arizona. And he got
the backing of New York Gov. Mario Cuomo as well.
   ``We clashed from time to time, but that conflict, that trying
and testing of ideas and energies, can only be good for the party
and for the nation,'' Gephardt said.
   Dukakis picked up 27 Missouri delegates along with Gephardt's
backing, and Simon released the delegates he had won. But it hardly
mattered.
   Dukakis had gained a majority of delegates with his two-to-one
victory in California, bringing down the curtain on a race for the
nomination that had long since lost its suspense.
   At his first news conference since gaining a mathematical lock
on the nomination, Dukakis rejected Jackson's assertion that he had
earned the right to choose whether he would join Dukakis on the
ticket.
   ``He deserves consideration. He's done a very impressive job in
running his campaign,'' Dukakis said. ``But there are other people
who will be considered as well, and it's up to the nominee to make
that selection.''
   He said his top priority would be selecting a ``first-rate''
candidate who could assume the presidency if needed, and said
traditional political considerations such as geographic region or
ideology were of less importance.
   ``Other considerations obviously are not irrelevant, but they
pale by comparison,'' Dukakis said.
   ``I'm going to cast my net far and wide,'' he said. ``It is best
to begin with as large a group as possible.''
   He said he hoped to have ``a very good idea'' of who his running
mate would be before the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta
in mid-July.
   Brountas said no formal search committee was planned, and that
he would discuss the selection with top campaign staff members and
consult with political, business and labor leaders.
   Brountas also said ``I'm sure'' Jackson would be among those
consulted.
   Dukakis was asked if any women were on his list, and replied,
``There's no list.''
   He said there was no ideological or issue litmus test. ``I'm not
looking for a clone,'' he said.
   Dukakis turned briefly to the fall campaign against Republican
nominee-to-be George Bush, taking issue with the vice president's
comparison of this election race to the 1972 campaign between
George McGovern and Richard Nixon.
   ``That's nonsense,'' Dukakis told a television interviewer.
``This isn't Nixon-McGovern, and it's not FDR-Hoover. This will be
a campaign between two individuals, both of whom have been in
public life for a long time.''
   When Dukakis returned home on Wednesday night, he was greeted by
a crowd of about 75 people, most of them campaign workers in his
Boston headquarters.
   He arrived several hours late after being delayed in St. Louis
by severe thunderstorms.
   ```Here I am the nominee. I can't do anything about the
weather,'' he joked.
   He thanked the campaign workers for their support and help,
saying: ``You have helped to teach me, and I'm very grateful to all
of you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
