<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Britain-AIDS     06-09 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-AIDS,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Jailed For AIDS Infection Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man received a two-year jail sentence Thursday
for threatening to contaminate meat with AIDS-infected blood unless
one of Britain's large grocery store chains paid him $135,000.
   Unemployed Arthur Adams, 40, wrote to J. Sainsbury PLC in
November demanding the money, claiming he represented a man
suffering from AIDS, prosecutor Martin Heslop told Old Baiey
Central Criminal Court.
   Sainsbury's contacted the police and Detective Chief Inspector
Graham Clifford, posing as a store representative, started
negotiations with Adams.
   Clifford's numerous phone calls led first to Adams' dropping his
demand to more than $70,000 and then to his arrest when he tried to
collect the money.
   ``I was at the end of my tether,'' Adams was quoted as telling
police.
   ``My mind was twisted with hatred and depression ... I had no
reason for choosing Sainsbury's. It could have been anyone. I never
had any AIDS samples or knew anyone with the disease. It was merely
a confidence trick.''
</TEXT>
