<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CanceledGraduation     06-09 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canceled Graduation,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Says There Was No Suicide Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRVIEW, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school senior says administrators
apparently misinterpreted his comments in deciding to cancel
graduation ceremonies and final exams for fear that students would
carry out a suicide pact.
   Neal Loeslein, 18, denied the existence of a suicide pact or
other plans for violence among students at Fairview High School.
   ``There wasn't one. That was just a rumor,'' he said in today's
Pittsburgh Press.
   Loeslein told the newspaper he was the student present at
Christmastime at the home of another senior who fatally shot
himself in the head with a handgun in this affluent Lake Erie
suburb of about 7,500 people.
   He said that talk of a suicide pact surfaced soon afterward and
that the talk apparently intensified two weeks ago when he told
classmates in a general way, ``This is a graduation we will all
remember.''
   Loeslein said he had planned to play out a practical joke at the
ceremony but had not decided on the joke.
   He accused administrators of spreading rumors. ``They built all
of this out of nothing,'' he said.
   Officials on Tuesday canceled baccalaureate ceremonies scheduled
for today and graduation ceremonies scheduled for Sunday for about
150 seniors, saying they have evidence of a suicide pact among
friends of the dead student.
   Officials said another, similar handgun was stolen from the dead
student's home.
   ``It's more than just pranks,'' said school Solicitor Frank
Kroto. ``It's more than the typical end of the year dissatisfaction
with authority.''
   Administrators, who spoke to the Erie Morning News on condition
they not be identified, said consultants determined at least two
students involved in the alleged suicide pact were indeed suicidal.
   Kroto also said several school administrators also received
personal threats and are under police protection. He gave no
details.
   State police Cpl. James Scheig said law enforcement authorities
are not investigating the alleged threats of violence or the
possibility of suicides. He said some administrator's homes were
being checked periodically.
</TEXT>
