<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   06-09 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0487,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Outline Timetable for Peace Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Sandinista proposal to end
civil war, details. Pick up 4th pvs, ``The Contras ...'' EDITS
thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government
outlined a plan today that could lead to a lasting cease-fire in
its six-year civil war with U.S.-backed rebels.
   Gen. Humberto Ortega, the defense minister, released a timetable
to free imprisoned rebels and former national guardsmen, to discuss
democratic reforms and to disarm the rebels, known as Contras.
   The plan, if approved by the Contras later today, would begin
Friday with the release of 200 former national guardsmen.
   ``They (the Contras) asked for the timetable and now they don't
have any pretext not to sign'' a peace agreement, said Paul
Reichler, a Washington attorney who is on the Sandinista
negotiating committee.
   Ortega released the plan at a news conference and said he was
giving it to Contra negotiators. There was no immediate comment by
Contra leaders.
   Under the plan, Contra combatants should begin moving into seven
determined zones and Sandinista troops will move out of those areas
on June 16.
   On July 12, the Contras could relieve ``exclusively humanitarian
aid'' and eight Contras can take part in internal talks with the
political opposition in Managua. On the same day, the government
would begin 60 days of talks on democratic reforms.
   At the end of that period, the Contras would begin disarmament,
Ortega said. By Oct. 10, Contras would leave the zones and
disarmament would be completed.
   On the same date, the Contras can receive ``exclusively
humanitarian aid.'' Also, eight Contra representatives can take
part in internal talks with the political opposition parties in
Managua. Also, 50 percent of the Contra prisoners will be freed and
400 ex-national guardsmen will be freed.
   The Contras had agreed to extend a truce that began on March 21
until today. It was not immediately clear whether the fighting,
which has killed more than 26,000 people would start again.
   The Sandinistas say they will unilaterally observe a truce until
June 30.
   The rebels accused the Sandinistas of being evasive about when
promised democratic reforms would be enacted.
   ``In our view, a concrete result depends on the political
goodwill of the government,'' Matamoros said.
   The Contras complained that the government postponed until today
a meeting that had been planned Wednesday afternoon with leaders of
Nicaragua's opposition political parties.
   The meeting would be the first time Contra leaders would be
allowed to hold political talks with the internal opposition groups.
   Meanwhile, the Sandinista police Wednesday rounded up 14
political opposition figures for staging an ``unauthorized march.''
They were detained briefly, then released.
   The demonstration was called to protest a law that has enabled
the Sandinistas to close radio stations for broadcasting what the
government claims to be misinformation or unconfirmed news about
the war or military draft.
   Among those detained were Erick Ramirez, president of the Social
Christian Party, and Agustin Harquin Anaya, president of a faction
of the same party.
   Negotiators for the government and the rebels differ on amnesty
for political prisoners, political representation in national talks
and disarmament.
   Matamoros said the Contras on Wednesday prepared a list of the
names of 4,207 political prisoners in 37 Sandinista jails. The
government claims there are 3,100 such prisoners.
</TEXT>
