<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--SurrogateParenting     06-09 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Surrogate Parenting,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Ban On Pregnancy-For-Pay Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who arrange surrogate births for a
profit would face up to five years in prison and a $50,000 fine
under legislation approved today by the Michigan House.
   Representatives voted 90-10 to outlaw pregnancy-for-pay
contracts as being unenforceable and contrary to public policy.
   However, the legislation would let a woman in a surrogacy
agreement be compensated for her expenses. She also could accept
gifts from the contracting couple, as long as it's clear the gift
didn't amount to the buying of a child.
   The legislation would guarantee that in the case of a custody
dispute the baby would remain with its mother until a judge
determined whether it was in the child's best interest to give
custody to the father.
   The Senate is expected to give final approval, said Sen. Connie
Binsfeld.
</TEXT>
