<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PlaneCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0517 06-09 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0517,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six National Guardsmen Killed In C-130 Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with last bodies pulled from
wreckage. PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Witnesses said ...'; DELETES
next-to-last graf, `The bodies ...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military transport plane was
practicing touch-and-go landings before it crashed and burned in a
fireball, killing the six Air National Guardsmen aboard,
authorities and witnesses said.
   The last two bodies were pulled from the wreckage of the C-130
turboprop this morning, said Col. Dennis Wood, a spokesman for the
Air Force Base in Little Rock, Ark., where the plane was based.
   The plane was about a mile short of the Greenville Municipal
Airport runway when it crashed Wednesday afternoon. Workers used
lights to search through the night for bodies.
   Witnesses said the plane appeared to veer to its left as it was
landing and crashed into a clearing near the runway.
   ``I didn't see it come down. When I saw it, it was a just a big
fireball,'' said Reggie Kellems, who was driving a tractor about
100 yards away. ``There was debris flying all up in the air.''
   Military authorities sealed off the area shortly after the crash.
   Air Force officials said the plane was on a training mission.
   ``They had been with us for some time doing touch-and-go
training landings,'' said Richard Brewer, air traffic manager at
the northeast Mississippi airport. ``The plane was in the pattern
and the first we knew something was wrong was when it impacted.''
   Air Force officials said they couldn't confirm that it was
practicing a touch-and-go landing when it crashed.
   In September 1986, a C-130 practicing touch-and-go landings
crashed at Fort Campbell, Ky., killing three of the five National
Guardsmen aboard. A survivor said the plane had lost an engine. In
June 1987, three Navy aviators died when their EA-3B Skywarrior
electronic warfare jet crashed during a touch-and-go drill at
Miramar Naval Air Station in San Diego.
   In touch-and-go drills, a pilot allows the plane's wheels to
briefly touch the runway before taking off again. The drills often
simulate a ground drop in combat conditions, in which cargo would
be dumped out of the moving plane.
   Maj. Jim Bates, a spokesman at Little Rock Air Force Base, said
the aircraft was assigned to the 189th Tactical Airlift Group of
the Arkansas Air National Guard.
   He said it is not unusual for members of the Arkansas Air
National Guard to be on training missions out of state.
   Wood said guardsmen from other states train at the air base,
where 81 of the large planes are stationed.
   A spokeswoman for the air base, Airman 1st Class Deborah Doyle,
identified the dead as:
   Maj. Andries R. Zwaan, 39, a pilot with the 189th Tactical Air
Lift Group at the Arkansas Air National Guard based in Little Rock;
Staff Sgt. David Bingham, 24, a member of the 181st Tactical Air
Lift Squadron at Hensley Field in Dallas, Texas; 2nd Lt. Mark R.
Brandt, 24, of the 180th Tactical Air Lift Squadron at Rosecrans
Municipal Airport at St. Joseph, Mo.; 2nd Lt. Thomas D. Leece, 28,
of the 934th Tactical Air Lift Group of Minneapolis, Minn.; Master
Sgts. Edwin J. Smith Jr., 35, and Danny W. Holland, 39, both
assigned to the 189th.
   Another C-130 from Little Rock arrived late Wednesday with more
than 40 crash investigators and support personnel.
</TEXT>
