<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TwinDeaths     06-09 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Twin Deaths,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Given Life Term for Beating Deaths of Twin Sons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman has been sentenced to life in prison for
the beating deaths of her AIDS-infected, heroin-addicted infant
twin sons.
   ``The human soul is capable of evil acts,'' Judge Michael Sapala
said Wednesday in sentencing Linda Diane Cannon, 30, of Detroit.
   Sapala, in a non-jury trial, convicted Cannon two weeks ago of
second-degree murder in the deaths of Shawn and DeShawn. The
4-month-old babies died of skull fractures induced by severe
beating in October 1987.
   According to testimony, both children contracted AIDS and became
addicted to heroin before birth from their mother.
   The twins were Cannon's ninth and 10th children. Seven have been
placed in foster homes, while the other died of sudden infant death
syndrome.
   Cannon's attorney, Robert Edick, said his client was unable to
handle ``the never-ending cycle of demands ... with twins.''
   Cannon told Sapala she was sorry and wanted to rebuild her life.
She will be eligible for parole in 10 years.
</TEXT>
