<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Israel-Revolt     06-09 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Revolt,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Bank Commander Sees Waning Revolt but Surge in Terror</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli military official said Thursday his
troops have quelled the Palestinian uprising against Israel's
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip but now are bracing for
increased terrorism by a ``hard core'' of Arab youths.
   ``It took us more time than we expected,'' said Maj. Gen. Amram
Mitzna, but Israeli troops have ``gained back the deterrence that
we lost at the beginning of the intifadah'' _ Arabic for uprising.
   Mitzna, the military commander of the West Bank, spoke to
reporters during a visit to Washington about the 7-month Arab
revolt that has resulted in the deaths of 203 Palestinians and two
Israelis.
   ``There is no more high velocity of violence in the streets,''
Mitzna said. ``The situation is calming down.''
   The Palestinians' willingness to openly confront Isaeli soldiers
``is less and less,'' Mitzna said.
   Instead, Palestinians are resorting to ``pinpoint attacks'' such
as hurling firebombs at Israeli patrols, Mitzna said. He predicted
the Palestinians will turn more to bombs and guns rather than the
stones and burning tires that were their main weapons until now.
   ``A hard core of Palestinian youngsters is still there,'' Mitzna
said, although the majority of the population is tiring of the
revolt.
   Having failed to accomplish political gains in the uprising,
``it is a great worry for us that once again pure terrorism will
return'' as Palestinians seek recognition for their demands, he
said.
   The 1.5 million Palestinians in the territories captured by
Israel in the 1967 Mideast war are demanding an end to Israeli
control and an independent state.
   Mitzna said the terrorism would be directed both against the
estimated 65,000 Jewish settlers in the predominantly Arab
territories, and against dense Israeli population centers.
   He predicted Israel will have to maintain higher than normal
troop levels in the occupied territories despite the returning calm
because ``I don't think we'll be able to go back to the status
quo.''
   Israeli intelligence has reported broad disagreement within the
leadership of the Palestine Liberation Organizaiton over the future
course of the revolt, he said.
   Some think the uprising should be stopped because of its failure
to achieve a political breakthrough and the high human toll it has
exacted, he said.
   Others in the PLO think the anti-Israel violence should be
escalated in order to drive a permanent wedge between the
Palestinians in the territories and Israel.
   Instructions by the Palestinian leadership to boycott Israeli
products, resign from Israeli-paid jobs and withhold payment of
Israeli taxes have had partial success which is now being eroded,
he said.
   He conceded that Israel still does not know who are the leaders
of the uprising.
   But he said the assassination in Tunis last April of Abu Jihad,
the No. 2 man in the PLO, will adversely affect the ability of the
organizers to continue their revolt. Abu Jihad, who is widely
believed to have been killed by Israeli commandos, was in charge of
operations in the occupied territories.
   Israel has also taken another step to crush the leadership of
the revolt by ordering the expulsion of Mubarak Awad, a Palestinian
with U.S. citizenship whom Miztna described as the theoretical
``mastermind'' behind the revolt.
   ``His deportation is first of all to cut his immediate influence
in the area,'' he said.
   The United States has asked Israel to reconsider the move, but
Mitzna insisted that although Awad did not have a role in
organizing the revolt, its leaders were translating his anti-Israel
writings into action.
</TEXT>
