<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DualDukakis Bjt   06-09 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dual Dukakis, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Carefully Draws Line Between Candidate, Governor Roles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was 9 a.m. and Tom Herman was out the door of
the Massachusetts Statehouse after an early morning meeting with
his boss, Michael Dukakis.
   Herman's time was up _ this was a Statehouse day for Dukakis,
who for 15 months has carefully juggled his dual role as
Massachusetts governor and presidential candidate.
   Herman, a top presidential campaign issues adviser, recalls
asking Dukakis to review position papers on health care and crime
on a day the governor was tending to state duties.
   ``Tom, Statehouse days are state business days,'' Dukakis
lectured him.
   ``It drives some people crazy, but that's Mike Dukakis,'' Herman
said. ``He has two more-than-full-time jobs now, and while it can
sometimes be very frustrating for us at the campaign, he feels very
strongly about Statehouse days.''
   Throughout his presidential campaign Dukakis, with few
exceptions, has spent at least two and generally three full days a
week at the Statehouse. Those Statehouse days mean campaign aides
have limited access to their candidate.
   Although he does use his Statehouse office for some campaign
staff meetings and receptions with visiting congressmen, such
sessions are infrequent and generally held either in the early
morning before state offices open or in the late afternoon.
   ``We respect his time as governor and will only interfere with
that if it is absolutely necessary,'' said campaign spokesman
Leslie Dach. ``Campaign folks always want more time for the
campaign, but he's got a big job here.''
   There are some obvious signs of the separation of governor and
candidate.
   Dukakis had a campaign-financed telephone installed in his
Statehouse office so that he doesn't call advisers, delegates,
supporters, congressmen and others on his state phone. Campaign
phones also were installed in the governor's press office and those
of his top aides.
   ``In fact I'm speaking to you on that phone,'' John DeVillars,
the governor's deputy chief of staff, said in a recent interview.
``Michael has a very cautious and careful and conservative approach
to making certain that his political activities are separate and
distinct from the exercise of his responsibilities as chief
executive. That's an approach that has marked his entire career.''
   The state each month charges the campaign for copying, courier
services and other campaign-related expenses it incurs.
   The careful bookkeeping is nothing new for Dukakis, who for
years has reimbursed the state whenever his state car has been used
to drive him to fund-raisers or to the supermarket. He also lists
such trips as income on his tax returns.
   But Dukakis now has a horde of campaign reporters following him
daily and it is inevitable that there will be some overlap between
his state duties and his candidacy. At recent Statehouse briefings,
Dukakis has set the ground rules: questions on the topic of the day
first before the media free-for-all.
   Sometimes overlap is deliberate; other times it is not.
   When Dukakis signs state legislation that he believes helps his
national candidacy, the words ``model for the nation'' frequently
flow from the mouth of the governor-candidate. He also is quick to
schedule photo sessions with visiting congressmen or dignitaries.
   But when campaign reporters are trying to make a national issue
of a state problem _ its current budget crisis or controversial
prison furlough program, for example _ Dukakis is equally quick to
link them to a ``national problem'' or cite his record of making
``tough choices,'' a stock line in his campaign stump speech.
   Other examples of overlap include the inclusion of a campaign
aide in the governor's scheduling meetings and increased demands on
Dukakis Statehouse aides to answer campaign-related queries.
   Dukakis also has used his gubernatorial stationery when sending
campaign-related letters to President Reagan, Secretary of State
George Shultz, other administration officials and congressional
leaders.
   The overlap also works the other way.
   While on the road campaigning, Dukakis lugs along two nylon bags
filled with state work, which he tends to at breakfast and while
traveling between campaign stops.
</TEXT>
