<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BishopExecution     06-09 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bishop Execution,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Meeting With Parents, Mormon Clergy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A child molester who murdered five boys
will die by injection after midnight tonight, barring any
unforeseen appeals.
   Arthur Gary Bishop, who has forgone further appeals, met
Wednesday with his parents, his lawyer and Mormon Bishop Heber
Geurtz and planned to spend his final hours fasting, said
Corrections Department spokesman Juan Benavidez.
   ``He seems to be preparing himself for what will take place, as
well as anyone can,'' Benavidez said.
   Bishop, 36, would be the third person in Utah and the 99th
person in the nation to be executed since the U.S. Supreme Court
reinstituted capital punishment in 1976.
   Because Bishop wants to die and has been found competent by a
judge, civil rights groups such as Amnesty International and the
American Civil Liberties Union say last-minute friend-of-the-court
appeals are unlikely.
   Bishop fired his attorneys and said he would not contest his
death sentence further after the Utah Supreme Court rejected his
appeal in February. He has said he hopes his death will bring peace
to the parents of his victims.
   ``Art is resolute in his decision to go through with this,''
said his attorney, Walter F. Bugden Jr. ``He is as ready as one can
be to die.''
   Bishop was taken late Wednesday to a holding cell near the death
chamber. Utah law allows the condemned to choose between death by
lethal injection or firing squad.
   Bishop's oldest victim was 13; two were 4, another was 6 and the
other was 11. Two of the boys were drowned after being struck on
the head with a hammer, another was killed with a hammer, one was
suffocated and one shot.
   In taped statements to police after his arrest, Bishop, an Eagle
Scout and excommunicated Mormon missionary, said: ``I know I'm
damning myself to hell for doing it. I'm glad you caught me,
because I couldn't stop. ... I would do it again if I had a
chance.''
   He also laughed at several points during his confession,
describing to police how he ``did'' his victims.
   The lawyer said Bishop's spirits were ``not particularly high,''
but he did joke about closing out his $5 commissary account at the
prison.
   ``He said something about not wanting to overdraw the account
here because we already know there are First Security banks all
over hell,'' Bugden said.
   The money was given to his brother, Douglas Bishop, who is
serving a prison term for sexually abusing boys.
   The last execution in Utah was in August, when Pierre Dale Selby
was put to death for the 1974 torture-murders of three people
during a robbery at a stereo shop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
