<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CatastrophicIllness     06-09 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catastrophic Illness,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Benefit Bill Gets Favorable White House Mention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly passed legislation expanding Medicare to
help the elderly deal with the costs of serious illness received
favorable mention from the White House and the endorsement of Vice
President George Bush on Thursday.
   ``The president is very concerned about long-term health care,
as he has said a number of times,'' White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said. ``We don't want to forecast the final action on
this bill, but we look favorably upon it.''
   Bush, who flew to Houston to campaign for the presidency,
endorsed the measure in a statement issued a statement through his
office.
   ``The legislation which passed yesterday will, for the first
time since the founding of Medicare, extend benefits for our
seniors,'' the vice president said. ``Now they do not have to live
in fear that their life's savings would be wiped out by a prolonged
hospitalization.''
   The legislation, the first major expansion of Medicare in 23
year, is more ambitious than the proposal originally laid out by
the president. However, Secretary of Health and Human Services Otis
Bowen has said he will recommend that Reagan sign it.
   The measure passed the Senate, 86-11, on Wednesday and was sent
to the White House.
   The new legislation provides a kind of safety net for Medicare
beneficiaries faced with extraordinary expenses from acute
illnesses such as cancer.
   It also introduces a general prescription drug benefit into the
Medicare program for the first time, applying to those who run up
more than $600 a year in drug bills.
   The expanded benefits are estimated to cost $32.6 billion over
the next five years and are to be paid by the potential
beneficaries through an assessment of $4 a month on Medicare
premiums of 32 million covered individuals.
</TEXT>
