<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Reporters     06-09 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Reporters,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Covering His Campaign Is an Education</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>By RITA BEAMISH</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says the reporters covering his
campaign will be better people for the experience and should in
turn ``educate their bosses.''
   Jackson frequently criticizes the news media in his speeches,
telling voters not to be misled by reports that play down his
chances of winning the presidential nomination.
   But he suggests he's done plenty for the reporters, educating
them on American culture by taking them to the back corners of the
nation where he campaigned.
   ``I've taken media people to low places. I've taken them to the
ghettos, the barrios, to reservations. I've also taken them to the
high places to see the real America,'' he said.
   He said this week he has seen a shift in news media attitudes
toward his candidacy over the course of the campaign
   ``There has been an evolution in the media's consciousness and
in its maturity,'' he said. ``After all, the media leaders
themselves are bound by their own culture and they must grow and
expand.''
   ``Our campaign in some measure has been a factor in educating
many members of the media. Some have made better grades than
others,'' Jackson said. ``In the course of our campaign you have
seen a growth process taking place.''
   ``The people working on my campaign will be better people when
it's over. They'll be different people. They've seen more of
America than most Americans have. The media people working on my
campaign know more than their editors do, their publishers do.''
   These reporters now must ``educate their bosses,'' he suggested.
   He objected that news reports have raised the issue of his race,
and he said there should be more minority members and women in
positions of news leadership.
   ``I'm the stimulus. I'm the catalyst for that change. And one
day when you look into newsrooms you're going to see black, white
and brown publishers and editors, correspondents, script writers,''
he said. ``There must be a multicultural presence in that room to
have a multicultural result.''
</TEXT>
