<HEAD>Fifth-Graders Accused of School Sex Assaults</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elementary school parents jammed a
principal's office Thursday after learning that three fifth-graders
were arrested for sexually assaulting boys in the school bathroom.
   The incidents took place between January and April, said police
spokesman Tom Hoolahan, and involved up to nine victims who in some
cases were forced into oral sex.
   The suspects _ ages 10, 11 and 12 _ were arrested Wednesday and
charged with one count each of sexual battery.
   Ida M. Fisher Elementery School Principal Paulette Martin
announced Thursday that the boys had been suspended, and denied
there were security problems at 830-pupil school.
   ``Everyone there says that there's security,'' said parent
Teresa Troy, among those at Ms. Martin's office Thursday. ``There's
no security _ they're lying and everyone's covering it up.''
   Another mother, Debra Allen, complained her daughter had come
home with a black eye earlier in the week, and school officials
knew nothing about it.
   The alleged offenders, described by police as ``older-looking
and stronger,'' were in the same fifth-grade class as the victims.
The teacher allowed groups of boys to go to the bathroom to
minimize class disruption, school officials said.
   The case was discovered Monday when one victim told a teacher
and Ms. Martin alerted police.
   The boys told investigators they were mimicking acts they saw on
late-night cable television, said police Sgt. James Mazer.
   ``The incidents are isolated to students in this one class,''
Mazer said. ``We don't know with what regularity the attacks
occurred. We believe they didn't happen every day, but a few
times.''
   The two older boys have been placed in the custody of the state
Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services. The youngest
suspect was released to his parents' custody.

</TEXT>
