<HEAD>Fire on Cheyenee Reservation Appears Under Control</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with fire nearly under
control, CORRECTS number of firefighters to 800 sted 900; PICKS UP
4th graf pvs, `That's about ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAME DEER, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A force of 800 firefighters closed the
noose early today around the fire that has scorched nearly 23,000
acres of grass and timber since Sunday on the Northern Cheyenne
Indian Reservation.
   Fire boss Al Kutt said he probably would declare the blaze
contained tonight and under control Friday night _ a day earlier
than he had predicted _ and might be able to begin demobilizing the
firefighting force on Saturday.
   ``It's looking great, really great,'' Kutt said.
   Four days of temperatures over 100 degrees and low humidity had
fueled the fire, but sudden cooling Wednesday night gave
firefighters a boost, Kutt said.
   ``I'm sitting here with a wool sweater on,''' he said.
   The fire was 98 percent contained by Wednesday night, said fire
information officer Michelle Ravnikar. Hot, dry weather and wind
gusts combined to double the size of the fire Tuesday night, when
it ballooned from about 10,000 acres.
   ``That's about the most extreme fire behavior I've ever seen,''
Al Kutt, incident commander, said Wednesday. ``It went bananas last
night.''
   At the most extreme points, the fire stretches about 10 miles
from east to west and seven miles from north to south.
   Crews came from Montana, Wyoming, Idaho and the Dakotas fought
the blaze. Officials have estimated the cost of the firefighting
effort at $450,000.
