<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AspenHousing     06-09 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aspen Housing,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aspen Public Schools Enter Housing Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school board in this mountain resort has
decided to go into the real estate business to help employees live
in the community, where the average price of a house is $275,000.
   ``Aspen is a very expensive place to live. We want our teachers
to be an integral part of our community and not have to commute,''
board President Jon Seigle said Wednesday.
   The district, with an enrollment of just over 1,000, is
negotiating to buy a three-bedroom condominium and may lease a
house and rent it to a new administrator, he said.
   Officials also are looking at buying land and leasing it to
teachers to build homes, Seigle said. The board is working with the
Aspen-Pitkin County Housing Authority to acquire 10 to 15
properties in coming years, he said.
   In Aspen, the going price for a two-bedroom condominium is about
$1,200 a month, he said, while the school district's average salary
is about $2,600 a month.
   ``While Aspen is a very attractive place to come and work, it
causes us problems when we get a final candidate for a job and they
look at the price of housing,'' Seigle said.
   Some teachers and administrators commute 20 to 30 miles, he said.
   ``Every employer group is affected, from the person who is
trying to hire the dishwasher to the people who are hiring the
school superintendent,'' said Jim Adamski, executive director of
the housing authority.
   Costs for housing provided by the district will be negotiated in
future salary and benefit packages, with the teacher or
administrator paying the district rent, said Seigle.
</TEXT>
