<HEAD>House Approves $4.2 Billion for National Science Foundation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved a two-year, $4.2 billion
spending plan for the National Science Foundation on Thursday after
trimming the measure down to comply with President Reagan's request.
   The bill, which continues programs that give government grants
to researchers, was approved 405-5 and sent to the Senate.
   The bill as approved by the Science, Space and Technology
Committee had envisioned $210 million more spending than the
president requested. By voice vote, the House approved an amendment
by Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., to cut that amount.
   The House also added a provision offered by Rep. James
Traficant, D-Ohio, giving domestic firms an advantage in bidding
against foreign companies for government science contracts.
   The bill included language prohibiting the science foundation
from spending money in cases in which employers have not taken
steps to ensure a drug-free workplace.
