<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     06-09 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Missiles,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Die-Hards Vow To Continue Protest Despite Missile Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUTLANGEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Barbara Kirchner and her band
of die-hard anti-nuclear protesters, the vigil goes on outside a
rocket base despite the superpower accord scrapping medium-range
nuclear weapons in Europe.
   Ms. Kirchner, 21, vows to persist until the last of the missiles
leaves West Germany in 1991. But now she's under pressure from the
anti-nuclear movement to clear out of a house near the Mutlangen
U.S. missile base, 25 miles east of Stuttgart.
   For the past two years Ms. Kirchner has been the most outspoken
among the few remaining activists occupying the ramshackle building
200 yards from the entrance of the Pershing 2 missile site.
   ``Only about six to eight are regulars here anymore,'' Ms.
Kirchner said of what was once a group of more than two dozen that
occupied the house and regularly protested at the site after
missiles were stationed in November 1983.
   The house is owned by a peace group called the ``Peace and
Encounter Center,'' Ms. Kirchner said. ``Now (with the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty ratified June 1) they want
us to move out so they can use it to conduct seminars on
non-violent resistance,'' she said. ``But we don't want to leave
and we're not going to stop until everything is out.''
   In the months before and during initial deployment of the
missiles in West Germany, hundreds of thousands of West Germans
protested nationwide. As the first site to get the nuclear weapons,
Mutlangen became a focal point for demonstrators.
   Ms. Kirchner spoke to The Associated Press on Wednesday during a
press tour of the site given by U.S. officials to explain how
verification and removal of the Pershing 2s in accordance with the
INF treaty would be conducted.
   About 100 protesters stood outside the entrance as reporters
were bused in, some waving, others holding up banners reading:
``Take the Toys from the Boys,'' or ``You Can't Have Both, Babies
and Bombs.''
   Within the West German anti-missile movement there are mixed
feelings about the results of the superpowers' INF treaty to remove
the Pershing 2s. Some see it as a victory, while others see it as a
propaganda stunt.
   ``It's being sold to the public as disarmament, when in fact
there are still thousands of air, sea and other nuclear weapons,''
Ms. Kirchner said.
   But she claimed the treaty shows her group has been successful.
   ``We have achieved something. The (West German) government will
find it very difficult to ever again take part in an arms
buildup,'' Ms. Kirchner said.
</TEXT>
