<HEAD>Refinery Fire Out After Burning Nearly 20 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a Chevron refinery was
extinguished Thursday after burning for nearly 20 hours following
an explosion at the plant.
   The fire began in a pump station at the refinery west of Port
Arthur on Wednesday morning and spread to some small storage tanks
nearby.
   Later Wednesday, some burning fluid began spreading along the
ground and into ditches, but was kept isolated, Chevron spokesman
Art Spencer said.
   Five people suffered minor injuries. And one firefighter was
admitted to a hospital for observation, suffering from dehydration
and heat exhaustion.
   Spencer said it was too early to determine what caused the
explosion.
   Crews located a valve believed to be feeding the fire with
unfinished gasoline and closed it off Wednesday afternoon, but the
fire continued through the night.
   Spencer said most of the blast occurred away from the main
manufacturing area and was not affecting all operations at the
plant.
   The refinery pump station moves hydrocarbons _ unfinished
gasoline _ from the manufacturing section to the storage area,
Spencer said.
