<2ND_LINE>PM-Philly Prisons, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0577,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Order Frees Hundreds of Prisoners in Philadelphia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with city failing to meet
cap, midnight population; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `District Attorney
...'; SUBS 11th graf pvs, `U.S. District ...' with two grafs to
conform.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defendants were jailed in serious cases only
as the city struggled today to meet a court-imposed cap on its
prison population.
   The city had freed 180 inmates as of Wednesday afternoon, but it
was not enough to meet the limit of 3,750 prisoners by the court's
deadline of 5 p.m. Wednesday. That triggered a moratorium on the
jailing of inmates on minor charges.
   At midnight Wednesday, the count stood at 3,865, according to
Bail Commissioner Charles Murray.
   Under the court order, the moratorium is the only sanction
imposed against the city for failing to meet the cap, said William
C. Babcock, special court-appointed prison master. The order
contains no fines or other penalties, he said.
   District Attorney Ronald Castille, who unsuccessfully challenged
the population cap, criticized the city's decision to bail out
inmates.
   ``If the city puts up the bail, there's no incentive for the
person to show up,'' he said. ``If he wants to come in, he can. But
why should he?''
   A small group of Philadelphians cursed inmates leaving one jail
Wednesday, and people driving by shouted, ``Lock 'em up,'' and
``Don't let them out!''
   Terry Williamson, a spokesman for the district attorney's
office, said the order prevents the city from jailing all but those
accused of the most serious crimes _ murder or attempted murder,
rape or attempted rape, kidnapping, arson, robbery, aggravated
assault, or crimes involving a gun, knife or large amounts of drugs.
   Other suspects will be arraigned, given court dates and freed.
   Police will continue to make arrests without regard for the
prison population, said spokesman Detective Edward Tenuto. ``Police
will do their duty as they're trained to do,'' he said.
   U.S. District Judge Norma Shapiro on Friday ordered the city to
reduce the prison population to 3,750 inmates, 259 fewer than
Monday's total.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals issued an emergency stay
at Castille's request but unexpectedly reversed itself Tuesday
without explanation.
   The ceiling was set in a consent decree the city signed in 1986
and originally was scheduled to meet a year ago. The agreement
stemmed from a 1982 class-action suit by inmates challenging
conditions in Philadelphia's four prisons.
</TEXT>
