<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BombDefects     06-09 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb Defects,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Plant Manager Pleads Guilty to Concealing Bomb Part Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former manager of a plant
supplying bomb guidance components to the Air Force and Navy has
pleaded guilty to lying to conceal defects in the parts.
   Ralph Iadarola, 53, manager of the Courter Operations plant in
Boyne City in 1985-86, on Wednesday told U.S. District Judge Robert
Holmes Bell that he was aware of unreported test failures on
laser-guided bomb gyroscopes made by Allied Corp.'s Bendix Guidance
Systems Division.
   ``I literally shut my eyes,'' said Iadarola, currently of
Roseland, N.J. ``I knew of the problems, but I did nothing to
disclose the problems or solve them. This was wrong.''
   Iadarola was indicted in August on one count of conspiring with
six employees he supervised to defraud the U.S. government by
allowing the reports to be falsified and sent to the government. He
also was charged with 19 counts of making the false statements and
concealing facts from the government and with 14 counts of mail and
wire fraud.
   He pleaded guilty Wednesday to the conspiracy count and one
count of causing a false report to be prepared and facts to be
concealed from the Air Force.
   Iadarola faces a maximum of five years in prison and a $250,000
fine on each count at sentencing Aug. 19.
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas J. Gezon said Iadarola
pleaded guilty in exchange for the government's agreement not to
fight his request that he receive a sentence similar to those his
former employees received.
   The six men were each fined $5,000. Bell also ordered each to
perform 200 hours of community service and placed them on three
year's probation.
   The U.S. Defense Department has barred all seven men from
supervising military projects for three years.
</TEXT>
