<DOCNO> AP880609-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Missiles     06-09 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Missiles,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From Interpreters To Vodka, Missile Bases Ready For Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at this U.S. air base
are thinking of everything, from interpreters to miniature bottles
of vodka, as they prepare for a Soviet inspection of the base's 101
cruise nuclear missiles.
   At a half-dozen gates around the base, disheveled groups of
anti-nuclear protesters are waiting it out too.
   The protesters' smoky, littered tent and cardboard camps have
been at Greenham Common, 50 miles west of London, since 1981.
   It is one of the oldest of the ``peace camps'' set up at U.S.
facilities to protest the deployment of U.S. intermediate-range
missiles in Europe.
   Deployment began in November 1983 when the first missiles
arrived at Greenham Common.
   Under the superpower arms control agreement ratified June 1, the
900 missiles are being removed from bases in four West European
countries, along with around 1,800 Soviet medium-range missiles
aimed at Western Europe.
   But the protesters say they will stay on _ suspicious that Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government and the United
States will simply agree to install some other deadly weapons at
Greenham.
   ``I doubt if ratification means much,'' said Sarah Hipperson, a
middle-aged protester who gave up a job and a regular home six
years ago to live outside Greenham Common. ``We are looking for a
whole conversion (away from nuclear weapons.)''
   On Wednesday, the U.S. military allowed journalists into
Greenham Common and two other intermediate-range nuclear missile
bases, at Florennes in Belgium and Mutlangen, West Germany, for the
first time.
   The previously closely shrouded weapons were shown off before
the arrival of the Soviet inspectors. According to the treaty, the
first inspections by 10-member teams will take place at 16 hours
notice in July or August.
   The inspectors will make ``baseline'' checks to verify the
missiles in place before dismantling. By 1991 all the missiles must
be gone, sent back for destruction under Soviet eyes at U.S.
facilities.
   ``What you'll have at the end of this is scrap metal,'' said
Greenham Common comander William E. Jones, indicating the 55-foot
missile launchers lined up beside the giant, grass-covered bunkers
_ from which they still make forays into the English countryside on
manuevers.
   ``When they've been, I shall feel very verified,'' said Jones,
46, of Memphis, Tenn., adding the treaty provisions were tight
enough to stop cheating by either side.
   The Soviet team, which can stay as long as 4{ days on any one
inspection visit, will remain on the base or be taken under escort
to the second cruise base in Britain, at Molesworth. Twenty-nine
missiles are deployed there.
   Lt. Col. Michael McCarney, project director for the inspection
arrangements, has collected miniature bottles of vodka for the
Soviets, and is piling up Sears, Roebuck catalogues _ a favorite
with a Soviet team that visited a facility in San Diego recently.
   Greenham Common, a U.S. air force base for most of the time
since World War II, has been part of historic events before.
   On June 5, 1944, the eve of the D-Day landings to defeat
Hitler's Germany, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower addressed paratroopers
of the 101st Airborne Division at Greenham Common. ``The eyes of
the world are upon you tonight,'' he said in words echoed around
the globe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
