<DOCNO> AP880609-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TradeDeficit     06-09 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Deficit,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commerce Department Releases Adjusted Deficit Figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department released new figures
Thursday showing that the country's huge trade deficits are
improving but not as quickly as previously believed.
   The department's new statistics for the first time in two years
adjust the monthly numbers for normal seasonal changes in shipping
patterns.
   With seasonal adjustment, the trade deficit for March turned out
to be $11.9 billion, 22 percent higher than the previously reported
$9.7 billion figure.
   The non-adjusted figure, the best showing in three years, had
been hailed by the Reagan administration as solid evidence that the
country's trade problems had finally turned around.
   The administration said the new figures still show an improving
trend, noting that the average monthly deficit for the first three
months of the year was $12.5 billion, compared to an average
deficit of $14.3 billion in the final three months of 1987, a
decline of 13 percent.
   The non-adjusted figures showed a sharper 21 percent drop from
the fourth quarter to the first quarter.
   ``The trade deficit is on a downward trend, exports are
increasing and it's a very encouraging picture in terms of the
foreign trade deficit,'' said presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater in an assessment that was echoed by private economists.
   ``The seasonally adjusted figures show that trade is slowly
turning and that should be the story for the rest of the year,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co. ``There is no
reason to be discouraged by the new figures.''
   Commerce Undersecretary Robert Ortner said the revised figure
had been anticipated, given the fact that U.S. export sales always
climb sharply during March and the seasonal adjustment would take
that into account.
   Most government statistics are adjusted to factor out
fluctuations which occur on a seasonal basis, such as the normal
drop in housing construction during winter months. But the
government was forced to abandon seasonal adjustments of the trade
figures for two years because of problems with collecting the data
on a timely basis.
   With that problem solved, the government will resume reporting
seasonally adjusted trade figures beginning with the April trade
report, scheduled to be released next Tuesday.
   Ortner said that the deficit so far this year is running at an
annual average of $150 billion, about what the administration has
been expecting. The merchandise trade deficit hit a record $170.3
billion last year.
   The annual figure for 1987 was revised slightly from an original
figure of $171.2 billion. The 1986 figure was also revised to show
a deficit of $155.1 billion. The changes in the annual totals
reflected more complete data rather than any effect from seasonal
adjustments which will not change annual totals.
   The February deficit, which had originally been reported at
$13.8 billion, was raised to $14.4 billion while the January
deficit, originally reported as $12.4 billion, was lowered by the
seasonal adjustment to $11.3 billion.
   Government statisticians hope that the seasonal adjustments, by
smoothing out the month-to-month volatility will ease some of the
extreme reactions financial markets have had to the monthly trade
figures.
   Bad trade figures were blamed for adding to the pessimistic mood
right before last October's stock market crash. Just two months ago
the original report on the February deficit, which was much higher
than had been expected, sent the Dow Jones industrial average down
by 101 points, its fifth worst loss ever.
   The seasonal adjustments will cover about 80 percent of U.S.
trade. One major exception will be oil imports. The government said
it could not detect any seasonal pattern to these shipments so they
will not be adjusted.
   Before 1986, the government had always adjusted the monthly
import and export figures to smooth out seasonal shipping patterns.
However, it was forced to abandon the practice when a tide of
imports overwhelmed the ability of the Customs Service to process
the trade information on a timely basis.
   In some months, the so-called carryover of late information from
previous months accounted for 50 percent of the new month's total.
That figure has now been reduced to around 3 percent per month.
</TEXT>
