<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Blair     06-09 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blair,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Senate Candidate Blair Withraws From Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas L. Blair, Republican Senate candidate
who faced a stiff race against incumbent Democrat Paul Sarbanes,
said Thursday he is withdrawing as his party's candidate.
   Blair cited ``intense pressures and business events'' in a
letter dated June 8 to Daniel Flemming, state Republican Party
chairman.
   ``I regret my present inability to conduct a full-time campaign
to retire Mr. Sarbanes from the Senate,'' Blair, 43, said in the
letter. ``He should and can be defeated, but he won't be defeated
by anything less than a full-time candidate. To my great regret, I
find I simply cannot meet that responsibility.''
   Rep. Helen Delich Bentley, state GOP national committeewoman,
and Jackie Phillips, a campaign official, had tried to persuade
Blair to delay the announcement until party leaders decide what to
do, The Evening Sun of Baltimore reported Thursday.
   Nelson Warfield, state GOP executive director, said Thursday
afternoon that no letter had been received at the party's Annapolis
office and as far as he was concerned Blair was still a candidate.
   Blair's office said he was unavailable Thursday and referred
calls to the Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee in
Washington, D.C. Blair's letter was released through that office.
   Blair, who has never run for political office, extensively used
radio and television ads in winning the March primary over eight
opponents. But he faced an uphill fight against the two-term
incumbent Sarbanes.
   A party source, quoted in The Evening Sun, said that the firm
that took over Blair's company, a health care management consulting
firm called Jurgovan & Blair, won't give him the time off to
campaign. Jurgovan & Blair became a wholly owned subsidiary of
American International Group in July 1986.
   Patricia Sutter, public relations manager for American
International in New York, said she couldn't comment.
   Blair had not voted for nearly eight years before re-registering
just prior to filing his candidacy last year. His only previous
activity with the Republican Party had been to head a fund-raising
club called the Eagles Club whose members make a $2,500
contribution to the party.
</TEXT>
