<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shevardnadze-Shamir 2ndLd-Writethru   06-09 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shevardnadze-Shamir, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0653,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Diplomats To Visit Soviet Union</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Shevardnadze statement,
Israeli consular team to visit Moscow. Pick up 3rd graf pvs: `It
was...' Trims thereafter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze said today that a team of Israeli diplomats will visit
the Soviet Union next month but said full diplomatic relations
cannot be resumed until Israel agrees to an international peace
conference on the Middle East.
   Shevardnadze made the statement to reporters after a meeting
with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel. Both men described
the session as friendly and useful but without any breakthrough or
flexibility on either side.
   The Soviet minister also said emigration of Soviet Jews was
continuing. He said there were some constraints, which he
identified as ``military secrets only.''
   ``I would not call this meeting a new stage in relations, but it
was a useful meeting,'' Shevardnadze later told a news conference.
   ``If we can convene an international conference,'' Shevardnadze
said, ``that would make it possible to settle the problems of our
diplomatic relations.''
   Shevardnadze, asked if the Soviet Union would not restore full
diplomatic relations without a U.N.-sponsored conference, answered,
``Yes.'' He said a conference was the only way to reach a
comprehensive settlement of the Middle East problem.
   Shamir told reporters the hour and 50-minute session was ``very
friendly, productive and useful.'' But he stood firm against an
international peace conference.
   Shamir told Israeli reporters that a consular team would visit
the Soviet Union in the second half of July and indicated it would
issue visas to Soviet Jews who wish to emigrate.
   A Soviet consular team earlier visited Israel and this would be
a reciprocal visit.
   But Shevardnadze, asked if the team would issue visas, said,
``No.''
   It was Shamir's first meeting with a Soviet official since 1984,
when he met Foreign Minister Andrei Gromyko. Shevardnadze has met
Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, who takes a more flexible
position on the Middle East.
   Diplomats said the meeting could signal a new warming of
Soviet-Israeli relations and reflected the increased Soviet
interest in improved ties and increased influence in the Middle
East.
   Shamir said it would be difficult for the Soviet Union to play a
constructive role in a Middle East settlement without having
diplomatic relations with Israel. The Soviet Union broke relations
during the 1967 Middle East War.
   The Israeli prime minister said the two discussed the Middle
East situation, the state of Soviet-Israeli relations, the problem
of emigration of Soviet Jews, the arms race and arms reduction.
   He gave no details but said, ``I think there will be some
further discussions on the same problems.''
   The Soviet Union sought the meeting with Shamir in its first
contact with the conservative leader. Shamir has opposed a Soviet
call for a Middle East peace conference and the exchange of
Israeli-occupied Arab lands for peace. Peres has been more
conciliatory.
   Israel favors direct talks with her Arab neighbors and officials
say an international conference is an excuse for not negotiating
directly with Israel. It says it will not accept any imposed
settlement.
   Israel is opposed to inclusion of the Palestine Liberation
Organization in any conference, while most nations regard the PLO
as the only legitimate representative of the Palestinian people.
</TEXT>
