<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin Bjt   06-09 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin, Bjt,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeltsin To Attend Conference That May Become Battleground For
Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the Communist Party firebrand
and fallen protege of Mikhail S. Gorbachev, has been elected to
attend a party conference where he and other reformers may square
off against conservatives over Gorbachev's reforms.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Thursday
that Yeltsin will attend this month's 19th Communist Party
Conference.
   The presence of the outspoken, acid-tongued Yeltsin, who was
ousted in November as Moscow party boss, may make for lively debate
at the nationwide conference, the party's first in 47 years.
   The election of Yeltsin to the party conference continues the
roller-coaster career of the 57-year-old Russian who was fired as
Moscow party boss and stripped of his post as a non-voting member
of the Politburo because of a speech he gave to the Central
Committee in October.
   Prominent advocates of Gorbachev's reform drive allege that
middle-echelon apparatchiks in the 20-million member Communist
Party have maneuvered to bar many Gorbachev allies from the meeting.
   The newspaper of the Moscow city party, Moskovskaya Pravda,
complained Thursday that ``election of the candidates has not
everywhere been conducted in the atmosphere of broad openness.''
The nominating procedure should be changed because some party and
non-party members ``could not voice their opinions,'' it said.
   The conference is considered crucial because it will consider
potentially radical changes that remove vestiges of Stalinism from
the Soviet political and legal system. Those changes could be in
doubt if conservatives dominate among the 5,000 delegates. The
conference is scheduled to convene in Moscow June 28.
   Among changes they will consider is a proposed limit on the
terms of Communist Party officials, who have been virtually assured
of lifetime tenure.
   However, a set of proposals approved by the party's
policy-making Central Committee, published on May 26, advocates a
limit of two five-year terms for all party officials, including
Gorbachev, the party's general secretary.
   Such provisions, as well as Gorbachev's campaign for
``perestroika,'' or economic and social restructuring, threaten the
power and privilege of many party officials.
   The contest for election to the 19th Party Conference has been
like no other party balloting in memory, with disputes openly aired
in official media, a petition drive on behalf of one reformist
candidate in Moscow's Pushkin Square, and a street rally in
Leningrad that reportedly drew 1,500 people.
   Prominent pro-Gorbachev supporter Tatyana Zaslavskaya, a
sociologist, charged Friday that because of conservative
bureaucrats' maneuvering, ``the most pronounced advocates of
perestroika were not selected'' as delegates to the conference.
   That evening, the Moscow party leadership put Zaslavskaya and
some other outspoken Gorbachev supporters back on the ballot as
candidates to help fill the 319 delegate slots from Moscow.
Zaslavskaya and several others were not elected, but other
prominent perestroika advocates were, including filmmaker Elem
Klimov and economist Leonid Abalkin.
   The Politburo, the party's ruling body, acted Monday to make
sure the views of rank-and-file Communists are represented at the
conference, in an apparent move to further short-circuit the
influence of middle-level officials.
   In an official communique, the Politburo instructed local party
committees to collect proposals from the grassroots to to make sure
they will be taken up. Yeltsin's October speech criticized the No.
2 man in the Soviet leadership, Yegor K. Ligachev, and complained
that Gorbachev's program for social and economic change was moving
too slowly.
   He gave several interviews to Western television networks last
week during the Soviet-American summit, solidifying his reputation
for speaking his mind freely about highly controversial matters. In
one interview, he called for Ligachev to resign because he was
blocking reforms.
   A week after being fired from his Moscow party job, Yeltsin was
named first deputy chairman of the State Building Committee.
   Yeltsin was named a delegate from Karelia, an autonomous Soviet
republic north of Leningrad and near the Finnish border. Yeltsin
has no known contacts with Karelia, but Gerasimov, speaking at a
government news briefing, said there was no requirement in party
rules that a conference delegate live or work in the area he is
chosen to represent.
   By calling a party conference, Gorbachev is using an instrument
that was last used, and then discarded, by Stalin. The party's
nominally supreme body is the congress, which meets every five
years. The last party congress, the 27th, took place in 1986.
</TEXT>
