<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JusticeCosts     06-09 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice Costs,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Lists The Costs of Justice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It costs an average of $118,200 a year to
protect a federal witness and $35,500 to conduct a state or federal
wiretap, the Justice Department said Thursday in a report on crime
and justice.
   The study by the Bureau of Justice Statistics also found that it
costs $13,200 a year to house a federal prisoner and that crime
victims who receive compensation under various state programs are
awarded an average of $3,000 apiece.
   The U.S. Marshals Service operates the witness security program
for 5,200 people who testify for the government in major criminal
cases and, facing possible reprisals, are given new identities and
relocated at government expense.
   Some $46 billion in federal, state and local taxes was spent on
both criminal and civil justice system in the United States in
1985, the report said, reiterating a figure published in an earlier
study.
   The data, based on information gathered from 1980 to 1986, was
issued at a news conference where Attorney General Edwin Meese III
underscored the impact of crime.
   Meese referred to earlier studies that showed almost every
American will be the victim of a theft during a lifetime and that
if crime continues at current levels, five of every six people will
be the victim of an attempted or completed crime of violence.
</TEXT>
