<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Chronology     06-09 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Chronology,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Look At How The Nicaraguan Peace Process Evolved</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The moves toward peace by Nicaragua
and the rebels stemmed from the regional peace plan signed in
August by the presidents of Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala,
Costa Rica and Honduras.
   The following is a chronology of the events in Nicaragua to
bring about an end to the nation's more than 6-year-old civil war.
   Nov. 6, 1987 _ President Daniel Ortega asks Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo to mediate indirect talks between representatives of
the Sandinistas and the U.S.backed rebels, known as Contras.
   Dec. 3 _ The first round of indirect talks is held in the
Dominican Republic.
   Dec. 21 _ The second round of indirect talks takes place, again
in the Dominican Republic.
   Jan. 16, 1988 _ Ortega, at a meeting in Costa Rica of the five
Central American presidents, announces direct talks with the
Contras mediated by the cardinal.
   Jan. 28 _ The first direct talks are held in Costa Rica.
   Feb. 18 _ The second round of talks last only one day and are
broken off by Obando y Bravo, who cites the lack of flexibility by
both sides. The Cardinal then calls for the talks to include
democratic reforms.
   March 2 _ After a series of letters between the cardinal and the
president, Ortega removes Obando y Bravo from his post as mediator
and calls for face-to-face talks. He names his brother, Gen.
Humberto Ortega, as the head of the Sandinista delegation.
   March 8 _ The Contras back out of talks set for the following
day, citing a lack of preparation. The two sides later agree to
meet in the southern border post at Sapoa March 21.
   March 21 _ The two sides meet face-to-face for the first time in
Nicaraguan territory. Each announces a halt to offensive military
operations.
   March 23 _ The Sandinista leaders and the Contra representatives
announce cease-fire plan.
   March 27 _ The first 100 political prisoners are freed.
   March 28 _ Technical teams from the Sandinistas and the Contras
meet at Sapoa again to work out the mechanics of the cease-fire.
   April 1 _ The formal truce begans.
   April 4 _ Another round of unsuccessful technical talks were
held at Sapoa.
   April 14 _ The third round of technical talks begins.
   April 15 _ The Contra leaders come to Managua for the first time
to hold three days of high-level talks with the Sandinistas.
   April 28 _ The second go at talks in the capital were held.
   May 26 _ Both sides meet for three days of meetings in Managua.
The Sandinistas offered a proposal following a Contra demand for
democratic reforms.
   May 31 _ The 60 day truce formally ends. The Sandinistas
unilaterally extended it until June 30. The Contras agree to
prolong the cease-fire until June 9.
   June 7 _ The two sides hold the fourth attempt at talks. The
Contras said they would not resume meetings if no agreement was
reached. The Sandinistas offer a compromise plan calling for
democratic reforms before full disarmament by Oct. 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
