<DOCNO> AP880609-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   06-09 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, Four Wounded In West Bank Clashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Motorist who died not included in 2d graf death count</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers killed a Palestinian and
wounded four on Thursday, one of the most violent recent days in
the occupied lands, and Arabs mounted another general strike to
begin the seventh month of their rebellion.
   At least 203 Palestinians have been killed and more than 5,000
injured since the uprising began Dec. 8, and 5,000 Arabs are in
prison. An Israeli soldier and a Jewish settler also have been
slain.
   Stores were closed and public transport halted Thursday in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and in Arab east Jerusalem, but
the army said many Palestinians ignored the general strike.
   A 40-year-old Arab motorist died of a heart attack after his car
was stoned as he passed the Dheishe refugee camp near Bethlehem,
the army said. Israel radio said camp residents stoned several
Arab-owned cars, apparently to enforce compliance with the strike.
   The radio quoted military officials it did not identify as
saying Thursday was one of the most violent days since the level of
protest began to decline in May.
   In an attempt to quell violence, the army put eight refugee
camps and towns under curfews that confined nearly nearly 10
percent of the 1.5 million Palestinians in occupied territories to
their homes.
   A report by six army doctors on army methods in Gaza accused
soldiers of misusing tear gas by firing it into closed spaces.
   It also said use of high-velocity bullets that can cause
devastating injuries is unjustified in dispersing protests. The
army will not say whether it uses such ammunition.
   At Khezaa village in the southern Gaza Strip, the army razed the
home of a Palestinian accused of trying to firebomb a building
Thursday that houses the local council appointed by Israeli
authorities.
   ``The message of demolishing the house must be clear to
everybody. Anybody who tries to harm these people (appointed Arab
officials) will be caught ... and severely punished,'' the army
commander of the southern Gaza Strip said on Israel radio. He was
identified only as Col. Yitzhkad.
   The unsuccessful attack occurred two days after the attempted
assassination by stabbing of Hassan Tawil, 74, the mayor Israel
appointed for El Bireh in the West Bank. Palestinian underground
leaders have demanded that all municipal officials appointed by
Israel resign.
   Israeli military officials in the West Bank said many students
and Palestinians who work in Israel ignored the strike called by
the United Leadership of the Uprising, which is led by the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``School attendance was about 70 percent Thursday, compared to
nearly 100 percent Wednesday,'' said Olivier Rafowicz, a spokesman
for the military government.
   Army radio said masked men entered West Bank schools Thursday
and urged students to leave classes and demonstrate. Palestinian
leaders had asked students to boycott classes.
   Spot checks showed several schools closed, including some in
east Jerusalem and Ramallah.
   Rafowicz said most of the 45,000 West Bank Arabs working in
Israel reported to their jobs. He had no figures for Gaza.
   Arab doctors said soldiers killed Ahmed Hassan Hawari, 17, with
a bullet in the head in Sebastiya village near Nablus. The army
said Hawari was standing on a terrace and an officer shot him when
the youth raised a large rock, apparently to throw at soldiers.
   Dozens of protesters attacked soldiers with bottles and stones
in the Nablus market and the troops opened fire, wounding two, the
army reported.
   Hospital officials said soldiers shot an 18-year-old Palestinian
and a 12-year-old girl in the legs at Tulkarem. The army confirmed
one wounded.
   The team of Israeli doctors organized by Dedi Zucker, a
left-wing member of Parliament, said high-velocity bullets disperse
in the body and shatter bones.
   ``They work on the principle of the dumdum, so it is much more
damaging. The bone fragments virtually act as bullets in the
body,'' said Dr. Ruhama Marton. Her reference was to soft-nosed
bullets first made at the Dumdum Arsenal near Calcutta, India.
   According to the report, such bullets produced two
quadriplegics, 13 paraplegics and 20 cases of serious internal
injuries.
   The doctors accused soldiers of misusing tear gas by firing into
closed spaces but said they could not determine whether tear gas
had caused miscarriages.
   Bill Lee of the U.N. relief agency said last week that tear gas
fired into confined spaces, had killed 11 Palestinians and caused
dozens of miscarriages.
</TEXT>
