<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GorillaMyDreams     06-09 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorilla My Dreams,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colossus to Get Gorilla Girlfriend From St. Louis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULF BREEZE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colossus will get his first glimpse of
another gorilla in more than 20 years when his gorilla girlfriend
arrives next week from St. Louis on a breeding loan, a zoo official
said Thursday.
   Colossus, billed as the largest lowland gorilla in captivity at
6-foot-2 and more than 550 pounds, hasn't seen another member of
his species since infancy, when he was captured in West Africa.
   Colossus and his soon-to-be girlfriend, Muke, are both 22, prime
breeding age for such apes, said Pat Quinn, director of The Zoo,
which is near this Pensacola suburb in western Florida.
   Muke, pronounced Moo-key, arrives Wednesday.
   ``Have I got a girl for him,'' Quinn joked.
   To prepare Colossus for his blind date, scientists from the
University of West Florida have been showing him videotapes of
gorillas.
   ``He did respond,'' Quinn said. ``He was most interested in
gorillas that interacted with humans because that's what he is used
to.''
   Colossus has been the star attraction at The Zoo since he took
his first step into the outdoors at a gorilla compound March 18. He
came to the zoo from Benson's Animal Park in Hudson, N.H., where he
had been kept in a small indoor cage since his capture.
   An effort in New Hampshire to produce offspring from Colossus
through artificial insemination failed because the huge ape wasn't
very sexually active. Quinn said Colossus has recently shown signs
of more sexual interest.
   Gorillas are an endangered species and Colossus is seen as
particularly attractive for breeding because he was captured in the
wild and will introduce a new gene pool into the community of
captive apes.
</TEXT>
