<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Tatars     06-09 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Tatars,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crimean Tatars Criticize Government For Denying Them Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Yeltsin, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday refused to grant an
autonomous homeland to Tatars forcibly deported from their Crimean
homeland during World War II. A member of the ethnic group said it
would protest the decision.
   A government commission said in a report ``there are no grounds
for establishing'' autonomy for Tatars, Turkic-speaking descendants
of the Mongols.
   ``Now we don't have any faith in the government,'' Zeni Ametov,
a 35-year-old Tatar, said in a telephone interview from his Moscow
home.
   Ametov said he was ``now in a state of shock'' and said Crimean
Tatars tentatively are planning June 20 demonstrations in Moscow
and other cities to protest the decision.
   The government announcement was a major setback for the ethnic
group, whose members have been agitating for a return from what
they consider exile in Central Asia to their ancestral lands on the
Black Sea.
   A government commission headed by President Andrei A. Gromyko
was formed to study Tatar grievances after activists staged an
extraordinary 21-hour demonstration in Red Square last summer.
   The commission's report, carried by the official Tass news
agency, criticized groups of Crimean Tatars for ``insisting that
the issue of creating a Crimean autonomy be resolved first.''
   It said there has been greater employment and educational
opportunities in the past year.
   The issue of disgruntled ethnic minorities has been a sensitive
one for Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who has acknowledged
that appeasing the country's more than 100 national groups is among
the Soviet Union's most pressing problems.
   The Crimean Tatars, as well as ethnic Armenians, have taken
advantage of greater tolerance under Gorbachev to stage public
demonstrations.
   The Tatars were deported from their Crimean homes after Josef
Stalin accused them of collaborating with the Nazis during World
War II.
   Tatar activists say about 110,000 people, or 46 percent of their
population, died during or soon after the deportation. The rest
were resettled in the Ural Mountains, Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan.
   The Tatars, who today number about 300,000, were rehabilitated
in 1967 but still not permitted to return en masse to the Crimean
Peninsula.
   The government statement noted that the Soviet Union has eased
restrictions that barred some Tatars from returning to the Crimea.
   ``Since the middle of 1987, about 2,500 Crimean Tatars have been
granted resident permits and fixed up with jobs in the Crimea,''
the statement said.
   In addition, ``extra conditions have been created to develop
their national culture and opportunities broadened to study their
native language.''
   But Ametov said Crimean Tatars who have moved back to their
homeland have done so solely on their own initiative after lengthy
battles with authorities.
   ``There are some improvements, but that is only through the
efforts of individuals,'' Ametov said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
