<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf of last item, datelined New York, to CORRECT
by deleting reference to Nyro writing ``Up, Up and Away.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Laura Nyro credits her
decision to quit smoking last summer for her return to the concert
stage after 10 years.
   ``It made my instrument very rich and stable,'' she said.
``Also, whenever you quit any addiction, your life is new again.
You feel if you can free yourself that way, you can do almost
anything.''
   Nyro, 41, said her summer tour, beginning Thursday night in
suburban Rochester, is dedicated to the animal rights movement.
   Nyro was 17 when the singing group Peter, Paul and Mary
popularized her song ``And When I Die.'' Other hits she wrote
include the Fifth Dimension's ``Stoned Soul Picnic.''
</TEXT>
