<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CanceledGraduation     06-09 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canceled Graduation,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senior Says Remarks Were Misinterpreted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school senior says he told classmates
their graduation would be memorable, but he just intended a
practical joke, not the violence feared by administrators who
canceled final exams and graduation exercises.
   Neal Loeslein, 18, who witnessed a friend's suicide, denied that
some students at Fairview High School, troubled by the death, had
made a suicide pact.
   ``There wasn't one. That was just a rumor,'' he told The
Pittsburgh Press in a story published Thursday.
   Officials in Fairview, an affluent, suburban Erie County
district, decided earlier this week to cancel Wednesday's finals,
Thursday's baccalaureate service and Sunday's graduation for about
150 seniors because they felt they could not guarantee the safety
of students and guests.
   An administrator who spoke to Erie County newspapers on
condition he not be identified said psychologists believed the
threat of violence during graduation was real and they advised the
board to cancel all events that would give the troubled students a
forum to carry out their threats.
   Loeslein told the Press he was the student present at
Christmastime at the home of another senior who fatally shot
himself in the head with a .44-caliber Magnum. He said talk of a
suicide pact surfaced soon afterward and that the talk apparently
intensified two weeks ago when he told classmates in a general way,
``This is a graduation we will all remember.''
   Loeslein said he had planned to play a practical joke at the
ceremony but had not decided what it would be. He said his remarks
were misconstrued by classmates and officials.
   An attempt by The Associated Press to reach Loeslein by
telephone Thursday was unsuccessful because the family has an
unlisted number.
   Requests for comment on Loeslein's remarks were referred to the
school board solicitor, Frank Kroto, who did not return phone
messages Thursday.
   After the suicide, school officials called in experts from the
University of Pittsburgh's Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic
to talk to students. Loeslein said his own counselor told school
officials he was doing well, but the Pittsburgh counselors warned
he was still troubled.
   Loeslein told the Press he has had trouble with school officials
for repeated rule violations. His mother, Shirley Loeslein, said
some teachers and students have an unfair opinion of her son.
   ``After (the student died), the paranoia set in,'' she said.
``They were afraid that he (Loeslein) might explode or something.''
   School administrators who spoke to The Erie Daily Times and The
Erie Morning News said the Pittsburgh counselors diagnosed at least
two unidentified students as suicidal and possibly homicidal.
   ``We went from trying to protect several students from
themselves to trying to protect the entire class and their parents
from these disturbed kids,'' one high-ranking administrator said.
   Kroto said several officials had received death threats, but he
would not be more specific.
   State police Capt. Douglas L. Greenfield in nearby Girard said
police were not asked for assistance until Wednesday, and a
spokesman said Thursday no complaint about any death threats had
been filed.
   State police said the homes of threatened administrators were
the object of increased routine patrols, and school board President
Barbara Junker said the administrators have been offered whatever
private protection they believe appropriate.
   Loeslein and other students said they know of at least one
administrator, in charge of discipline, who was the object of
written and verbal statements that could be misconstrued as threats.
   ``I think they are totally overreacting,'' Loeslein said.
   Senior class officers donated their $800 class fund, much of it
intended for flowers and other graduation costs, to create a
special suicide prevention fund to be administered by the school's
guidance department.
   ``The officers thought this was the best way to do something
positive,'' class President Gary Guzzardo said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
