<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NeedleExchange Bjt   06-09 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Needle Exchange, Bjt,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Say Needle-Exchange Program Like Pouring Gasoline on Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYNN WHEELER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Announcement of the first program to
distribute hypodermic needles to drug users has sparked a debate
between those who say the plan will curb the spread of AIDS and
those who say it will encourage drug use.
   ``It's like trying to put out a fire with gasoline,'' said Lon
Mabon, executive director of the Oregon Citizens Alliance, a
conservative political group opposed to the project.
   Outside-In, a Portland social service agency, will use a $67,000
grant from the American Foundation for AIDS Research to conduct the
nation's first test to determine if exchanging used needles for
new, sanitary ones will curb the spread of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome. Sharing needles has been one of the main ways
for transmitting the human immunodeficiency virus that causes AIDS.
   To qualify for the program, a person will have to admit
intravenous drug use, show identifiable injection marks and have a
needle to exchange for a new one. Participants, who can remain
anonymous, will receive periodic blood tests and counseling.
   ``In a way it's a hook to get drug users reconnected to the
helping system, while seeing if it doesn't decrease the spread of
the HIV virus,'' said Bradley J. Woodworth, president of
Outside-In's board of directors.
   But Mabon criticized it as sending a wrong message. ``It seems
very contradictory on one side of our government and society to say
drugs are wrong ... and then to be handling out needles,'' he said.
   Mayor Bud Clark said the needle exchange is ``worrisome'' and
might be interpreted as encouraging drug use at a time when the
city is making great efforts to eradicate drugs. He called for
researchers to make public results of the program as soon as
possible.
   Gov. Neil Goldschmidt also has some reservations about the
program, said press aide Gregg Kantor. ``Any time you appear to
make these drugs easier to take, it worries him,'' Kantor said.
   That doesn't necessarily mean the governor opposes the idea,
Kantor said.
   ``We'll have to wait and see what the results show, and whether
it makes sense or not,'' Kantor said. ``It may, in fact, help
reduce the spread of AIDS.''
   Rosanna Creighton, executive director of Citizens for a Drug
Free Oregon, a group that lobbies for anti-drug laws, questioned
whether drug addicts would participate in the program.
   ``If you look at the history of their lifestyle and behavior
patterns, it doesn't look like a strong possibility,'' she said.
   Woodworth said a similar program in Scotland showed drug users
were willing to travel up to two miles to get clean needles.
   ``There may be some who are totally unsalvageable. We're trying
to find out if there's a percentage of people whose behavior can be
modified.
   Dr. Lester Wright, the state's top public health officer, said
he thinks the needle exchange program is worth a try.
   Wright, who is deputy administrator of the state Health
Division, rejected arguments that the program will encourage drug
use.
   ``Drug use is unhealthy, it's stupid and it's illegal, but it is
happening,'' he said. ``I don't see a need to make it any more
fatal than it already is.''
   ``Because of the AIDS problem, I think we have to look at
anything that could reduce its spread and evaluate whether it
works,'' Wright said.
   Several critics expressed fears that the program would hurt
Portland's reputation.
   ``This whole free needle thing is just one more nail in the
coffin as far as our image,'' said mayoral candidate Ron Still, a
former police chief.
   Legal opposition has been holding up a similar program in New
York City. In Massachusetts, state lawmakers on Wednesday debated a
needle distribution program in Boston.
   Woodworth said Portland's comparatively low AIDS infection rate
among drug users, 5 percent compared to 60 percent in New York,
makes the city an ideal location for the project.
   ``This is a city where it's not too late to see if it makes a
difference,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
