<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MoneyLaundering     06-09 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Laundering,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Bill To Help Track Drug Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee approved
legislation Thursday to make it more difficult for drug dealers and
other criminals to hide their profits.
   The bill would require banks to file transaction reports for all
cashiers' checks, money orders and travelers' checks of $3,000 or
more. Now, banks need to file such reports on transactions of
$10,000 or more.
   The measure would also authorize law enforcement agencies to
inspect the records of bank insiders suspected of being involved in
criminal activity against the bank without the targeted people
being tipped off. The Financial Privacy Act now requires such
persons to be told when agencies are looking at their record.
   The legislation would also authorize the treasury secretary to
target an individual institution in a geographical area for
additional recordkeeping where drug activity is heavy and large
cash sums are being generated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
