<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Arms Sale,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon OKs $300 Missile Sale to West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress on Thursday it
had approved the sale of 1,600 Maverick air-to-ground missiles to
West Germany.
   Assuming no congressional objections, the Pentagon said the West
Germans would be provided 1,500 Maverick missiles plus another 100
training missiles at an estimated cost of $300 million.
   The U.S. Air Force will be responsible for overseeing the
transaction and the prime contractors will be the Hughes Aircraft
Co. in Tucson, Ariz., and the Raytheon Co. in Lowell, Mass.
   ``The (Maverick) missiles are considered vital to the Federal
Republic of Germany's stated goal to increase ammunition stocks to
defend against Eastern Bloc armor,'' the Pentagon said.
