<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Somalia     06-09 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Somalia,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aid Workers Describe Heavy Casualties, Executions In Somalia
Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Somali troops executed dozens of men and
destroyed homes of suspected rebel sympathizers in a town where at
least 1,000 people were killed or wounded in recent fighting,
foreign aid workers said Thursday.
   The workers, who were airlifted from the northern Somali town of
Hargeisa and arrived in Nairobi on Wednesday, could not give an
accurate count of the number killed or wounded in fighting that
began with a moonlit rebel attack May 31. They also could not say
how many were civilians, soldiers or rebels.
   However, the accounts depicted bloodier hostilities than have
been admitted so far by the pro-Western government of Maj. Gen.
Mohammed Siad Barre.
   Jean Metenier, 28, a French technician working for the German
Emergency Doctors Humanitarian Organization, said he saw dozens of
bodies around Hargeisa, Somalia's second largest town, including
almost two dozen corpses of young men in civilian garb found behind
his house.
   ``The soldiers would make summary trials, and then execute
them,'' said Metenier, whose house was next to that of Gen. Mohamed
``Morgan'' Siyad, Somalia's northern army commander and Barre's
brother-in-law. ``They were all in civilian clothes and all young
men.''
   Metenier said he did not witness the executions, but heard the
gunfire and counted 21 bodies between May 31 and June 2.
   He said troops driving bulldozers scooped up five of the bodies
behind his house one day and dumped them on a street corner a block
away.
   Mentenier also said about 1,000 wounded were admitted to the
Hargeisa hospital in the first five days of clashes.
   ``Probably most of them were soldiers,'' Metenier said of the
wounded. ``I think in town, a lot of people have been injured,
mostly civilians.''
   Six evacuees seated with Metenier at Nairobi's Norfolk Hotel
corroborated his accounts of fighting, atrocities and the
destruction of homes of suspected rebel sympathizers, but they
would not speak individually to reporters.
   An American aid worker, Ron Wieland of Dazey, North Dakota, said
a shell went through the window of his house when government troops
chased rebel forces up a dry river bed running alongside his
compound. Wieland, 36, said no one in his house was injured but
that ``the situation warranted evacuation.''
   Metenier said the fighting was fiercest in the town center and
on Gennet, one of the nearby hills. ``The government was shelling
daily with tanks, bazookas and MiG-19 aircraft,'' he said.
   He said about 5,000 people lived on the slopes of the hill, the
site of the state National Refugee Commission compound.
   Food stores, other supplies, trucks and equipment were kept in
the compound where the commission coordinated the distribution of
relief aid to 350,000 Ethiopian refugees in 15 northern Somali
camps including Hargeisa, he said.
   He said that even if emergency stocks and transportation had not
been destroyed in the government bombardment of the hill, the
fighting had closed off the road to the camps, cutting off the
refugees' lifeline.
   Metenier also said rebels had taken control of a small power
plant about 12 miles outside Hargeisa which operated the water
pump. He said Hargeisa had been without water since the first few
days of the rebel attack.
   The rebels intensified their offensive in May, one month after
an agreement between Ethiopia and Somalia in which the Horn of
Africa nations agreed to cease support and sanctuary to insurgents
fighting each other's government.
   The rebels of the Somali National Movement, which took up arms
against the government in 1981, claim to control Barao, a town of
50,000 people 110 miles east of Hargeisa, the Hargeisa airport and
three nearby garrison towns.
   Siad Barre seized power in a 1969 military coup. The United
States is Somalia's staunchest ally.
   The evacuees who spoke were among 165 foreign aid and relief
workers airlifted from Hargeisa last Friday and Saturday in a
U.N.-coordinated airlift that angered the government.
</TEXT>
