<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MIAsIdentified 2ndLd-Writethru a0717 06-09 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MIAs Identified, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0717,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Four Men Killed in Vietnam Identified</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 2nd graf with Carlucci participation;
inserts one graf after pvs 3rd graf, ``The four were,'' with other
remains awaiting identification</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army laboratory in Hawaii has positively
identified four sets of remains as Air Force fliers missing from
the Vietnam war, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   The four, three of whom died in a 1966 plane crash, were
identified by the Army's Central Identification Laboratory in
Honolulu and were transported to California on Thursday after a
full military honors ceremony at Hickam Air Force Base, Hawaii.
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci participated in the honors
ceremony shortly after his arrival at Hickam from visits in South
Korea and Japan following the Moscow summit.
   Carlucci, Adm. Ronald Hays, commander of U.S. Pacific forces,
and other military leaders stood on a reviewing stand as the four
flag-draped transfer containers were carried past an honor guard
and color guard to a C-141 transport plane.
   Carlucci made no remarks during the 25-minute ceremony.
   The four were among a group of 17 remains repatriated by Vietnam
to the United States on March 2, the Pentagon said in a statement.
The Army lab is still attempting to identify the others from that
group.
   Also awaiting identificaiton are 27 sets of rmeains that were
repatriated on April 6.
   The Pentagon identified the men as:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Air Force Lt. Col. Vincent A. Chiarello, who was born on Aug.
30, 1939, and listed his home of record as New York City.
   _Air Force Lt. Col. Bernard Conklin, who was born on Feb. 27,
1932, and listed his home of record as Stony Point, N.Y.
   _Air Force Chief Master Sgt. James S. Hall, who was born on Oct.
5, 1935, and listed his home of record as Greensboro, N.C.
   Chiarello, Conklin and Hall were three of eight men aboard an
RC-47 reconnaissance plane when it was reportedly attacked by a MiG
jet fighter. According to Pentagon records, the plane went down
over Son La-Hoa Binh Province after a radio distress call.
   _Air Force Lt. Col. Robert R. Gregory, lost over North Vietnam
on Dec. 2, 1966. Gregory was born on March 22, 1932, and listed his
home of record as Cape Girardeau, Mo.
   According to the Pentagon, Gregory was the pilot of an RF-4C
reconnaissance jet that was shot down over North Vietnam. His
navigator survived the crash and spent more than six years as a
prisoner-of-war.
   With the latest identifications, 2,400 Americans remain listed
as missing in Indochina as a result of the Vietnam war, of whom
1,762 are listed as missing in either North or South Vietnam.
   All told, the remains of 156 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States and subsequently identified by the laboratory
since the end of the war.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the cooperation of the
Socialist Republic of Vietnam that resulted in the recovery and
return of these remains and hopes it is representative of continued
cooperation to resolve this long-standing humanitarian issue,'' the
Pentagon said in its statement.
</TEXT>
