<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolUniforms     06-09 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Uniforms,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students at Two Public Schools to Don Uniforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The best-dressed students at two public elementary
schools could be in blue-and-white uniforms this fall as principals
try to stifle fashion rivalry and tighten discipline.
   The Dade County School Board adopted the voluntary program
Wednesday for the Martin Luther King and Charles R. Drew elementary
schools in Liberty City.
   A study by the school principals found overwhelming acceptance
of the uniforms, and school officials anticipate a high rate of
cooperation.
   Drew and King are the first public schools in Dade to adopt
uniforms, but the practice has taken hold elsewhere. In Baltimore,
where four public schools adopted uniforms last year, the outfits
were so successful in raising self-esteem, ending fashion wars and
improving discipline that 35 more schools will follow suit this
fall.
   The uniforms at Drew and King will be jumpers or skirts and
blouses for girls and trousers, shirts and ties for boys. Uniforms
for low-income students will be donated by private companies.
   ``When they wake up in the morning, when they look in that
closet, they are going to know what they're going to wear and
they're going to come to school focusing on the basic skills,''
said Fred Morley, principal at Drew.
</TEXT>
