<HEAD>Cardinal Celebrates Mass in Moscow Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York and more than a
dozen other clergy celebrated Mass on Thursday at Moscow's only
Roman Catholic Church, the cardinal's secretary said.
   Monsignor James McCarthy said O'Connor, four other cardinals and
10 priests visiting Moscow for the celebration of the 1,000th
anniversary of Chrisitianity in this land, said Mass for about 70
people at downtown Moscow's St. Louis Church.
   O'Connor, who arrived with a Vatican delegation Wednesday, also
traveled to Zagorsk, a city about 35 miles northeast of the Soviet
capital for the closing session of a four-day Russian Orthodox
Church council dedicated to the millennium, McCarthy said.
   While in Zagorsk, the site of a medieval monastery that now
houses a seminary, the 68-year-old O'Connor met church officials of
various faiths including Metropolitan Filaret of Minsk, head of
external affairs for the Russian Orthodox Church, and Archbishop of
Canterbury Robert Runcie, the cardinal's secretary said.
   The Roman Catholic delegation to the millennium was honored at a
dinner given by Russian Orthodox church leaders Thursday evening.
   ``It was a very open, warm and cordial dinner with an honest
exchange'' between the two delegations, McCarthy said.
   Celebrations of the anniversary of Christianity continue in
Moscow through Sunday and then move to Leningrad, Kiev and Vladimir.
