<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Spy     06-09 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Spy,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Clears Way For Morison Imprisonment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday cleared the way
for the imprisonment of former U.S. intelligence analyst Samuel
Loring Morison, convicted of espionage and theft.
   The court, by a 6-3 vote, denied Morison's emergency request to
remain free pending a formal appeal of his conviction.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist had turned down Morison's
request on June 2 and Morison's lawyers then turned to Justice
William J. Brennan for help.
   After Brennan referred the request to the full court, a federal
trial judge in Baltimore ruled that Morison could remain free until
June 15 while the full court considered his bid to stay out of
prison.
   Presumably, U.S. District Judge Joseph Young's order now will be
set aside and Morison will have to begin serving a two-year term.
   The Supreme Court order issued Thursday was one sentence. It
said, ``The application for continued release from detention
presented to Justice Brennan and by him referred to the court is
denied.''
   Justices Brennan, Thurgood Marshall and Harry A. Blackmun
dissented. They voted to let Morison remain free until the court
acts on his formal appeal.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the conviction in
April, rejecting Morison's arguments that Congress intended laws
against spying to protect against the distribution of classified
material to a foreign government rather than leaks to the press.
   Morison, grandson of the late Pulitzer Prize-winning naval
historian Samuel Eliot Morison, was convicted in October 1985 of
giving to Jane's Defence Weekly photographs taken by a U.S. spy
satellite of a Soviet nuclear aircraft carrier under construction.
   Morison, who worked as a civilian for the Navy, also was
convicted of the theft of the photos and government documents
describing a May 1984 explosion at the Soviet Union's Severomorsk
naval base.
   He was sentenced to two years in prison but remained free under
$100,000 bond pending appeal.
   Prosecutors said Morison's actions endangered national security
because the photos revealed how a U.S. spy satellite worked. They
also said he leaked the photos to get a full-time job with Jane's
after doing part-time work for the military journal while employed
by the Navy.
   Defense attorneys contended Morison was trying to educate the
public about a Soviet navalbuildup and that the photos told the
Soviets nothing they had not learned already from a 1978 incident
in which the spy satellite's operations manual was sold to a Soviet
agent.
   The case is Morison vs. U.S., A-876.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
