<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0728 06-09 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0728,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to End Debate on Death for Cop-Killing Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 9th graf pvs bgng, `D'Amato's bill,' with 1 graf to show
jurisdiction; ADDS 2 grafs at end to include House Banking vote</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 69-27 Thursday to choke off a
filibuster that has blocked action on a bill permitting the death
penalty for major drug dealers who kill police officers.
   The decision sets up a vote on the bill Friday that supporters
and opponents agreed probably would result in approval.
   ``This sends the message that we're not going to tolerate the
kind of warfare we're seeing on the streets of our cities,'' Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., chief author of the bill, told his
colleagues.
   But opponents such as Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash., derided the
measure as an election-year attempt to appease public demands to do
something about illegal drugs. They also noted the death penalty
already exists in many states and it hasn't deterred drug pushers.
   ``Once again, we're going for an election-year slam dunk on
drugs,'' Evans said, noting that a similar bill was proposed in
1986. ``We're taking precipitous steps to indulge our own political
vanity.''
   Thursday's tally was nine votes more than the 60 needed to
invoke cloture, the parliamentary device used in the Senate to end
a filibuster. Opponents began an effort to talk the measure to
death after D'Amato originally attached it as an amendment to the
defense budget bill.
   But D'Amato dropped his amendment on the defense bill two weeks
ago, leading to Senate approval of that measure, in return for a
promise by Senate Democratic leaders to allow floor action on a
separate death penalty measure.
   Senate approval would send the bill to the House, where it faces
an uncertain future. It would go to the House Judiciary Committee,
which has in the past steadfastly refused to send such a measure to
the floor.
   D'Amato's bill provides that the death penalty can be imposed on
people who are convicted in federal courts of running a drug ring
and who are then separately convicted of killing law enforcement
officers or private citizens. It applies to federal laws, but could
also be followed by individual states.
   Before invoking cloture, the Senate killed, 65-31, a proposed
amendment that would have imposed a penalty of life imprisonment
without parole, instead of the death penalty, for persons convicted
under the terms of D'Amato's bill.
   While the Senate was debating, New York Mayor Edward I. Koch was
calling for the use of military forces to halt drug trafficking and
suggesting that the federal government should open tent jails in
Nevada to help relieve prison overcrowding caused by drug-related
arrests.
   ``We want the Navy with the Air Force on the high seas to
detect, apprehend and arrest drug smugglers,'' Koch told a hearing
by two House Armed Services subcommittees.
   The panels are looking at proposals approved separately by the
House and Senate to increase the military's role in the anti-drug
effort.
   Koch called for repeal of the Posse Comitatus Act, the 1878 law
barring the military from enforcing civilian laws. ``It's
ridiculous. Get rid of it!'' he said.
   He also noted prisons are too crowded now and suggested: ``The
federal government should open up tent jails ... out in Nevada.
Nevada won't like it ....''
   He was willing to split the cost with the U.S. government. ``If
the feds opened up additional jails _ as I hope that they will _
we'll pay one-third,'' Koch said. He endorsed creation of a federal
surtax with the new money to be devoted solely to anti-drug
programs.
   Meantime, President Reagan said the nation's problems with drugs
in the workplace arise partly from students who used illegal
substances in the 1960s and 1970s and who have retained
``destructive drug habits.''
   ``In many ways, our country is still paying for the erosion of
our values and the decline in self-responsibility that occurred in
the 1960s and the 1970s,'' the president said in a speech to
corporate leaders trying to drive drugs from the work site.
   ``The students of that period who used illegal drugs in high
school or college have, in many cases, taken their destructive drug
habits with them into their places of employment,'' Reagan said.
   Earlier Thursday, the House Banking Committee approved
legislation making it more difficult for drug dealers and other
criminals to hide their profits.
   The bill would require banks to file transaction reports for all
cashiers' checks, money orders and travelers' checks of $3,000 or
more. Now, banks need to file such reports on transactions of
$10,000 or more.
</TEXT>
