<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-LieDetectors     06-09 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lie Detectors,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Bill to Limit Private Employers' Use of
Lie-Detector Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed and sent to President Reagan
on Thursday legislation that would limit the use of lie-detector
tests by private employers.
   The legislation, which was approved 68-24, also would prevent
employers from taking adverse actions against employees solely on
the basis of the test results.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor
Committee, said the legislation ``will put an end to decades of
injustice.''
   Kennedy said the measure ``carefully balances the interests of
employers and employees, based on the known scientific evidence
regarding lie detectors and their potential for abuse.''
   Judy Goldberg, representing the American Civil Liberties Union,
said the bill ``will protect thousands of workers who are currently
being labeled as liars by these machines that don't work.''
   The House approved the bill last week on a 251-120 vote.
   The Office of Technology Assessment estimated that two million
polygraph tests were administered in 1987, with 90 percent given by
private employers. Most of those tested were job applicants,
although tests also were given to workers under investigation.
   Twenty-two states prohibit the tests in the private sector, and
19 regulate private use of the tests.
   The accuracy of test results has been questioned, and so has the
competency of some examiners.
   The compromise legislation _ which followed passage of separate
polygraph bills by the House and Senate _ would permit private
sector testing of applicants for only two types of jobs.
   Those applying for security guard positions could still be
tested, and so could prospective employees who would have direct
access to the manufacture, storage, distribution, or sale of
controlled substances.
   In addition, an employer could test an employee during an
ongoing investigation involving economic loss or injury to the
company.
   However, the employee must have had access to the property that
is the subject of the investigation. And the employer must have
reasonable suspicion that the worker was involved in the incident.
   Before the test began, the worker would have to have been given
specific information about the incident under investigation.
   Only the federal government would be permitted to administer
tests to those employed by, assigned to, or detailed to the
nation's intelligence agencies and to FBI contract employees.
   To protect the rights of workers, the bill would prohibit an
employee from being discharged, dismissed, disciplined,
discriminated against, or denied employment or promotion solely on
the basis of the test or solely because of his refusal to take the
test. To take action against the worker, an employer would have to
have additional supporting evidence.
   Questions on religious or political beliefs could not be asked.
Questions would have to be submitted to the test subject in writing
before the examination. The examinee could end the test at any time.
   Qualification standards would be set for examiners, who would
need a license granted by the state, if one were required by the
state. The examiner also would have to maintain a $50,000 bond.
   The legislation would take effect six months after it became law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ImportedShrimp     06-09 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Imported Shrimp,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama Shrimp Processors Caught In `Unfortunate Bureaucratic
Snafu'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Alabama businessmen told Congress on
Thursday they were processing imported shrimp under instructions
from the Commerce Department when their plants were raided in April
by armed Customs Service agents.
   D.J. Ficarino Sr., an owner of Mobile Freezers Inc., and Joseph
E. Ladnier, president of Sea Pearl Seafood Co., said they had been
informed by Commerce officials that they could label imported
shrimp as a U.S. product once they peeled, deveined and repacked
the shrimp.
   ``If I though I was doing something illegal, I would have sure
locked up my doors and done it at night,'' Ficarino said. ``I
certainly wouldn't do it in broad daylight.''
   The Customs Service, however, decided that the two shrimp
processors, as well as a third south Alabama company, Gulf Coast
White Knight, were illegally labeling imported shrimp as a product
of the United States. And on April 13, agents raided the three
plants and seized about 600,000 pounds of shrimp worth several
million dollars.
   The shrimp processors, according to Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala.,
were caught up in an ``unfortunate bureaucratic snafu'' that
resulted from differing interpretations by two U.S. government
agencies of the same law.
   That law permits an import to be labeled as a product of the
United States if it undergoes ``substantial transformation''
between the time it is imported and the time it is placed on the
market for sale to consumers.
   The National Marine Fisheries Service, a division of the
Commerce Department, had advised shrimp processors that peeling and
deveining of shrimp constiuted a ``substantial transformation.''
The Customs Service disagreed.
   At Thursday's hearing before the House Energy and Commerce
investigations and oversight subcommittee, U.S. Attorney Jefferson
B. Sessions III of Mobile, Ala., said he decided not to prosecute
the three shrimp processors because the advice they received from
the Commerce Department removed the element of criminal intent.
   Sessions said, however, that he agreed with the Customs Service
that peeling and deveining imported shrimp does not constitute a
``substantial transformation'' of the product.
   James W. Brennan, assistant administrator for fisheries at the
Commerce Department, acknowledged his agency had provided
misleading and inaccurate information to the south Alabama
shrimpers.
   But Brennan said that for the past 35 years, shrimp processors
all along the Gulf Coast have been placing ``product of the U.S.''
labels on imported shrimp they have peeled and deveined. And he
said his department received no notification from the Customs
Service prior to the April raids that such a practice now was being
considered illegal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Stocks-Arbitration     06-09 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stocks-Arbitration,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Securities Industry Proposes Compromise on Handling Disputes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A securities industry representative offered a
compromise Thursday in an attempt to head off legislation that
would bar securities firms from requiring customers to settle
disputes through industry-sponsored arbitration.
   The finance subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee is reviewing a proposal that would prohibit firms from
forcing customers to waive their right to sue in court as a
condition of opening a brokerage account.
   William J. Fitzpatrick, general counsel of the Securities
Industry Association, said securities firms, like any other
business, have a right to set the terms under which they are
willing to do business.
   That includes the right to demand that customers sign a
so-called mandatory arbitration clause binding them to settle
disputes before an arbitration panel sponsored by a stock exchange
or other market organization, he said.
   Fitzpatrick said if there is a problem with customers
unknowingly signing such agreements, ``the industry would have no
objection'' to offering a separate document disclosing the
arbitration clause and explaining its terms.
   However, Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the
subcommittee, argued that mandatory arbitration, properly disclosed
or not, is ``inherently unfair and oppressive.''
   ``Investors, like all the rest of our citizens, believe they
have a right to their day in court,'' he said.
   Markey said a survey by the staff of the Securites and Exchange
Commission showed that 95 percent of the nation's top retail
brokerage firms require customers to sign arbitration clauses when
they borrow money from the firm on margin.
   Ninety percent of the firms require the clauses for customers
who trade options and 38 percent require the clauses for cash
accounts. An additional 32 percent intend to begin requiring the
clauses for cash accounts.
   ``No one's holding a gun to a customer's head. What is going on
is a sort of benign neglect and a hurried process where the
customer signs an arbitration clause without really knowing what he
is doing,'' said G. Richard Shell, a professor of legal studies at
the University of Pennsylvania.
   He termed the industry's argument that customers are voluntarily
choosing arbitration when they give up their right to sue ``a kind
of trick.''
   ``The industry is getting something and the customer is getting
nothing because the customer always has the right to arbitrate
regardless of whether they sign the agreement,'' Shell said.
   The legislation being considered by the subcommittee would also
bar people with connections to the industry from serving on
arbitration panels. And it would give arbitrators the power to
compel securities firms to produce documents relevant to the case.
   Boyd Page, an Atlanta arbitration attorney, said firms often
``stonewall'' document requests or produce them only at the last
minute.
   The SEC plans to vote July 7 on whether or not to endorse a ban
on mandatory arbitration clauses. Three of its five members have
said they support such a ban.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shevardnadze-Shamir     06-09 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shevardnadze-Shamir,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze, Shamir Meet; Israeli Team To Visit Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
said Thursday the Soviet Union wants to restore diplomatic
relations with Israel but will not do so until the Israelis agree
to an international conference on Middle East peace.
   He spoke to reporters after his first meeting with Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who leads Israel's right-wing Likud bloc
and firmly opposes such a conference.
   Both sides said a consular team will go the the Soviet Union
next month on the first visit by Israeli diplomats since the Soviet
Union broke diplomatic relations during the Arab-Israeli war of
1967. A Soviet consular team now is in Israel.
   Shevardnadze and Shamir said there were no breakthroughs in the
meeting, shich lasted just 10 minutes short of two hours, but
described it as friendly, productive and useful.
   It ``does not signify a new stage in relations, but it was a
useful meeting,'' Shevardnadze said. ``If we are able to convene a
conference, that would make it possible to settle the problem of
our relations with Israel.''
   He and Shamir were here for the special General Assembly session
on disarmament. It was Shamir's first session with a high Soviet
official since he met in 1984 with Andrei Gromyko, then foreign
minister.
   Israel has sought a resumption of relations for years and the
Kremlin has stepped up contacts in hopes of increasing its
influence on Middle East peace negotiations.
   The Soviet foreign minister has met with Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres, who approves of a peace conference and of trading occupied
Arab territory for peace, which Shamir opposes.
   Perez, who leads the center-left Labor Party, and Shamir are
partners and rivals in Israel's tenuous coalition government.
Elections are due in November.
   What role the consular team will play in Moscow is not clear.
Israeli officials indicated the diplomats might issue visas to
Soviet Jews wishing to emigrate, but Shamir told Israel radio he
did not know whether they would be allowed to deal with Jewish
matters.
   Shevardnadze answered ``No'' when asked whether the Israeli team
would issue visas. ``There is a certain frame in that agreement and
the Israeli prime minister and foreign minister and the group
itself are well aware of what that understanding is,'' he said
without elaborating.
   ``Our team was well received in Tel Aviv and normal conditions
were created for their work. We shall try to do likewise for the
Israeli group.''
   Emigration of Soviet Jews is continuing, he said, and ``there
are no obstacles, but some constraints.'' He identified the
constraints as ``military secrets only.''
   Shamir told Israeli reporters later that Shevardnadze said the
situation of Soviet Jews will improve and the special Communist
Party meeting scheduled for June 28 will consider the problems of
Jews.
   Answering a question about an international peace conference,
Shevardnadze said: ``Israel must accept a conference before we can
restore ties. These are inter-related elements. Let us convene a
conference and let us also hold serious discussion on settling our
relations.''
   Shamir said he told Shevardnadze, ``Our relations are not
normal. ... We want an embassy in Moscow and you should have an
embassy in Israel.'' He said Shevardnadze agreed, but said the
solution was a peace conference.
   The Israeli prime minister wants direct talks with Israel's Arab
adversaries. He contends Israel would be outnumbered at an
international conference and pressured to make concessions.
   He told the Israeli reporters it would be difficult for the
Soviet Union to play a constructive role in a Middle East
settlement without having normal relations with Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
