<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Water-Energy     06-09 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water-Energy,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves $18 Billion Spending Package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee gave
voice-vote approval Thursday to an $18.05 billion fiscal 1989
spending package for water and energy development programs.
   The bill, totalling $92 million less than President Reagan
requested, is noteworthy because it contains no money for new
construction starts by the Corps of Engineers and the Bureau of
Reclamation.
   The no-new-starts posture is identical to the stand taken by the
House last month when it approved its energy and water
appropriations bill for the year starting Oct. 1.
   Hundreds of dams, harbor improvements and irrigation systems
would continue to get money for operation and maintenance and work
would continue on dozens now under construction.
   The Senate and House bills would also apply the no-starts
stricture to the superconducting super collider, the huge
high-energy physics installation that would enable scientists to
delve deeper into the nature of matter.
   Both bills would provide $100 million to continue preliminary
research for the SSC, but they would bar the start of construction
on the multi-billion dollar project in fiscal 1989.
