<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraSuit     06-09 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Suit,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sam Hall: I'll Go to Jail Rather Than Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ex-mercenary Sam Hall said Thursday he will go to
jail rather than testify in a $24 million civil suit brought by two
journalists who accuse U.S. officials and Nicaraguan rebels of
arms-for-drug deals in Central America.
   Hall has refused to answer some questions during depositions
taken in connection with suit about his relationship with two of
the defendants, retired Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub and Iran-Contra
figure Robert Owen.
   Hall is to appear for a contempt hearing in U.S. District Court
next Wednesday. The suit is scheduled to go to trial June 27.
   ``There are some embarrassing questions and I've been asked not
to answer them,'' Hall said in a telephone interview from his home
in Redington Shores near Tampa. He refused to say who asked that he
remain silent.
   ``There are some things I can't answer, like who briefed me (in
Nicaragua), like who gave me money, who gave me C-4 (plastic
explosive) instructions,'' he said. ``It would make me guilty of
violating the U.S. Neutrality Act.''
   Hall, brother of U.S. Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, was captured
spying on Nicaragua's Sandinista government in 1986. He was freed
in January 1987 because his captors said he showed signs of mental
instability.
   Attorneys for the plaintiffs, Tony Avirgan and Martha Honey,
want to know what Hall was doing for the U.S.-backed Contras and
who guided him.
   The suit, filed long before the Iran-Contra affair became
public, accuses Singlaub, Owen and other defendants of running a
secret right-wing terror network dating back to 1959.
   Also named in the suit are Theodore Shackley, former deputy
director of operations for the CIA; Contra director Adolfo Calero;
Medellin Cartel leaders Pablo Escobar Gaviria and Jorge Ochoa
Vasquez; Iran-Contra figures Richard Secord and Albert Hakim and
others.
   The suit accuses the defendants of funding illegal Contra
activities with drug runs in cooperation with the Medellin Cartel,
and threatening, imprisoning and even killing anyone who threatened
to uncover the ring.
   The suit also accuses them of responsibility for the 1984
bombing of a news conference in Nicaragua in which Avirgan was hurt
and eight people died.
   Hall said Singlaub's attorney, Thomas Spencer, had encouraged
him to testify, but Hall said he would refuse to testify to protect
his former boss.
   He said he also had contact with Owen, now a figure in the
Iran-Contra case, in the course of his work for the Contras.
</TEXT>
