<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShuttleBoosters 1stLd-Writethru a0714 06-09 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Boosters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA, Pentagon Meet on Allocating Rocket Fuel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3 grafs for 3rd graf pvs to include governor ordering
weekly inspections. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The National''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of NASA and the Defense
Department began discussions Thursday to decide which agency will
get the first batches of rocket fuel when the sole supplier of a
key ingredient gets back in business next week in Nevada.
   Kerr-McGee Corp. has announced it will resume manufacture of
ammonium perchlorate Monday at its Henderson plant, which shut down
under public pressure May 12, eight days after an explosion
destroyed a competitor's plant nearby.
   In Nevada, meanwhile, seeking to alleviate concerns about the
dangers of continuing manufacture of the fuel, Gov. Richard Bryan
ordered weekly inspections of the Kerr-McGee plant by the state
Division of Occupational Safety and Health.
   Bryan said he won't try to block resumption of operations but
that he will work with federal officials to minimize the amount of
ammonium perchlorate stored at Kerr-McGee.
   Kerr-McGee and Pacific Engineering & Production Co. were the
only producers of ammonium perchlorate, an oxidizer used in the
space shuttle booster rockets and in such military rocket programs
as the Navy's Trident, the Army's Stinger and the Air Force's
Peacekeeper (MX), Minuteman, Titan 34D and Delta.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration lost the fuel
for two shuttle boosters when the Pacific Engineering & Production
Co. plant was demolished by a series of explosions that also killed
two people. It left the space agency with rocket sets for only four
flights.
   ``The fact that Kerr-McGee is opening Monday does help the
situation,'' said Russ Bardos, director of shuttle propulsion for
NASA. ``The longer the delay in Kerr-McGee opening up, the more
serious the immediate problem in terms of keeing the flow and
processing moving on schedule.''
   Bardos and George Abbey, the No. 2 man in NASA's space shuttle
program, is scheduled to meet again Friday with representatives of
other rocket users to allocate the fuel.
   The ingredients in the fuel mix are different for each
application and the priorities must be decided in advance. Bardos
said it takes 10 days to two weeks to produce the 1.7 million
pounds of fuel used by the shuttles.
   NASA had scheduled nine shuttle flighs next year.
   ``We have lost two batches in the Pacific Engineering explosions
and we cannot recover those two batches in the next few months,''
Bardos said. ``Therefore, there will be an impact on at least two
flights.''
   But he cautioned that does not mean the shuttle can fly only
seven times next year. Four of the first 11 post-Challenger flights
_ two this year _ are dedicated to secret Air Force cargo, giving
the Pentagon an incentive to allocate some of its fuel to those
missions.
   Anita Bridges, a Kerr-McGee spokeswoman, announced Wednesday
that agreement had been reached with the Clark County (Nev.) Fire
Department and state officials over the plant's safety and are
ready to resume production.
   The impasse had threatened to block reopening of the plant
because of fears of another explosion.
   Kerr-McGee hired a team of independent safety experts to inspect
the plant and has ``done everything humanly possible to try to
alleviate the fears and concerns of our operation,'' the
spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0195 </DOCNO>
