<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Pro-ChoiceNuns     06-09 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pro-Choice Nuns,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuns Say Church Response to Their Abortion Statement Is Cause for
Hope</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by Roman Catholic officials not to
expel two nuns who signed an advertisement challenging the church's
anti-abortion stance may mark the end of the use of dismissal to
quiet dissent, one of the nuns said Thursday.
   ``I would like to hope that it's the beginning of a process for
our community ... and others to begin to look at the question and
to look at the question of choice for women,'' Sister Patricia
Hussey told a news conference. ``It's about our right to dissent
and our right to dissent publicly on the issue of choice.''
   ``I think also that dismissal would never again be used as an
instrument to quiet dissent,'' she said. ``It is not helpful. It is
not lifegiving, and in fact it's very draining and not for the good
of our congregation and not good for the church.''
   Hussey and Barbara Ferraro, members of the General Government
Group of the Sisters of Notre Dame deNamur, were under threat of
expulsion from the order after they refused to recant opinions in
an Oct. 7, 1984, advertisement in The New York Times which bore
their signatures.
   The full page advertisement, which noted the church's position
that abortion is never permissible, said ``there is a mistaken
belief in American society that this is the only legitimate
Catholic position.'' It also said ``a diversity of opinion exists
among committed Catholics'' on the issue of abortion.
   Shortly after publication of the advertisement, the 22 nuns and
four priests who signed the statement were asked to recant or face
dismissal from their religious orders. Because Hussey and Ferraro
refused to do so, they expected to be dismissed.
   Last Saturday, the order issued a statement from the Vatican
saying it ``will not proceed with the process to dismiss'' the nuns.
   ``We were as astounded on Saturday upon hearing the decision,''
Hussey said. ``I think they seriously listened to women in our
(religious) community ... who said dismissal and the threat of
dismissal is violent, it's non-gospel and it's non-Christian.''
   The nuns, who work with the homeless in Charleston, W.Va., at
the Covenant House, acknowledged that the Vatican still has the
final word and they could be excommunicated and their superiors
dismissed.
   Hussey said she hoped the Vatican would honor the order's
decision and that ``we will be able to be respected as autonomous
women in religious communities.''
   ``I hope the Vatican clearly knows that dissent is extremely
important to the life of the church and doesn't use its tactics as
it has in the past to squelch dissent,'' she said.
   ``Wouldn't it be wonderful if women now, and men in the Roman
Catholic Church, would not be fearful and would not be afraid to
speak out on their positions,'' Ferraro said.
   She cautioned, however, that those who go public could pay a
price.
   ``People need to realize it will not be without struggle, it
will not be without great personal cost. And based on what we went
through the past four years, it just does not come easily.''
</TEXT>
