<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CajunArtist 1stLd-Writethru a0778 06-09 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cajun Artist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0778,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cajun Artist To Display Paintings That Caused Stir In Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: Back in, to CORRECT spelling of
Livingston</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artist George Rodrigue said Thursday he will
have a one-day show on Capitol Hill of paintings that he had to
smuggle out of the Soviet Union following his exhibition there.
   Rodrigue, 43, of LaFayette, La., attracted widespead attention
when Soviet officials ordered him during the Moscow summit to
remove from display his oil paintings of President Reagan and
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Denied exit permits to take his exhibit out of the country,
Rodrigue said he turned to the visiting news media to ferry his 13
paintings back to the United States.
   He said some Americans traveling with Reagan's entourage
volunteered to carry the paintings on Air Force Two, the plane that
ferried the press. Rodrigue refused to identify the couriers, but
he said: ``They didn't have to go through customs.''
   Back in the United States, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., agreed to
co-sponsor the show on Friday ``to allow the American people to see
the paintings that the Soviet people were banned from seeing.''
   No one answered the telephone at the Soviet information office.
A message left on the recording machine was not returned.
   Rodrigue said his experience with Soviet functionaries left him
with a sour taste.
   ``The ordinary people I met were real nice,'' said the Cajun
painter. ``But the Soviet bureaucracy we could not deal with. There
was no negotiation.''
   Rodrigue was invited to the Moscow summit by a Soviet delegation
that hoped to create a Louisiana theme.
   During the summit, 13 of Rodrigue's paintings _ including the
oils of Reagan and Gorbachev _ were to hang in a restaurant at
Moscow's international trade center where a Louisiana chef served
Cajun food. Rodrigue said he was disappointed the Soviet people
could not enter the trade center without special passes.
   The day after Rodrigue put up the oils showing Reagan as a
cowboy on a white horse and Gorbachev carrying a red flag, Soviet
officials confiscated the paintings. Officials gave conflicting
reasons for the action.
   ``They asked `Why wasn't Gorbachev on a horse?''' he said.
``Then they said the paintings were too expensive. ... Then they
asked why Reagan's painting did not have a sun in it.''
   The various reasons were ``real stupid,'' Rodrigue said. ``The
bottom line really is they didn't want the president hanging in a
Russian restaurant. That's what I think.''
   But Rodrigue speculated widespread media attention on the
painting prompted the Soviets to reconsider. Two days before he was
to leave, they re-hung the two paintings.
   Then, he said, various officials tried to persuade him to donate
the picture of Gorbachev to the Soviet Union, an offer Rodrigue
said he would grant only if he could personally hand the painting
to the Kremlin leader.
</TEXT>
