<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0718 06-09 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State of Emgergency To Be Extended</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new material and editing. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha on Friday
morning extended the nationwide state of emergency for a third
year, according to a presidential statement.
   The statement came two days after blacks ended their biggest and
longest general strike. The extension takes effect upon publication
Friday in the government gazette.
   Botha said despite success in curtailing violence and unrest, he
believed ordinary laws were still inadequate to ensure public order
and safety.
   ``It is indeed the aspiration of the government that conditions
will change to such an extent that the declared state of emergency
can be lifted,'' Botha said in the statement.
   ``Intimidation and terror are aimed at undermining the
political, economic and social activities of all our communities.
It is also being employed to disrupt our courts and legal
procedures,'' he said.
   There were no immediate details of any possible changes in the
emergency regulations, which allow sweeping powers of detention,
outlaw many forms of peaceful anti-government protest, and restrict
freedom of speech, press and assembly.
   ``We might just as well prepare ourselves for a permanent state
of emergency,'' independent member of Parliament Jan van Eck told a
gathering in Johannesburg earlier Thursday. ``A minority regime
will not be able to govern this country without the very wide and
very aribitrary powers afforded by these state of emergency.''
   Despite banning of apartheid groups and restrictions on their
leaders, more than 2 million blacks stayed away from work, school
and shops from Monday to Wednesday.
   The action left streets deserted in major cities such as
Johannesburg and Durban and cost the economy about $250 million,
according to the Associated Chambers of Commerce.
   Botha first issued the nationwide decree on June 12, 1986, after
two years of daily violence that claimed 1,700. By mid-1987 the
violence lessened, but not after an additional 2,500 people died in
township political violence, security force action and in strikes
and other protests against the government's apartheid policies.
   About 100 bombings and land mine explosions have taken place in
the country in the past two years, most of them blamed on the
outlawed African National Congress. The ANC is waging a sabotage
campaign to end white domination of the government and apartheid
legislation which separates the races and restricts where the 26
million black majority may live, attend school, work and play.
   Although the violence has considerably subsided, except for
continual bloodshed between Zulu political groups in the natal
province townships, new emergency decrees were added this year.
   In February, 17 anti-apartheid organizations, including the
United Democratic Front coalition and the Azanian Peoples
Organization, were banned from all political activity. The two
Front presidents and treasurer, the last executive members not in
hiding or in detention, were banned from giving speeches or news
interviews.
   New restrictions on the press have been added periodically.
Journalists now are prohibited from being on the scene of unrest,
reporting security force action, treatment of emergency detainees
and a wide range of political statements the government considers
subversive.
   Two newspapers have been banned this year, and seven others
threatened with shutdown for publishing material the minister of
home affairs considers objectionable.
   When the emergency was reimposed in June last year, about 1,000
detainees were reported to have been technically freed from
detention for a few minutes, then redetained under the new decree
without ever leaving their cells.
   An estimated 40,000 people, including 10,000 children, have been
detained at some time during the past two years, according to the
now-banned Detainees Parents Support Committee.
   Several people detained at the beginning of the emergency,
including a black free-lance journalist and a white university
professor, remained in detention without charge two years later.
   The government has refused, even in Parliament, to give
definitive numbers of people in detention, saying it is not in the
national interest to divulge the information.
</TEXT>
