<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolhouseDoor     06-09 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schoolhouse Door,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>25 Years After Wallace's Stand, Racial Gains Noted At University</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 25 years after George Wallace's
``stand in the schoolhouse door'' at the University of Alabama, one
in 10 of its students is black, and on Thursday the school
sponsored a forum on race relations.
   The conference attracted more than 300 academics, alumni and
journalists. Harry Knopke, a university official who helped plan
it, said the event would mark the anniversary with something
``positive, productive and informative.''
   Since Wallace's showy, futile attempt to block two blacks from
enrolling at the state campus, black students and faculty members
agreed that much progress has been made at the university.
   Three blacks sit on the 15-member board of trustees; five blacks
have been elected homecoming queen and one black as student
government president; and black fraternities and sororities are on
the picturesque fraternity row.
   ``I like going to school up here,'' said Laura Tate, a black
senior from Selma. She said race relations on campus are a
considerable improvement over her hometown, where she said
incidents of racial hostility were commonplace.
   ``But there's always room for improvement,'' she said of the
university.
   Tate recalled her sophomore year, when her sorority, Alpha Kappa
Alpha, was greeted by a burned cross when they moved into a house
on all-white sorority row. Two white male students later were
suspended for the cross burning.
   ``When we acquired the house, they didn't like it. But I think
now people have just gotten used to us being there,'' she said.
   ``The university did react and deal with it in a very forthright
manner,'' said Rhoda E. Johnson, who heads the women's studies
department. She credited the university for efforts to deal with a
problem many institutions have ignored.
   ``At least we are trying to deal with the issue of race
relations at the university. That's a far cry from a lot of other
places,'' she said.
   The first black graduate, Vivian Malone Jones, finished in 1965;
ten years later, 10 percent of the school's students were black.
The figure dipped in the early 1980s and remains at about 9 percent
of a student population now 16,000 strong.
   Knopke, executive aide to the university president, said the
school has succeeded by systematic recruiting that reaches out to
Alabama students as early as ninth grade.
   The school's black enrollment is significantly greater than that
of it cross-state football rival, Auburn University, which had a
3.5 percent black enrollment in 1986.
   Like many other schools, Alabama has had a difficult time
attracting black faculty members. Knopke said about 2.5 percent of
the school's faculty is black _ a figure the school is trying to
increase.
   ``It's a common goal for both the adminstration and the
departments,'' he said. ``We're interested in a setting here that
fosters multicultural development. That's what a university is all
about. That's how people learn.''
   Jarrod Bentley, a black senior from Birmingham, agreed.
   ``I think Alabama has better prepared me to live in the real
world,'' he said. ``In deciding on a college, I wasn't thinking,
`Well, Wallace stood in the door 25 years ago.' I was thinking
about getting an education.''
   Bentley, an accounting major, said he has at times witnessed and
felt discrimination at the university.
   ``I'm not blaming it on the university or the state of
Alabama,'' he said. ``America itself still has a long way to go.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
