<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0784 06-09 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0784,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Cites Differences With Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs with Dukakis campaign reax</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate George Bush on
Thursday branded Michael Dukakis as an ``out-of-the-mainstream''
politician using ``moderate tones'' in an attempt to attract voters
inclined toward change.
   ``After eight years of one party in the White House, no matter
how successful, some good people will yearn for a change, hoping
that `change' means improvement,'' Bush told the Republican state
convention here.
   ``It's our job to let them know that this time, in this case,
change and improvement comes from the incumbent _ the incumbent
vice president.''
   In his most detailed, point-by-point attack on the Massachusetts
Democrat, his certain opponent in the fall, Bush said Dukakis would
raises taxes, harass Americans with IRS audits, weaken national
defense and advocate an isolationist foreign policy.
   Dukakis' communications director, Leslie Dach, scoffed at Bush's
contentions.
   ``Given where George Bush is in the polls, I think it's no
surprise that he's chosen to spend his time mudslinging and tearing
down,'' he said.
   Shortly before his speech to delegates assembled at the George
R. Brown Convention Center, the vice president told reporters he
was shifting his campaign into a more aggressive stance.
   ``I'm going to spell out the differences. I will do it
factually. I will do it fairly. I want to get it all together,'' he
said.
   In the speech, interrupted several times by applause, Bush said:
``At issue this year are two completely different visions of our
country and where it's going,'' the vice president told delegates
to the Texas state GOP convention.
   Bush said he believes he will do well this fall, despite polls
showing him trailing Dukakis, because he will run a
``look-at-the-record'' campaign.
   He said he and President Reagan inherited a sick country when
they were sworn into office in 1981, with the economy suffering
from ``stagflation'' and the United States suffering foreign policy
defeats abroad.
   ``The patient's back on his feet and better than ever,'' Bush
said. ``And now who do we hear knocking on the door but the doctors
who made him sick.''
   Bush charged that Dukakis would raise taxes and step up Internal
Revenue Service audits of citizens _ with or without justification.
   ``Governor Dukakis operates from the premise that most Americans
must be guilty (of tax cheating),'' he said. ``I operate from the
premise that most Americans are innocent and shouldn't be hassled.''
   On foreign policy, Bush accused Dukakis of favoring a policy of
retreat on the support of burgeoning democracies around the world
while opposing development of new U.S. weapons systems.
   The vice president said the Soviets would never have negotiated
a medium-range missile treaty if there had been the sort of nuclear
freeze that Dukakis advocates. He also chided Dukakis for
advocating greater reliance on multi-lateral bodies, such as the
United Nations, to advance U.S. foreign policy interests.
   ``He's...old-style '60s liberalism,'' on crime, Bush said of
Dukakis.
   Bush claimed that Dukakis lacks experience to make practical
decisions affecting taxes and the overall economy.
   ``When I wanted to learn the ways of the world, I didn't go to
the Kennedy School (at Harvard), I came to Texas,'' he said. ``I
didn't go to a symposium on job creation. I started a business. I
didn't study a monograph on the effects of economic growth, I met a
payroll.''
   ``My opponent is an articulate defender of a flawed world view,
a man who holds strong convictions and who speaks in moderate
tones,'' he said. ``But his views and values are too often, in my
view, out of the mainstream.''
   Earlier, at a news converence, Bush said he didn't put much
stock in polls showing him behind Michael Dukakis because ``I am
convinced the country doesn't want to swing left'' politically.
   ``Yeah, I don't worry about it,'' the vice president said when
asked to comment on a newly released Texas Poll showing him leading
Dukakis in his adopted home state by only 7 percentage points.
   ``I feel really relaxed about it. I really do,'' he said.
``We're not play-acting here. I like fighting back.''
   Bush said he had no quarrel with the way his campaign is being
run, although he acknowledged that ``there will be some changes
along the way.''
   Campaign manager Lee Atwater, while sidestepping the question of
whether Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III would be soon
arriving to head the campaign, strongly suggested that such a move
is in the offing.
   ``My sense is that everybody would love to see Jim Baker as
campaign chairman,'' he said. ``My idea is that anytime that he'd
like to come, we'd love to have him.''
</TEXT>
