<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Meets Arias, Takes Wife Home From Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf pvs with Bush comment, Dukakis
campaign response, edits for transition, picks up 4th graf pvs,
bgng: Dukakis, who</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, the all-but-sure Democratic
presidential nominee, met Thursday with Costa Rican President Oscar
Arias and said the United States should encourage democracy in
Central America through economic assistance instead of military
force.
   The Massachusetts governor also attended Harvard University's
commencement, took his wife home from the hospital where she had
spinal surgery six days ago and spent several hours catching up on
state business.
   Dukakis, meanwhile, came under attack from Republican George
Bush, who spoke to Republicans at a Texas state convention in
Houston. Bush attacked the Massachusetts governor for
``old-style...60's liberalism'' whose views are ``out of the
mainstream.''
   ``It's clear that the vice president doesn't think that his own
record or vision can bring him the votes he needs in November,''
retorted Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach.
   Dukakis was speaking at a Thursday night victory party
celebrating his Tuesday primary victories clinching enough
delegates to assure his nomination. Dukakis' campaign, meanwhile,
continued a low-key search for a running mate amid quiet
preparations for the Democratic National Convention in July.
   Dukakis, who has been critical of Reagan administration Central
America policies, told reporters after meeting with Arias that if
elected he would ``develop a new relationship based on repect''
with the region's leaders.
   ``We did have an opportunity once again to talk about concerns
that he has and I have and all of us have about Central America,
about his leadership in bringing peace to the region and about the
opportunity economically for development,'' said Dukakis, who held
a similar meeting with Arias several months ago.
   Arias, in Boston to deliver a commencement address at Harvard,
laughed when asked if he would endorse Dukakis for president. He
said he would ``do business with whoever you decide to send to the
White House.''
   He then referred to Dukakis' fluent Spanish and said, ``Perhaps
it's easier, we can get along in the same language. That helps.''
   Dukakis, speaking in Spanish to a television reporter traveling
with Arias, said efforts to remove Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega from power should be centered on negotiations that involve
Central American leaders.
   The governor said the Reagan administration has failed to
consult with Arias and other leaders in the region during efforts
to persuade Noriega, who is under U.S. indictment on drug charges,
to step down.
   At Massachusetts General Hospital, Dukakis stood by as his wife,
Kitty, thanked the hospital's doctors and staff for caring for her
during her hospitalization after surgery to repair herniated discs
in her neck.
   Mrs. Dukakis said her doctors told her she could remove her neck
brace by next month when her husband formally accepts the
nomination at the Democratic convention.
   Outside the hospital, Dukakis smiled and refused to answer when
asked to comment on Jesse Jackson's assertion that he deserved to
be offered the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket because of his
strong performance in the primaries. On Wednesday, Dukakis said
Jackson deserved consideration but not a guaranteed offer.
   While Dukakis spent the afternoon at his Statehouse office,
campaign aides met to discuss strategy for weekend meetings in
Michigan where work is to begin on drafting the party's election
platform, a process that will involve negotiations with the Jackson
campaign. Deputy campaign manager Jack Corrigan will lead Dukakis'
delegation to the meetings, bringing with him most of the
campaign's top issues advisers.
   Dukakis is to work at the Statehouse on Friday and attend the
Massachusetts Democratic Convention on Saturday. On Sunday he is to
address the nation's mayors at a national conference in Salt Lake
City. Dukakis will focus on the nation's drug problems and their
effect on families, campaign aides said.
   Several members of Congress are scheduled to visit with Dukakis
early next week before he heads to the South for three days of
campaigning.

</TEXT>
