<HEAD>Rebels Attack U.S. Ambassador's Home With Mortar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with students clashing with security
forces, Shining Path attacks in highlands. CORRECTS spelling of
Ecsodi, sted Escodi. EDITS to trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas damaged the U.S.
ambassador's residence with mortar fire Thursday. Elsewhere in the
capital, college students protesting a student's death clashed with
security forces at three campuses.
   Police said protesters lobbed dynamite sticks, firebombs and
rocks at police and soldiers who surrounded the schools on foot and
in small tanks and armored vehicles. Eighty students were arrested
and dozens were hurt after police fired buckshot and tear gas.
   Three rebels of the pro-Cuba Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement
fired three mortar rounds at U.S. Ambassador Alexander Watson's
home and fled in a waiting car, police said. The roof was damaged
but no one was hurt.
   Watson was eating breakfast in the two-story colonial residence
and his wife and infant daughter also were at home when a 60mm
mortar shell exploded at 6:30 a.m., embassy spokesman Joao Ecsodi
said.
   ``The ambassador thought at first it was the backfire of a car.
It was not a big explosion,'' Ecsodi said.
   It was the third attack at U.S. government buildings in Lima
since April 1986.
   Ecsodi said the mortar round destroyed a ramp and lighting
fixture on the roof.
   A 10-foot-high concrete wall surrounds the residence, on a main
boulevard in Lima. Peruvian police frequently guard the perimeter
while embassy security agents patrol nearby.
   Police said the mortar was fired from a block away.
   Ecsodi said the guerrillas left circulars commemorating the
death of a pro-Cuba guerrilla leader, Luis de la Puente, who
launched his insurgency on June 9, 1965. He was killed in combat
four months later and his group broken up. The Tupac Amaru band
became active in 1984.
   Violence occurred at the main campus of San Marcos University,
about four miles west of downtown Lima; at its medical school
branch on the downtown periphery, and at the suburban National
Engineering University.
   The government had refused to grant permission for a planned
student march Thursday, saying it was fomented by campus-based
supporters of the Mao-inspired Shining Path guerrilla group.
   Security forces surrounded the campuses to keep demonstrators
from parading downtown to mark the death of a student killed in
Lima University protests a week ago.
   Students said they were also protesting an incursion by police
into San Marcos campus last week amid violent demonstrations. More
than 100 students were arrested then, police said.
   Reporters on the scene said dozens of demonstrators were wounded
as protesters tossed rocks and police fired buckshot and tear gas.
   Associated Press photographer Alejandro Balaguer was knocked
unconscious by a demonstrator's rock.
   In highland Apurimac state, Shining Path guerrillas killed a
school teacher, a village police chief and a farm worker in
separate attacks, Santiago Roldan, Apurimac's chief administrator,
said Thursday.
   He said the violence occurred recently in Apurimac towns and
villages, but had no details. Nearly the entire state southeast of
Lima is under a state of emergency because of rebel attacks.
</TEXT>
