<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     06-09 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Seventh Day, They Kept Talking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters and producers
negotiated for the seventh straight day on Thursday, while some
optimistic reports emerged for the first time in the 14-week-old
strike.
   The talks resumed Thursday morning at the headquarters of the
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers. Wednesday's
sessin lasted 12 hours.
   ``This is the seventh day of straight talks, and we expect to
have another long day,'' Writers Guild of America spokeswoman
Cheryl Rhoden said.
   Both sides have refused to characterize the talks. But in
discussing a report that a settlement was near, Ms. Rhoden said
``some issues remain unresolved.''
   The entertainment trade paper Daily Variety on Thursday reported
its sources said there was some basis for optimism in the
negotiations.
   The start of the fall television production season usually
begins the last week in June and the first week of July. The CBS
network has already announced a two-month delay for the debut of
its new shows, blaming the lengthy strike.
   Scriptwriters called the industry-wide walkout March 7, when
contract talks broke off over the issues of creative control on the
set and residuals for TV reruns.
   The strike has stalled TV and movie productions, with the
exception of a few independent producers such as Carson
Productions, which signed independent contracts with the union.
   The 9,000-member guild has signed full-term contracts with about
80 producers, but the alliance contends those producers employ only
a fraction of the 3,000 active writers.
   On Wednesday's ``The Tonight Show With Johnny Carson,'' the talk
show host noted in his monologue that it was the first
union-sanctioned show since the strike began. ``Tonight'' went back
on the air in mid-May with Carson writing his own scripts.
   ``Good evening, ladies and germs,'' Carson said, reading from
cue cards. ``It's good to have the highly paid writers back. You
can boo this monologue tonight, but bear in mind each joke has the
union label.''
</TEXT>
