<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NicaraguaTalks 2ndLd-Writethru   06-09 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua Talks, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0767,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Talks Break Off With No Accord</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with end of talks</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government and
the U.S.-backed rebels ended negotiations Thursday without reaching
an agreement on a permanent peace.
   ``It is with deep consternation we announce that an agreement
for a permanent cease-fire was not reached,'' Contra leader Alfredo
Cesar said, reading from a statement.
   The talks ended after both sides exchanged proposals detailing
measures for disarmament of the rebels and bringing democratic
reforms to Nicaragua.
   Cesar said a temporary truce would remain in effect but he would
not say how long.
   ``The war that our people have been suffering for seven years
and that has almost stopped should not be renewed,'' Cesar said.
``The (Nicaraguan) Resistance will not initiate offensive military
operations.''
   He would not say whether further talks would be held.
   ``There is no new meeting programmed,'' he said. ``We have
reiterated our deep conviction to looking to solutions to the
conflict in our motherland in a civilized way.''
   The talks Thursday came on the final day of the fourth round of
talks since the sides signed a cease-fire accord on May 23. The
rebels and the government have been unable to work out the details
by which the rebels would disarm and reforms would take place in
Nicaragua.
   Earlier Thursday, the rebels objected to parts of the
government's proposal, including the Sandinista's amnesty plan and
the lack of a definite time schedule for granting democratic
reforms.
   ``These are fundamental for the (Nicaraguan) Resistance and
makes the difference between an agreement or no agreement,'' Cesar
had told journalists.
   The Contras had maintained that Thursday's talks were the last.
   Paul Reichler, an American lawyer working as a government
negotiator, told journalists sharp divisions among the Contra
leadership caused the talks to reach an impasse Thursday afternoon.
   He said he held several private meetings with Cesar, who told
him the problems were with Col. Enrique Bermudez, the ranking
military leader.
   ``He said Bermudez would follow orders from the (U.S.) State
Department and he called him Colonel America,'' Reichler said,
reportedly relating a May conversation with Cesar.
   Reichler also said he had met with Cesar on May 23 in Miami, and
said the two agreed on six demands by the Contras for bringing
democratic reforms to Nicaragua. He said those rebel demands were
included in the Sandinista's proposal.
   ``We fully expected there would be an agreement two weeks ago
based on what Alfredo (Cesar) told us,'' Reichler said. ``Cesar is
unwilling now to accept the terms he proposed unless Bermudez goes
along.''
   The government proposal, presented Thursday morning by Gen.
Humberto Ortega, called for a gradual political amnesty, with the
first 200 prisoners freed after the signing of an agreement and the
last coming on Sept. 28.
   The rebel proposal called for all of the prisoners to be freed
within five days of an agreement. Contra leader Aristides Sanchez
said it would be a ``show of good faith.''
   The rebels said there are 4,207 political prisoners, while the
International Red Cross, seen here as sympathetic to the
government, put the figure at 3,324.
   The Contras also demand the armed forces totally be separate
from the ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front in name as
well as actions. The govenment agreed to the ``separation and
independence of the powers of the state.''
   The rebels want a clear timetable for enacting political
freedoms, including complete pluralism, freedom of expression, the
right to strike, electoral reforms and guarantees of a mixed
economy.
   The Sandinista proposal said those items would be discussed
during 60 days among the 14 political parties and eight rebel
representatives after it was certfied that the Contra combatants
moved into designated zones to disarm.
   The talks would be held before the date set for the fighters to
lay down their arms. The Contras said they needed assurances that
the democratic measures would not only be discussed but enacted.
   Several points in the rebel plan were ruled as unacceptable by
the government during earlier meetings. They included a 90-day
suspension of the military draft; permission for the Contras,
formally called the Nicaraguan Resistance, to open offices in
Nicaragua; and licenses for independent television stations.
   Both sides stopped offensive military operations March 21, the
first day of the first face-to-face talks that led to the plan
signed two days later. A formal 60-day truce ended at the end of
May but both sides extended it. Both sides have repeatedly accused
each other of violating the accord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
