<HEAD>Libyan Leader Apologizes For Causing Uproar At Summit
^With AM-Arab Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi addressed
fellow Arab leaders in a somber mood Thursday to offer his
apologies for creating an uproar by insulting them at a plenary
meeting earlier in the week.
   Wearing spectacles and with the white hood of his robe pulled
low over his eyes, Gadhafi assured the summit, including 17 other
Arab leaders, that his unprecedented public attacks on them were
not personal but should be considered as ``brotherly squabbles that
only serve to strengthen Arab unity.''
   Gadhafi outraged Arab heads of state at Wednesday's session,
telling them that those among them who cooperate with the United
States were ``lackeys of imperialism and ... can go to hell.''
   He held up the session for more than an hour, refusing to enter
the meeting hall until several leaders had pleaded with him. When
he finally came into the hall, he wore a white glove on his right
hand.
   The Libyan delegation put out word that the glove was intended
to avoid ``contact with traitors'' during the traditional
handshakes.
   He wore no glove while addressing the closing meeting of the
three-day summit, convened to consider the Palestinian uprising in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The rest of his speech was devoted to further exhortations for
Arab unity.
