<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-09 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Spread Across Deep South</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled through much of the South on Thursday from
the Carolinas across the Gulf Coast states to eastern Texas, and
temperatures were unseasonably low across much of the nation.
   The storms produced golf ball-sized hail south of High Point,
N.C., and one-inch hail at Lillington, N.C., between Raleigh and
Fayetteville.
   Thunderstorms also developed in the western Plains and in the
Colorado Rockies. Small hail was reported near Colorado Springs,
Colo.
   Rain was scattered over southwest Oregon and northern
California, with the heaviest rain along the coast.
   Rain was widespread along the East Coast from southern New
England to the southern Appalachians.
   Temperatures soared to over 100 degrees Thursday in southwest
Texas and the southeast corner of New Mexico while much of the
nation had afternoon temperatures in the 60s and lower 70s.
   The cool temperatures extended as far south as northern North
Carolina, the Tennessee Valley and northern Arkansas and as far
west as the eastern portions of the northern and central Plains.
   A frost and freeze advisory was posted for Friday morning for
northern Michigan, a freeze warning for the northern mountains of
western Pennsylvania, with scattered frost in Wisconsin, New York
state and northern New England.
   Detroit had a record morning low for the date of 40 degrees,
which was 54 degrees less than Monday's record high. Flint, Mich.,
tied a record low of 35 just two days after a 91-degree record high.
   Other record lows for the date Thursday were Duluth, Minn., 31;
Miami Beach, Fla., 69; and Toledo, Ohio, 38.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Mount Shasta, Calif., to 106 degrees at Del Rio, Texas.
The nation's low Thursday morning was 21 degrees at South Lake
Tahoe, Calif.
   Friday's forecast called for scattered thunderstorms from the
eastern Carolinas to Florida and parts of the central Gulf Coast
region, widely scattered showers in northern Maine and western New
York, scattered thunderstorms over the Rockies and western parts of
the northern and central Plains, showers and a few thunderstorms
scattered in Idaho and the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s or 80s over much of
the nation, except 60s or below from the Great Lakes region across
the northern and central Appalachians to the northern and middle
Atlantic Coast states and along the Pacific Coast. Temperatures
were expected to climb to the 90s in parts of North Dakota and
eastern Montana and the 90s to near 105 degrees from southern and
western Texas to the Southwest deserts.
</TEXT>
