<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Gandhi     06-09 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gandhi,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Says India Will `Do Our Best' Not to Build Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India said
Thursday ``We've had the means for almost 14 years now'' to make
atomic weapons, ``but we'll do our best not to do so.''
   However, ``it's difficult to say what sort of pressure we would
come under in case Pakistan did build a (nuclear) weapon,'' he
added in a Cable News Network television interview.
   It was one of the bluntest public acknowledgments by any Indian
leader that India's lone atomic explosion in 1974 provided that
Asian country the capability for making nuclear weapons.
   Experts have said this was the case, but official statements
about the blast staged in the Rajasthan Desert by the government of
the late Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, Rajiv's mother, have always
stressed that it was merely ``a peaceful explosion of an atomic
device.''
   Rajiv Gandhi succeeded his mother as prime minister after she
was assassinated by Sikh bodyguards outside her New Delhi home in
1984.
   In other statements Thursday in the United States and Wednesday
in Bonn, West Germany, the prime minister accused India's neighbor,
Pakistan, of aiding Sikh terrorists. He described as ``two big
negatives'' of otherwise much-improved Indo-U.S. relations the flow
of American military aid to Pakistan and what he termed America's
``looking the other way on Pakistan's nuclear program.''
   Gandhi, in New York for the United Nations disarmament
conference, said during the CNN interview: ``It's very obvious that
they (Pakistan) have a nuclear weapons program.
   ``They have a program which is based on well-smuggled or stolen
technologies,'' he continued. ``And it's now pretty obvious to the
whole world where these technologies are being stolen from. And
we're sad that those countries who can control them, put some
pressure on them to stop this program, are not doing so.''
   Gandhi's government has been urging the United States to stop
granting waivers to Pakistan under the U.S. law barring American
aid to countries developing atomic weapons.
   Attempts to smuggle nuclear technology or equipment to Pakistan
from the West have surfaced over the years. Last February, a
Pakistani-Canadian was sentenced to five years in prison after
being convicted in Philadelphia of trying to export illegally to
Pakistan special metals used in atomic bombs.
   Pakistan maintains that its nuclear program is solely for
producing power and other peaceful uses.
   Before leaving Europe on Wednesday, Gandhi charged that by
allegedly helping Sikh extremists, Pakistan was ``perhaps the
largest supporter of terrorism in the world.''
   Disputing the idea that the Sikhs of India's violence-ridden
Punjab state deserve more autonomy, he said, ``They do have
autonomy.'' In the last election, he said, more Sikhs voted than
ever before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka-Elections     06-09 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka-Elections,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Killed on Regional Election Day in South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TANGALLE, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Election-day violence left two people
dead Thursday, raising to 12 the number of people killed in the
island's southern province in the last three days.
   Most of the killings have been blamed on extremists of the
Sinhalese ethnic majority, who oppose the elections to the southern
District Council.
   Many voters apparently were discouraged by the violence despite
the presence of thousands of police and members of other security
forces.
   An Election Commission official said turnout reached a low of 15
percent at some voting stations. The province has more than 1.2
million registered voters.
   He said winners of the 53 council seats, contested by 166
candidates, would be announced Friday.
   One of the victims Thursday was a government official fatally
shot while taking food to election workers, police reported.
Special arrangements for feeding workers were made because many
shops and hotels closed in response to threats from the Sinhalese
extremists.
   Police shot a Sinhalese youth to death when he tried to set fire
to a state-owned bus near Tangalle, 90 miles south of Colombo.
   District Councils are a provision of a treaty Sri Lanka and
India signed in July in an attempt to end a separatist war by
rebels of the Tamil ethnic minority. More than 8,000 people have
been killed during the five-year conflict.
   Rebels were to lay down their arms in exchange for more autonomy
in the Tamil-dominated northern and eastern regions, but the
largest group refused and India has sent in more than 50,000
soldiers to fight the insurgents.
   The People's Liberation Front, extremists from the Sinhalese
majority, contends the peace agreement made too many concessions to
Tamils and has said its men will kill anyone who supports the
accord.
   Authorities have blamed 325 killings on the group since the
agreement was signed, including the deaths of 24 candidates in the
seven District Council elections held so far.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million population and claim discrimination by the
majority Sinhalese, a predominantly Buddhist group.
   India became involved because it is the main power in the
region, Hinduism is the dominant religion among its 800 million
people and it has a Tamil minority of 60 million in southern Tamil
Nadu state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
