<DOCNO> AP880609-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Jailbreak     06-09 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Jailbreak,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Inmates Shoot Guards, Take Two Hostages In Breakout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with nine grafs to UPDATE with hostages released,
CORRECT that one guard shot sted two; picks up 8th pvs: ``Once
over...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three inmates shot a guard and took two hostages
Thursday while escaping from one of Canada's oldest and most
notorious prisons.
   The guard at Laval Institute was seriously wounded, but the
hostages were later released in apparently good condition, said
Paul Fournier, a spokesman at the federal maximum-security prison
just north of Montreal.
   The hostages _ a woman prison guard and the driver of a car the
inmates commandeered outside the prison _ were found walking on a
road about 20 miles southeast of the prison.
   Fournier said earlier the guard taken hostage was believed
wounded by gunfire, but later denied it.
   Police throughout the Montreal area launched a search for the
inmates.
   The breakout began Thursday morning in the prison paint shop.
   Rene St. Arnaud, 26, serving a 12-year sentence for armed
robbery; his brother Pierre, 24, doing seven years for robbery; and
Robert Henley, 29, serving a life sentence for murder, overpowered
the woman guard on a walkway overlooking the workshop and took her
hostage.
   The inmates began using a fork-lift truck to get over the wall
of the 115-year-old prison, but they were spotted by other guards.
Gunfire was exchanged, Fournier said.
   The guard who was shot was hit in the shoulder and leg, the
spokesman said.
   Once over the wall, the convicts stopped a passing car, took the
driver hostage and headed toward Montreal.
   Fournier said eachguard at the sprawling prison is armed with a
handgun and semi-automatic rifle. Names of the two hostages were
not immediately released.
   The medieval-looking prison has seen many dramatic escapes and
riots. In September 1986, 286 prisoners caused $500,000 damage in a
rampage to protest living conditions.
   In July 1986, five inmates escaped through a network of air
shafts and tunnels and emerged through a manhole cover outside the
walls.
   Nine prisoners held eight hostages during a three-day
disturbance in August 1980, in which one convict was killed.
   The prison was slated for demolition in 1971 but reopened three
years later because of a lack of prison space elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
