<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BlantonWedding     06-09 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blanton Wedding,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Tennesse Governor Marries for Second Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Ray Blanton of Tennessee, whose
1981 felony conviction in a liquor license conspiracy case sent him
to prison for two years, was married Thursday evening to a longtime
friend near the U.S. Capitol.
   Blanton, who is running for Congress in Tennessee, married Karen
Flint, whom he has known since the late 1970s when he was governor
and she was a staff member of the Appalachian Regional Commission.
   It was the first marriage for Ms. Flint and the second for
Blanton, who was divorced from his first wife, Betty, in April 1987.
   Friends said no honeymoon is immediately planned and that
Blanton and his new wife would immediately return to Tennessee
where he will resume his campaign for the state's 8th District
congressional seat.
   The groom wore a tuxedo and the bride a white dress and matching
veil. They emerged briefly outside the Democratic Club on Capitol
Hill, where the private ceremony was held, to pose for pictures,
but neither talked with reporters or answered questions.
   Blanton gave a thumbs up gesture when asked how the wedding
went. As the couple retreated back into the building, he was heard
saying, ``We enjoyed this.''
   Members of the bride's family said about 80 to 90 people
attended the ceremony performed by James Ford, the chaplain of the
House of Representatives.
   The bride's family is from suburban Arlington, Va., but she
lives in Nashville where she has a real estate license.
   Blanton was the governor of Tennessee from 1975 to 1979. Two
years after he left office, Blanton was convicted of mail fraud,
extortion and conspiracy in connection with the issuance of state
liquor licenses.
   He served two years in prison on the charges.
   The mail fraud charges later were vacated as a result of a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling, but the others charges remain under appeal.
