<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Vietnam     06-09 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Vietnam,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Says Vietnamese Former U.S. Employees May Go To America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister said Thursday
that Vietnamese who worked for the United States during the war may
go to America if there are assurances they will not mount attacks
on their native country.
   Since South Vietnam fell and the country was reunified in 1975,
about 900,000 former South Vietnamese officials and U.S. employees
have undergone political ``re-education,'' according to the State
Department.
   ``We have declared that we are ready to let them go if there is
a guarantee for our security,'' said Foreign Minister Nguyen Co
Thach. ``That means they must not be allowed to have hostile
activities focused toward Vietnam.''
   He told reporters at a breakfast news conference that ``some
tens of thousands'' of people may be leaving and that U.S. and
Vietnamese officials agreed to meet in Hanoi in July to discuss
security guarantees and other details.
   On Thursday, Thach met with retired Army Gen. John W. Vessey
Jr., President Reagan's special envoy on this and other
humanitarian issues involving Vietnam.
   ``I have asked Gen. Vessey if he would like to have all the
people who cooperated with (South Vietnamese President Nguyen Van)
Thieu's army, and he said that would be too much,'' said Thach.
   He reiterated Vietnam's pledge that by 1990 it will withdraw all
its troops from neighboring Cambodia, which it invaded in late 1978
to topple the Khmer Rough government of Pol Pot. Both Vietnam and
Cambodia are communist countries.
   ``If Vietnam is not out by 1990, we could be bogged down forever
in Cambodia,'' said Thach.
   ``We were there (originally) with more than 200,000 soldiers; we
have withdrawn 82,000 to 87,000,'' he said, adding that 50,000 more
will be withdrawn this year.
   It is estimated that 2 million people _ a fourth of Cambodia's
population _died in executions, famine and civil war from
1975-1979, under the radical Khmer Rouge communist regime.
   Thach said Vietnam's troops will leave even if there is no
political agreement for a transition government, but added: ``With
a political settlement, you can have security.''
   He also indicated that Vietnam will not invade again even if Pol
Pot returned to power:
   ``The Western countries condemned Pol Pot from 1975-1978, when
Vietnam recognized Pol Pot ... and we have criticized Pol Pot with
arms after that. We were criticized by the West. If Pol Pot returns
again, it is the responsibility of the Western countries to
criticize him,'' said Thach.
   The United Nations and the United States do not accept the
Vietnam-installed government of Cambodia as legitimate, instead
recognizing the rebel coalition of the Khmer Rouge, forces under
former Cambodian leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk, and the
non-communist forces of former Cambodian Premier Son Sann.
   Thach said that he was sure the Cambodian people would not allow
Pol Pot and the Khmer Rouge to rule again.
   ``If there was world condemnation of the crimes of Pol Pot, it
would demoralize his followers,'' he added.
</TEXT>
