<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ConvoyStopped     06-09 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convoy Stopped,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Group Says It's Prepared To Remain Camped In Laredo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group seeking to deliver 30 tons of food,
clothing and medical supplies to Nicaragua camped at this border
city Thursday and plotted how to win reversal of a federal policy
blocking the mission.
   ``We are kind of holding our place here today, waiting for the
pressure to build,'' said Gerry Condon, an organizer of the
Veterans' Peace Convoy to Nicaragua. ``We are hoping it won't be
long, because there are people here who want very bad to make this
trip to Nicaragua.''
   The convoy began from four different regions of the country on
May 21, and arrived at Laredo Tuesday night, planning to cross into
Mexico on Wednesday morning. But Treasury Department officials said
the group's plans to leave the 37 trucks, buses and cars hauling
the cargo in Nicaragua would violate a 1985 trade embargo.
   Ninety-four convoy members have made a commercial campground in
northern Laredo their base since Wednesday. At the campground
Thursday afternoon, members sought shade from temperatures over 100
degrees and planned strategies.
   The group got support Thursday from about 50 people picketing
the federal building in Austin and from U.S. Rep. Albert
Bustamante, D-Texas, who wrote Treasury Secretary James Baker on
Thursday urging him to allow the convoy to cross the border for
humanitarian reasons.
   A Treasury Department spokesman in Washington said Thursday that
the department's Office of Foreign Assets Control told convoy
supporters last month that taking the vehicles into Nicaragua would
require a license and posting of bonds to assure their return to
the United States within 30 days.
   ``They were notified in late May what the law was and what the
facts were on what can be exported to Nicaragua,'' said the
Treasury spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``I mean
there's no surprise here.''
   Condon said the convoy's position is that the vehicles are
needed to distribute the supplies, and are a form of humanitarian
aid allowed under the embargo.
</TEXT>
