<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Religion     06-09 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Religion,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underground Church Seeks Help from Vatican</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of an underground Catholic church said
Thursday they were seeking help from a Vatican official when he
presents a message from Pope John Paul II to Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   Ivan Gel, a leader of the underground Ukrainian Catholic Church,
said several bishops, priests and laymen from the church went to
Moscow planning to meet Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, who arrived
Wednesday for a Russian Orthodox celebration of the 1000th
anniversary of Christianity in this land.
   ``We will put the question to him about the restoration of the
legal status of the Ukrainian Catholic Church,'' Gel said.
   Casaroli is carrying a message from the pope to Gorbachev but
has not divulged the contents.
   Other members of the Roman Catholic delegation led by Casaroli
said some contact with the Ukrainians was likely, but they could
not say whether there would be a meeting.
   The Ukrainian Catholic Church, which has its roots in the
western Ukraine, ceased to exist officially in 1946 when it
officially was united with the Orthodox Church. But Gel, who is
from the western Ukrainian city Lvov, said at least four to five
million worshipers continue to attend the underground services.
   Gel, who said he spent 18 years in labor camps and exile for his
religious activities, said the last of the church's political
prisoners was released in November 1987.
   Instead of arresting clergy and believers who are practicing
their faith, authorities now regularly levy fines of about $80 for
unsanctioned religious services, Gel said, adding that parishioners
take up collections to pay the fines.
   Gel credited Gorbachev's reforms with easing the problems of
Ukrainain Catholics. ``The democratization of society enables a
greater satisfaction of our spiritual needs,'' he said.
   But the church has not been officially recognized. The Russian
Orthodox Church is bitterly opposed to recognition of the Ukrainian
church, claiming it was formed only as a result of a forced split
in the Orthodox Church at the end of the 16th century.
   The Russian Orthodox Church ended its four-day millennium
council Thursday at a monastery in the city of Zagorsk, about 35
miles northeast of Moscow.
   Metropolitan Filaret of Kiev and Galich said the council had
approved construction of a home for old priests and others
connected to the church, in what could be a tentative step away
from government controls on religious activity.
</TEXT>
