<DOCNO> AP880609-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra 2ndLd-Writethru a0782 06-09 1058</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0782,1,050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Prosecutor Seeks Dual-Jury Trial of North, Poindexter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs bgng, `The judge,' to
UPDATE with North comments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution picked Oliver L. North to be
the lead-off defendant in the first of four Iran-Contra conspiracy
trials but suggested trying him with former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh notified U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell of his selection of North but also asked
the judge to consider the alternative of empaneling two juries for
one trial of the fired National Security Council aide and his
former boss.
   Walsh, who also proposed a joint two-jury trial for arms dealers
Albert Hakim and Richard V. Secord, said this procedure still would
protect each defendant's constitutional rights against the
prejudicial use of immunized congressional testimony.
   Gesell ruled Wednesday that four separate trials were necessary
to allow one defendant, say North, to use the immunized
congressional testimony of Hakim or Poindexter, for example, as
evidence to defend the charges against him.
   The judge ruled that because the independent counsel statute
dealt with wrongdoing by high-level government officials, North and
Poindexter should be tried first. He gave Walsh until Friday to
designate the lead-off defendant.
   North indicated he was unconcerned by being selected for the
first trial or being tried separately from his co-defendants.
   ``I guess Winston Churchill probably said it best,'' North told
CBS News. ``He said never give in _ never, never, never give in.
And whether I have to fight this thing out alone in the courtroom
or with others, we will fight it out to the end and in the end, we
will win.''
   In court papers, Walsh said his proposal for two dual-jury
trials ``would meet the court's interest in protecting the rights
of the defendants while alleviating the enormous burdens on the
government of trying each defendant sequentially.''
   In a two-jury trial, one panel would hear the evidence against
one defendant and the other would consider the case against the
second defendant. One of the juries would leave the courtroom
before a defendant introduced evidence prejudicial to the other,
such as immunized congressional testimony.
   Walsh cited seven previous multijury federal court trials in
which the procedure was upheld on appeal.
   These included a 1982 dual-jury bribery trial of two District of
Columbia officials. U.S. District Judge Charles Richey empaneled
two juries because one of the defendants had given a confession
that was inadmissible against the other.
   All the defendants except Secord, a retired Air Force major
general, were given limited grants of immunity from prosecution by
Congress to compel their testimony before the congressional
Iran-Contra hearings last year. Walsh cannot use the immunized
testimony of a defendant against that individual.
   But Gesell has ruled that the defendants could use each other's
immunized testimony to help their defense.
   In his filing Thursday, Walsh said it would be logical to try
Poindexter and North together because they both are accused of
``using their positions of trust and power to facilitate and
protect an illegal financial and logistical network'' to help the
Nicaraguan rebels by privately raising money and diverting profits
from the U.S.-Iran arms sales.
   North, a retired Marine lieutenant-colonel, and Poindexter, a
retired Navy rear admiral, are accused of ``numerous acts of
obstruction of justice and false statements intended to cover up
the activities of the `Enterprise''' Walsh said.
   Similarly, Hakim and Secord, former business partners who
brokered the arms deals through a series of foreign companies and
secret Swiss bank accounts, are both charged with conspiracy to pay
illegal gratuities to North by setting up a $200,000 trust fund for
his family, Walsh said.
   All four defendants are charged with conspiracy to defraud the
government, theft of government property and wire fraud.
   ``The evidence the government would offer at separate trials of
North and Poindexter and of Secord and Hakim would be
overlapping,'' Walsh said. But two dual-jury trials ``offers clear
advantages in terms of judicial efficiency, conservation of the
government's resources and speedy adjudication of the cases.''
   ``Four separate and sequential trials will result in at least
some of the defendants living under the cloud of an indictment for
several months,'' Walsh said.
   ``The government will be forced to incur the substantial expense
of trying four cases involving substantially similar proof and
witnesses, including the costs of maintaining the Office of
Independent Council'' and an elaborately guarded security facility
built at government expense for the defense lawyers to examine
reams of classified documents collected during the investigation.
   Walsh's request for two trials instead f four appeared to be
intended to lessen some of the tactical disadvantages that legal
experts said he would face if forced to try the four defendants
separately.
   Former U.S. Attorney Joseph diGenova said Gesell's ruling on
Wednesday presented Walsh with his ``worst-case scenario.'' He and
other former prosecutors say getting conspiracy convictions is
difficult when only one alleged conspirator is in the courtroom.
   Four separate trials also would force Walsh to disclose evidence
he intends to use against the other defendants long before they
must stand trial. Walsh also would be forced to divide his staff
into four separate trial teams because of the inevitable exposure
to immunized congressional testimony.
   Legal experts said they viewed the North case as the logical
place to start prosecuting because of the breadth of charges
against him. The indictment contains 16 counts against North,
compared with seven naming Poindexter.
   Among the additional charges, North is accused of obstructing
the FBI investigation of the installation of a $15,000 security
fence around his suburban Virginia house and for accepting payment
for it from Secord. He also is accused of pocketing $4,300 of the
$90,000 in travelers checks given to him by a Contra leader to
cover expenses.
   He also is accused of conspiring with two conservative
fund-raisers to use a tax-exempt foundation illegally to raise
private donations for the Nicaraguan rebels.
   ``You pick North first because he is the top banana in terms of
expansiveness'' of the evidence, said diGenova.
   ``It gives you the chance, if you are only to have one trial, to
get most of your evidence in and tell your story about the
conspiracy,'' he said, referring to the possibility of presidential
pardons that might avert subsequent trials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Presbyterians 1stLd-Writethru a0819 06-09 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presbyterians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0819,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Begin Discussions On Christian Response To Nuclear
Arms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf, `Heger said ... and ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE
with panel's actions Thursday night.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Presbyterian statement that would declare
nuclear war immoral went before a church panel Thursday, after foes
of the controversial paper sought a one-year delay for the
3-million-member denomination to discuss it.
   The paper, ``Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age,'' is the
result of a five-year process in the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.),
and has drawn the most interest among issues before the church's
200th General Assembly in St. Louis.
   Other issues include health care, pornography, AIDS, religious
freedom, Central America and concerns including the election next
week of one of the top denominational staff officers.
   The ``Christian Obedience'' paper's recommendations include
declarations that both nuclear war and the theory of nuclear
deterrence are immoral.
   It also discusses tax resisters, saying the church should not
adopt a policy of resistance, but be willing to support its members
who feel called upon to resist.
   The paper also says the decision to go along with government
policy should be as painstakingly taken as the decision to resist.
   Presbyterians for Democracy and Religious Freedom, a sanctioned
group in the denomination, say the paper encourages tax resistance
and does not reflect the majority viewpoint of the nation's largest
Presbyterian denomination.
   The paper is a ``partisan document,'' that gives short shrift to
opposing views, the Rev. Paul Scotchmer, PDRF executive director,
told the assembly Committee on Peacemaking and International
Relations at a hearing Wednesday.
   PDRF President John Boone, a layman from Tennessee, said if the
paper is as solid as its supporters believe, ``it can stand the
test of one year.''
   Also opposing the paper is The Presbyterian Council for
Chaplains and Military Personnel, whose director Charles E.
McMillan told the committee the paper glorifies conscientious
objection while denigrating military service.
   The Rev. Harry Hassell of Highland Park Presbyterian Church in
Dallas, the largest church in the denomination, urged the committee
to replace references to tax resistance with discussions on a
Christian's responsibility to pay taxes while working within the
system for change.
   The committee of 58 clergy, laity, seminary and youth delegates
split up into subcommittees later Thursday, with a 16-member group
assigned to deal with the ``Christian Obedience'' document.
   That group, chaired by the Rev. Thomas J. Heger, a campus
minister from Eugene, Ore., can recommend revisions, withdrawal or
acceptance of the document.
   It will report to the full committee Saturday with the full
assembly scheduled to take up the paper Tuesday night, the next to
last day of the convention.
   Heger said he could not predict how his subcommittee might
handle the report, but in discussions Thursday night, the panel
removed some language and changed other wording in the 5{ pages of
recommendations.
   Panel members felt some language placed resistance to government
policy on the same level as cooperation, and changed language which
they felt could be interpreted as routinely offering financial
support to government resisters.
   Other recommendations which have not been dealt with include
suggestions the church offer legal aid for conscientious objectors
and financial aid for their families.
   A separate recommendation is the creation of a voluntary Fund
for Obedience to Higher Authority ``for those who suffer financial
loss or difficulty as a result of acts of conscience.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
