<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MelanomaVaccine     06-09 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Melanoma Vaccine,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cancer Specialist Begins Patient Trials On Skin Cancer Vaccine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patient trials are beginning on a
vaccine to prevent recurrence of melanoma, a hard-to-treat skin
cancer that strikes about 27,000 Americans eash year, the vaccine's
developer said Thursday.
   ``What it means is there is potential for some hope, and perhaps
we're going to be able to immunize a patient against potential
recurrence,'' said Marc Wallack, a cancer specialist and chairman
of general surgery at Mount Sinai Medical Center.
   He is coordinating a three-year study on at least 200 patients
around the nation who have had melanomas surgically removed but are
at high risk of the cancer returning, spreading and killing them.
   The trials are under way at the University of Florida; Duke
University in Durham, N.C.; M.D. Anderson cancer institute in
Houston; the University of Alabama; and Emory University in
Atlanta, he said.
   Cancer vaccines aren't a new idea, and vaccines for various
cancers are being studied around the nation. They aim to prevent
cancers from returning by ``waking up'' the body's immune system so
it will seek out and destroy cancer cells that may have broken off
a tumor and migrated, thus escaping surgical removal.
   Dr. Philip Livingston of Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New
York is working on a different type of vaccine for melanoma, which
resists traditional chemical and radiation therapies.
   ``I'm not saying one is better than the other, but it's a
different approach,'' said Livingston, whose work uses purified
chemicals taken from cancer cells, while Wallack's uses cancer-cell
membranes mixed with smallpox vaccine virus.
   In Wallack's ``vaccinia melanoma oncolysates'' vaccine, four
types of melanoma cells are infected with smallpox vaccine viruses.
Membranes from infected cells are injected into patients weekly for
13 weeks, and then bi-weekly for the remainder of one year.
Smallpox energizes the immune system, alerting it to the cancer, he
believes.
   The study is double-blind, meaning neither doctors nor patients
know who is getting vaccine and who is injected with a placebo.
During follow-ups, Wallack will compare the cancer recurrence and
survival rates of the two groups of patients.
   Researchers wonder if extracts from the four melanoma cells used
in Wallack's study will trigger immune systems for the dozens of
types of melanoma, Livingston said.
   ``It's a little bit of a shot in the dark in that regard,'' he
said.
   Wallack said the four cell types he's using should prove
effective on all melanomas. And if his preliminary test results are
repeated, the vaccine will help at least 15 percent of the
patients, he said.
   Skin cancers are diagnosed in about 500,000 Americans each year
and are readily cured by surgical removal _ except for advanced
melanoma, recent American Cancer Society figures show. Of about
7,800 annual skin cancer deaths, 5,800 involved melanoma.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
