<HEAD>Reagan Nominates Three Army Major Generals For Three-Star Rank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has nominated three Army
major generals for new assignments and promotions to three-star
rank, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   Assuming Senate confirmation, the Pentagon said Maj. Gen.
Johnnie H. Corns would be promoted to lieutenant general and become
the head of the U.S. Army Japan. Corns, 52, is a native of Gordon,
W.Va., who is currently serving as the commanding general of the
6th Light Infantry Division at Fort Richardson, Alaska.
   Maj. Gen. Leonard P. Wishart III has been nominated for the rank
of lieutenant general and a new assignment as the deputy commanding
general of the U.S. Army Training and Doctrine Command and
commanding general of the Combined Arms Center at Fort Leavenworth,
Kansas, the Pentagon said.
   Wishart, 53, is a native of Newark, N.J. who is currently
serving as the head of the 1st Infantry Division at Fort Riley,
Kansas.
   The third promotion involves Maj. Gen. Robert D. Hammond, the
Pentagon said. He has been nominated for promotion to lieutenant
general and reassignment as the head of the Army Strategic Defense
Command, the Army component of the Star Wars research effort.
   Hammond, 55, is a native of Altadena, Calif., who is currently
serving as the head of the Space and Special Weapons Directorate in
the office of the deputy chief of staff for operations and plans.
