<1ST_LINE>r i AM-East-WestSecurity     06-09 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East-West Security,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Officials Accuse East of `Propaganda' in Disarmament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POTSDAM, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference on East-West security
opened in Potsdam Thursday with strong attacks by Western officials
on what they called ``propagandistic'' disarmament proposals often
put forward by the Soviet bloc.
   Parliamentarian David Owen, leader of Britain's reformist Social
Democratic Party, said he rejects East bloc proposals that all
nuclear weapons be removed from Europe. He called such ideas
``naive nonsense ... and sheer propaganda.''
   ``If the Soviets retain their weapons and Western Europe does
not'' the nuclear threat to the West only increases, Owen said.
   Jack Matlock, the U.S. ambassador in Moscow, also accused the
Soviets of making proposals with propagandistic intentions.
   ``From time to time we face proposals that smack of this,''
Matlock said, without going into specifics.
   Owen also took issue with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
contention at the latest U.S.-Soviet summit that the West has no
right to try to dictate Kremlin human rights policies.
   ``Respect for human rights under internationally agreed norms is
certainly an important area,'' he said.
   Oskar Fischer, East Germany's foreign minister, sided with
Gorbachev on the human rights issue in opening the three-day
conference in this East German city southwest of Berlin. The
conference is being sponsored by the Institute for East-West
Security Studies in New York City.
   Fischer said: ``The meaning of all human rights is turned upside
down if the attempt is made ... to make one's own system of society
and one's own values the measure of all things, and to judge other
states by these standards or even impose one's views on them.''
   He added, ``While we do not force our convictions upon anybody
else, we expect others to do likewise.''
   Fischer also renewed his calls for a nuclear-free corridor about
150 kilometers (93 miles) wide along the borders between NATO and
Warsaw Pact nations.
   Fischer said the Warsaw Pact is ``ready for the most radical
reductions in the conventional field.''
   But he did not say if the Soviet bloc is willing to concede to
the kind of asymmetrical reductions demanded by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
   Fischer also urged both sides to work closer in the economic
sphere, saying:
   ``The arms race is putting an almost unbearable burden on the
economies of both East and West. Engaging in competitive armament
while trying to resolve global problems exceeds the economic
capacities of all our countries.''
   Others scheduled to address the conference include U.S. Commerce
Secretary William Verity; West German Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, and John Whitehead, U.S. deputy secretary
of state.
</TEXT>
