<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-NATO     06-09 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-NATO,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlantic Alliance Wants Human Rights Improvements In East Before
Troop Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and its 15 NATO allies
agreed Thursday to press the Soviet Union for human rights reforms
before entering negotiations to reduce troop concentrations in
Europe.
   Despite the ``glasnost'' or openness initiated by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the allies agreed Soviet practices were
lagging far behind democratic declarations.
   The troop reduction talks are supposed to be held in Vienna
between the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the seven-nation
Warsaw Pact. The idea is to ease tensions from the Atlantic to the
Ural mountains after a 15-year impasse over reducing non-nuclear
forces in Central Europe.
   Summarizing the Western allies' stance at NATO's spring meeting
in the Spanish capital, a senior U.S. official said the decision
was that ``we ought to wait and see what the Soviets do in the area
of human rights first.''
   The official, who held a briefing under condition of anonymity,
said there was ``solid agreement'' on the position among the allies
and that Secretary of State George P. Shultz did not have to take
the lead in persuading the other NATO foreign ministers to go along.
   President Reagan, during his summit trip to Moscow, stressed
failure in Soviet bureaucracy rather than Soviet policy itself for
the deficiencies in the human rights situation.
   But Shultz and his senior advisers are also disappointed that
the reforms promised by Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze in
a pre-summit meeting with Shultz last month in Geneva had not been
adopted _ or found their way to the negotiating table in Vienna.
   Also, the Soviets have not agreed to permit monitors to report
on their compliance with human rights accords and 20 monitors who
were policing the 1975 Helsinki Agreement are still in jail, the
official said.
   The United States also is pressing the Soviets to release
prisoners jailed for their religious beliefs and wants the right of
appeal granted to Soviet citizens who are refused exit permits.
</TEXT>
