<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Britain     06-09 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Britain,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Law Minister Say BBC Representatives May Be Exprelled</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday
suggested it might order representatives of the British
Broadcasting Corp. to leave the country after the BBC aired a film
on children detained without charge in South Africa.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said a BBC spokesman phoned
his office Wednesday, asking for comment on allegations in the film
about torture of children during interrogation by police.
   Vlok said that when his spokesman, Leon Mellet, asked why the
comment had not been sought beforehand, the interviewer said,
``Quite frankly, the BBC does not believe the South African
government.''
   Vlok said, ``If this is the BBC's attitude, then why should the
South African government continue to host their representatives in
our country?''
   Vlok made his comments at a briefing to the President's Council,
an advisory body to President P.W. Botha.
   The South African government had appealed to the BBC for a
chance to view the film, ``Suffer the Children,'' before it was
broadcast Wednesday night. The BBC refused.
   The government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. reported
Thursday evening, ``There is a question mark over future BBC
representation in South Africa after the televising of a program
last night in which allegations were made about mistreatment of
minor children in detention in the country.''
   A spokesman for the BBC in London, who refused to be identified
in accordance with British custom, said, ``Naturally, the BBC
regrets any action which would impede our coverage from South
Africa.''
   The BBC said it commissioned the report from an independent
London-based company, Penumbra, which filmed inside South Africa
without government permission and without seeking police comment
because of emergency restrictions on the news media.
   Vlok also lashed out at members of the Detainees Parents Support
Committee, whose monthly reports on the numbers of people held
under emergency detention were widely quoted by local and foreign
news organizations as a reliable monitor during the past two years
of the national emergency.
   ``My warning to these people is: Stop it, or your wings will be
clipped,'' Vlok said. He did not elaborate.
   The government has refused, even in Parliament, to give detailed
information about the numbers of people held in detention, but has
frequently challenged the support committee to prove its figures,
based on interviews with families of missing people throughout the
country.
   In February, the support committee was one of 17 organizations
the government banned from all activity. Members of the group,
however, continued to make statements as individuals and one of
them, Max Coleman, has been engaged in a public debate with Vlok
for the past week about whether or not children under 16 remain in
detention.
   Vlok says 80 minors, none of them under 16, are now in detention.
   He accused the members of the support group of trying to
``destroy the morale, image and functions of the South African
security forces through its slanted, biased allegations and lies.
</TEXT>
