<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     06-09 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Says Hindus Harassed Because of Religious Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition party leader Sheik Hasina
told 10,000 people at a rally on Thursday that Hindus were being
harassed following Parliament's passage of a measure that makes
Islam the state religion.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad was expected to sign the
legislation Saturday, said an opposition politician, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Hasina, leader of the Awami League, and Khaleda Zia, head of the
Bangladesh Nationalist Party, have sponsored a campaign to oust
Ershad since November. Ershad, a former general, first took power
in a bloodless coup in 1982.
   The two opposition leaders and a leftist alliance of five
smaller anti-government parties said earlier they will hold an
eight-hour national strike Sunday to protest the Islamic bill.
   Hasina told the rally Thursday, ``We have reports that Hindus in
southern Gopalganj District and non-Moslem tribals in different
parts of the country are being threatened that their land will be
taken away by force.''
   She did not say who made the threats. Gopalganj lies 55 miles
southwest of Dhaka. Most tribesmen in Bangladesh are Buddhist, but
some are Christian.
   She urged Bangladeshis to rise up against the law and added,
``Our protests against the Islamic law will continue.''
   The measure passed by Parliament on Tuesday amends the
constitution by inserting the sentence: ``The religion of the
republic is Islam, but other religions may be practiced in peace
and harmony.''
   Parliament passed the bill, 254-0, after 15 opposition lawmakers
walked out in protest. Ershad's Jatiya Party holds 252 seats in the
300-member assembly. All voted for the bill and were joined by two
independents.
   Not all assembly members were present.
   Opponents contend that fundamentalist Moslems may use the
amendment to try to impose Islamic strictures on Bangladesh,
including Koranic law.
   More than 85 percent of Bangladesh's 105 million people are
Moslems, but the state has been secular since its creation in 1971.
The minority groups are Hindu, Christian and Buddhist.
   Within minutes of the bill's passage, thousands of people took
to the streets of the capital in protest. At least 30 people were
injured and 35 cars and buses damaged during protests Tuesday and
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
