<DOCNO> AP880609-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Walesa     06-09 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Walesa,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Applies for Passport for ILO Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said
Thursday he had applied for a passport to attend the annual
conference of the International Labor Organization in Geneva.
   The organization, an agency of the United Nations, groups
workers, employers and management representatives.
   ``I want to represent the working people who identify with
Solidarity,'' said Walesa, leader of the free trade union
federation that was outlawed after the 1981 imposition of martial
law in Poland.
   Speaking from his home, Walesa said he wrote the Foreign
Ministry asking for help in obtaining a business travel passport,
even though, ``I will represent a somewhat different point of view
than our government.''
   Government spokesman Zbigniew Augustynowicz said Walesa, winner
of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, had not filed all the documents
required. He had no comment on Walesa's prospects for getting a
passport.
   The application comes a month after Walesa helped lead an
illegal strike at the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk that ended without a
settlement May 10.
   All five workers in Poland's delegation to the International
Labor Organization conference belong to government-approved trade
unions, though one is a former Solidarity member.
   Two Western trade union groups _ the International Confederation
of Free Trade Unions and the World Confederation of Labor _
challenged the credentials of Poland's delegation because it does
not include any Solidarity members, the second year in a row they
have done this.
   Poland gave notice of its intention to withdraw from the
International Labor Organization in 1984 after being censured for
banning Solidarity, but it withdrew that notice last year.
   Poland regained full-fledged membership in the organization on
Wednesday after promising to repay $9 million in arrears.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 2337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlantBlast     06-09 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Orders Weekly Inspections At Rocket Fuel Oxidizer Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Bryan said Thursday he has
ordered weekly state inspections when production resumes at the
only U.S. plant making a fuel component crucial for military
rockets and the space shuttle.
   Bryan said he will not try to block the resumption next week of
ammonium perchlorate production at the Kerr-McGee Corp. plant here.
   ``We are under the impression the fire department believes all
their concerns were met,'' Bryan said.
   The plant came under scrutiny after the only other U.S. plant
manufacturing the rocket fuel oxidizer was destroyed in a series of
explosions May 4 that killed two people and caused an estimated $73
million damage.
   Bryan ordered the state Division of Occupational Safety and
Health to begin inspecting the Kerr-McGee plant in unannounced
weekly visits. He also said he wants to work with federal officials
to minimize the plant's storage of ammonium perchlorate.
   Kerr-McGee officials said the company will resume production of
ammonium perchlorate Monday morning. The plant had been shut down
since May 12 after state officials threatened to sue the company
for creating a public hazard.
   Clark County Fire Chief Roy Parrish said Thursday he was
withholding approval on resumption of production until the district
attorney's office reviews a letter sent by Kerr-McGee that company
officials said answers the fire department's concerns.
   Anita Bridges, a Kerr-McGee spokeswoman, said the company hired
independent safety experts to inspect the plant and has ``done
everything humanly possible to try to alleviate the fears and
concerns of our operation.''
   The Kerr-McGee plant can make 36 million pounds a year of
ammonium perchlorate, the oxidizier used on space shuttle boosters
and military and civilian rockets. The destroyed Pacific
Engineering & Production Co. plant had the capacity to produce 20
million pounds per year.
   The House Committee on Science, Space and Technology was told in
a recent hearing that demand for ammonium perchlorate would rise
from 37.8 million pounds this year to more than 60 million pounds
in 1989.
   Each set of shuttle boosters uses 1.7 million pounds of ammonium
perchlorate, and National Aeronautics and Space Administration
officials said Wednesday that the agency had eight booster rockets
on hand, enough for four flights.
   Richard Truly, chief of NASA's space flight program, said the
agency's schedule of nine missions next year might have to be
adjusted, depending on how long the shortage lasts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
