<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DigestBriefs     06-09 1432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Digest Briefs,1489</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: This package does not contain the following items from the
News Digest: SEOUL, South Korea _ South Korea; JERUSALEM _ Israel;
MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ Nicaragua; UNDATED _ Political Rdp; BOSTON_
Dual Dukakis; GIZA PLATEAU, Egypt _ Sphinx-Sewage.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution picked Oliver L. North to be
the lead-off defendant in the first of four Iran-Contra conspiracy
trials but suggested trying him with former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh notified U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell of his selection of North but also asked
the judge to consider the alternative of empaneling two juries for
one trial of the fired National Security Council aide and his
former boss.
   Walsh, who also proposed a joint two-jury trial for arms dealers
Albert Hakim and Richard V. Secord, said this procedure still would
protect each defendant's constitutional rights against the
prejudicial use of immunized congressional testimony.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 69-27 Thursday to choke off a
filibuster that has blocked action on a bill permitting the death
penalty for major drug dealers who kill police officers.
   The decision sets up a vote on the bill Friday that supporters
and opponents agreed probably would result in approval.
   ``This sends the message that we're not going to tolerate the
kind of warfare we're seeing on the streets of our cities,'' Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., chief author of the bill, told his
colleagues.
   But opponents such as Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash., derided the
measure as an election-year attempt to appease public demands to do
something about illegal drugs. They also noted the death penalty
already exists in many states and it hasn't deterred drug pushers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab summit called to discuss the
PLO-guided rebellion against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip ended Thursday with agreement by rich Arab nations to
subsidize the uprising.
   A communique issued at the end of the three-day summit said:
``The conference stresses its full commitment to extend all support
needed to secure the continuation and escalation of the uprising
under the leadership of the PLO.''
   Eight delegation chiefs, including the four wealthiest nations,
devised a formula in a 2{-hour meeting for subsidies to the
Palestinians and to Syria and Jordan, which are in the forefront of
the confrontation with Israel.
   In the communique, the 21 Arab League members again designated
the Palestine Liberation Organization as the ``sole legitimate
representative'' of the 5 million Palestinians.
   They also agreed to oppose any peace initiative that excludes
PLO participation and to demand an international peace conference
giving equal status to all concerned parties, including the PLO.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the Communist Party firebrand
and fallen protege of Mikhail S. Gorbachev, has been elected to
attend a party conference where he and other reformers may square
off against conservatives over Gorbachev's reforms.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Thursday
that Yeltsin will attend this month's 19th Communist Party
Conference.
   The presence of the outspoken, acid-tongued Yeltsin, who was
ousted in November as Moscow party boss, may make for lively debate
at the nationwide conference, the party's first in 47 years.
   The election of Yeltsin to the party conference continues the
roller-coaster career of the 57-year-old Russian who was fired as
Moscow party boss and stripped of his post as a non-voting member
of the Politburo because of a speech he gave to the Central
Committee in October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy issued an ``urgent notice'' to
Americans on Thursday after China warned that terrorists from
another country may be planning attacks on Americans living in the
Chinese capital.
   The unprecedented warning caused the U.S. Embassy to issue an
alert to the 1,500 Americans living in China that they should take
measures to protect themselves, said U.S. consular official Dewey
Pendergrass.
   The embassy said high-level Chinese public security officials
told the embassy Wednesday of possible terror attacks on Americans
by an unspecified third country. The Chinese did not give specific
information about the terrorists or what kind of attacks might be
planned.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California research team has isolated from
an African blood sample a strain of virus that can cause a fatal
AIDS-like disease by infecting, but not killing, cells in the human
body.
   Jay A. Levy, leader of the University of California at San
Francisco team that made the discovery, said Thursday that the new
isolated strain may be an important new tool in the development of
an effective drug against the AIDS virus.
   A University of Alabama-Birmingham team isolated still another
new virus strain from the family that causes AIDS-like disease in
Africa. George M. Shaw, leader of that team, said it appears to be
less virulent than virus strains identified earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Announcement of the first program to
distribute hypodermic needles to drug users has sparked a debate
between those who say the plan will curb the spread of AIDS and
those who say it will encourage drug use.
   ``It's like trying to put out a fire with gasoline,'' said Lon
Mabon, executive director of the Oregon Citizens Alliance, a
conservative political group opposed to the project.
   Outside-In, a Portland social service agency, will use a $67,000
grant from the American Foundation for AIDS Research to conduct the
nation's first test to determine if exchanging used needles for
new, sanitary ones will curb the spread of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome. Sharing needles has been one of the main ways
for transmitting the human immunodeficiency virus that causes AIDS.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials recommended Thursday
that all pregnant women be tested for hepatitis and that newborns
of infected women be vaccinated, to prevent 3,500 babies a year
from becoming potentially doomed hepatitis carriers.
   The Centers for Disease Control, which in 1984 recommended
type-B hepatitis tests for women in high-risk groups _ such as
injectible drug abusers and some venereal disease patients _ said
Thursday that many obstetricians don't know what the high-risk
groups are, and the plan has not worked.
   ``It is now evident that routine screening of all pregnant women
is the only strategy that will provide acceptable control'' of
mother-to-child hepatitis B transmission, the CDC said in its
weekly report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A genetically engineered human hormone holds out
the promise of a safer, more effective and more accessible
treatment for one of the most common causes of infertility in
women, according to a study.
   ``It does everything we want it to do so far,'' Dr. James Simon
said of the hormone, produced by recombinant gene-splicing
technology and called rechLH.
   ``In primate testing, rechLH initiated ovulation, it helped
stimulate normal hormonal production through the entire menstrual
cycle, the eggs were fertile and the monkeys produced embryos,'' he
said.
   ``But until we try it in humans, we can't be sure all the
advantages are real,'' said Simon, one of four authors of the study
that appears in Friday's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of students bused for integration in
Seattle will be halved by 1989, school officials said Thursday
after the first major city to desegregate its classrooms without a
court order adopted a system to educate many pupils closer to home.
   Seattle is adopting a cluster school concept designed after one
instituted in Cambridge, Mass., in 1981. The plan divides Seattle
into eight racially balanced clusters, each with six to 10 schools
from which parents have a ``controlled choice'' of schools.
   Michael Alves, a Massachusetts consultant who has worked on
similar efforts across the country, pronounced the plan
``first-rate'' after it was adopted unanimously Wednesday night by
the city's seven-member school board.
   ``It will maintain desegregated schools, it should work in a way
that is fair, and I think it is constitutionally defensible,''
Alves said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a subdued setting of marble and etched glass,
bettors on Saturday's 120th running of the Belmont Stakes will drop
thousands of dollars while dining on the likes of Caesar salad or
lobster tails.
   It's called upscale wagering, and New York's Off-Track Betting
Corp. is counting on this as the course of its future.
   The restaurant in Manhattan's Wall Street financial district
with its thick carpeting, brass rails and maroon and sporting-green
decor is one of two opened within the last two years by OTB in the
city. Scattered through its rooms are 11 betting windows for
parimutuel wagers at track odds and several huge screens for
watching races.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
