<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-20-20 Adv10   06-09 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-20-20, Adv 10,0877</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, June 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>`20-20' Celebrates Once Unlikely 10th Anniversary; Cronkite `At
Large'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This time last year, the odds that ABC's
``20-20'' would celebrate its 10th anniversary, as it does tonight
with a two-hour retrospective, seemed about 50-50.
   When ABC Entertainment President Brandon Stoddard announced he
was moving ``20-20'' from its long-time Thursday time period to
Friday, many people, including ``20-20'' co-host Hugh Downs,
complained loudly.
   ``I finally called (ABC President) John Sias a few weeks after
we went on, and I said, `I feel apologetic about all the public
moaning I was doing about the `dumb' move to Friday,''' Downs said
in a telephone interview from Los Angeles, where he was attending
the network affiliates' meeting.
   ``I'm very pleased that it came out all right, but it may be
that I'm not off base to think it's a tribute to the strength of
the show to virtually break tradition. People don't usually cross
calendar lines to follow a show that they like, and, by George!
people did.''
   ``20-20'' held its own in the ratings, finishing the season a
respectable 49th out of 85 regularly scheduled programs.
   Downs, who recently celebrated 40 years in the business, and
co-host Barbara Walters are no doubt a big reason for the show's
following. A proven team, they were paired years ago as co-hosts on
NBC's ``Today'' show.
   ``A major, major, major reason for the success of `20-20' is
Hugh and Barbara,'' said executive producer Victor Neufeld. ``I
think they have developed over the years one of the best-liked and
well-respected hosting teams in television. The chemistry is
perfect.
   ``Here's Barbara, the high-powered, major worldwide broadcasting
entity-slash-interviewer, sitting next to Hugh Downs, a gentleman,
an easy-going, respected but well-liked individual who is perfect
counter.''
   Other correspondents have included Silvia Chase and Geraldo
Rivera, who are no longer with the show, Tom Jarriel, Bob Brown,
John Stossel, Lynn Sherr and Stone Phillips. All are featured in
the retrospective.
   ``We work very hard at the concept of being close to our
viewers,'' said Neufeld. ``We do pieces that reflect what we think
is ... of interest around the country. We are not into ourselves
and do stories we think we want to do.''
   Although at the time Stoddard said he was confident the
``20-20'' audience would follow it to Fridays, he did assure
concerned television critics and viewers that the program would get
a new time rather than be canceled if its ratings dropped.
   Now, says Downs with a laugh, ``I'm content if they leave it on
Friday. I wouldn't want to move back to Thursday, in other words.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CRONKITE AT LARGE _ Walter Cronkite, who hopes to carve out some
additional air time in his contract renegotiations with CBS, gets
his first prime-time exposure of 1988 on Saturday with ``Walter
Cronkite at Large.''
   Cronkite, in a recent interview, declined to comment on the
negotiations, only to say, ``I think both sides are hopeful we can
come to a happy relationship again to continue the 38 years of my
association with the company. I can't characterize the negotiations
at the moment _ `open and continuing.'''
   Cronkite, the long-time anchor of the ``CBS Evening News,''
stepped down in 1981 and was succeeded by Dan Rather. Since then he
has been a special correspondent, anchoring irregularly scheduled
specials.
   Under Cronkite's contract, negotiated in 1980, his annual salary
drops from approximately $1 million to $150,000 when he turns 72 in
November, and he becomes a consultant rather than correspondent.
After Cronkite suggested publicly that he would be free to work on
other networks, CBS began negotiating to keep the symbol of CBS
News at CBS.
   Cronkite said he wouldn't mind continuing to do the ``At Large''
series, which allows him to travel widely doing stories of personal
interest.
   Saturday's edition features an update on the predictions of 20
years ago that the environment would be ruined by now without
protection; a report on Macau, a gambling center that will become
in a few years the property of distinctly anti-gambling communist
China, and a travelogue on hot-air ballooning in France.
   ``It's kind of an ideal program to do. Whether that's the exact
format of future programming I might do, I just don't know,''
Cronkite said. ``I think that's something for us to examine when we
kind of come to a decision what our relationship is.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   MAGNUM ENSHRINED _ Thomas Magnum's Detroit Tigers cap and
Hawaiian shirt will be donated to the Smithsonian Institution's
National Museum of American History in a ceremony June 22.
``Magnum, P.I.'' recently ended an eight-year run on CBS. The
Tigers cap, a tip of the hat to star Tom Selleck's hometown, and
the Hawaiian shirt were trademarks of the private eye, as was his
military cap from Vietnam. Museum curator Charlie McGovern said,
according to ``Magnum'' publicists, that the items were of special
interest to the museum because ``Magnum'' was the first television
show to deal with life after Vietnam for veterans.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 10</NOTE>
