<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights TwoTakes   06-09 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, Two Takes,0492</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has handed President Reagan a
victory on the trade issue, narrowly sustaining his veto and
refusing to enact a 1,000-page trade bill over his objections.
   On the 61-37 vote Wednesday, 10 Republicans abandoned the White
House and supported the override, while two Democrats voted to
sustain Reagan's second veto of a major trade bill in three years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
warned that a further decline of the dollar in foreign exchange
would not help improve the nation's trade deficit.
   Greenspan told a news briefing Wednesday at the International
Monetary Conference that the deterioration of the dollar ``will
augment the dollar-denominated U.S. trade deficit rather than
implement further progress.''
   Because U.S. manufacturers already are running at capacity or
near-capacity levels, further declines could not do anything to
help them sell more goods overseas or anywhere else, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Securities and Exchange
Commission defended his agency against charges by a House
investigator that it has failed to aggressively pursue insider
trading by foreigners.
   Citing the SEC's work in negotiating cooperation pacts with
Canada, Japan and other countries, Chairman David S. Ruder said
Wednesday: ``The commission has made substantial progress in recent
years, and expects to conclude additional agreements in the near
future.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audi of America Inc. said it was vindicated by a
proposed settlement of a class-action lawsuit charging that some of
its cars accelerate on their own, but consumer advocates called the
agreement a bad deal.
   Under the proposed settlement, Audi agreed to offer rebates of
$300 to $2,000 to 390,000 current or former owners of Audi 5000
sedans with automatic transmissions _ if they buy a new Audi
between Sept. 1, 1988, and June 30, 1991. The deal applies to Audi
5000 sedans built between 1978 and 1986.
   ``We've said all along there is nothing wrong with our cars,
there is no defect causing unintended acceleration,'' said Audi
spokesman Tom McDonald Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York investment banker Nicholas Brady is a
