<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Macmillan Bjt   06-09 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan, Bjt,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan, Bass To Face Off In Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: hearing begins at 1:30 pm EDT; lead prospects unlikely.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover target Macmillan Inc. and Texas
billionaire Robert M. Bass will face off today in court, where a
judge will decide whether the publishing giant can proceed with a
controversial restructuring plan.
   Macmillan rejected Bass's latest $1.9 billion buyout offer on
Wednesday, saying its restructuring plan is more beneficial to
shareholders.
   At a hearing in Delaware Chancery Court set for this afternoon,
Bass attorneys will seek to halt a dividend payout, which marks the
first phase of the restructuring, on grounds that Macmillan
directors have breached their fiduciary duties by failing to get
the best price for shareholders.
   Macmillan attorney Dennis Block defended the plan as ``perfectly
appropriate'' and providing ``substantial value to shareholders at
this time and (giving) them continuing equity interest in the
future of the company.''
   The restructuring plan would split the company into two publicly
held entities and pay shareholders a special dividend of $52.35 a
share. The dividend is scheduled to be paid Friday, and Macmillan
stressed it is proceeding on schedule.
   The time limit is extremely tight, and both sides likely would
prefer the judge to rule from the bench.
   Robert Dunlap Jr., an analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman &
Co., said if Macmillan ``manages to pay the dividend on Friday, it
would appear management has won.''
   Attorneys close to the deal say it is likely the Bass request,
which has drawn support from the aggressive New York investment
firm Coniston Partners, will result in at least a temporary delay
in the payout.
   Coniston, which has accumulated a 4.9 percent stake in
Macmillan, filed an affidavit in support of Bass's effort to block
the dividend payout.
   ``We're interested in seeing a full auction for the company and
having it sold to the highest bidder,'' said Coniston principal
Augustus Oliver, who pegged Macmillan's value at between $85 to
$100 a share.
   He would not comment on whether the partnership might make its
own bid for Macmillan.
   But one source close to the battle speculated that Coniston ``is
in it for the money _ they don't want to buy the company,'' and
that the partnership's affidavit was merely an attempt to ensure it
gets ``fair value for its stock.''
   Bass has offered to acquire the company for $73 a share in cash,
or, alternatively, to restructure it in a similar fashion. But
Bass, who owns about 9.1 percent of Macmillan's roughly 26 million
outstanding shares, offered to pay shareholders a dividend of $58 a
share.
   Macmillan plans to separate into Macmillan Publishing Co. and
Macmillan Information Co. In addition to the dividend, shareholders
would receive for each Macmillan share a half-share of common stock
in Macmillan Information and $4.50 in principal amount of Macmillan
Information subordinated debentures.
   On Wall Street, Macmillan rose 62{ cents a share to close at $76
on the New York Stock Exchange Wednesday.
   Coniston, fresh from its recent, unsuccessful proxy battle for
four seats on the board of Gillette Co., typically purchases a
large stake in a company and then pressures management to
restructure or take other action to boost its stock price.
   Macmillan has filed its own suit in federal District Court for
the Southern District of New York, charging Bass and his affiliates
with violating securities laws, repeatedly filing and disseminating
false information and engaging in a ``creeping tenders.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ConsumerElectronics Bjt   06-09 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Consumer Electronics, Bjt,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computers Aren't Enough _ U.S. Must Build Televisions, Companies
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States needs to build televisions,
not just computers, in order to remain a high-tech superpower into
the 21st century, some of the nation's technology giants say.
   International Business Machines Corp., Apple Computer Inc.,
Hewlett-Packard Co., American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and others
agreed this week that a strong consumer electronics industry is
critical to a strong technology base.
   The companies agreed Tuesday to form a task force to study how
U.S. companies can catch up to the Japanese in the next generation
of televisions _ electronics-crammed models that will produce
pictures nearly as sharp as magazine photos.
   At stake is a market that will grow to $40 billion a year
worldwide by the year 2010, as well as competence in a whole range
of related technologies, from speedy computer chips to advanced
signal processing.
   Zenith Electronics Corp. of Glenview, Ill., is the only
U.S.-based company still making televisions, and it lost money on
them last year.
   The announcement of the task force on high-definition television
is an acknowledgment of the damage the United States has suffered
by allowing its consumer electronics business to wither.
   ``They're finally learning what the Japanese have known for
years,'' said William Hassinger, assistant bureau chief for
engineering in the Mass Media Bureau of the Federal Communications
Commission. ``As the Japanese have found out, you can use consumer
electronics as a sort of economic engine to pull a train that has a
lot of other things in it.''
   The task force, created at a meeting in Santa Clara, Calif., of
the American Electronics Association, will be headed by Alexander
Stark, a senior vice president of AT&T, and Richard Elkus, chairman
of Santa Clara-based Prometrix Corp., a maker of semiconductor
production equipment.
   The task force is supposed to size up the situation and report
back in 30 days.
   Experts say consumer products ranging from compact disk players
to videocassette recorders have become so advanced that in some
respects they are more sophisticated than mainframe computers or
nuclear missiles.
   In fact, Japanese companies sell a large proportion of the
components for American weaponry even though they never set out to
create a military hardware industry. It was a spin-off from their
other product lines.
   Hassinger said the attempt to start up a television business
would be complicated by such things as the need to set up
dealerships, distributors, repair arrangements, advertising and a
base of customers.
   As for finding people to build them, he said, ``We have the
people here, but they're scattered around. It's hard to assemble a
well-coordinated design crew.''
   With enough effort, there is still time for the United States to
get into the market for advanced television.
   The televisions will start out at $2,500 or $3,500 when they
reach the market in the early 1990s, and even by roughly 2001 will
only capture about 1 percent of the world television market,
estimated John Hatch, a spokesman for the American Electronics
Association.
   After that, though, the market will take off, reaching $20
billion a year in the United States and $40 billion a year
worldwide by 2010, Hatch predicted.
   One of the critical issues in high-definition television is how
to set standards for the new technology. The standards that are
picked will affect how well the United States can compete with the
Japanese.
   Some U.S.-based companies are concerned that Japanese companies
could exert strong influence on the way standards are set in the
United States through their influence in the consumer electronics
group of the U.S.-based Electronic Industries Association.
   Zenith dropped out of the association last September,
complaining it was ``dominated by foreign concerns,'' but continues
to participate in its standard-setting efforts.
   But Mark Rosenker, the vice president for public affairs at the
Electronic Industries Association, said the organization is working
closely with other organizations such as the National Association
of Broadcasters and wants to create a standard that is acceptable
to everyone.
   ``If we don't have consensus, we could have a disaster on our
hands,'' Rosenker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PanAmSale Bjt   06-09 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pan Am Sale, Bjt,0780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Pan Am Plan to Sell Assets Shows Financial
Desperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. is in such desperate financial
straits that it was forced to take the drastic step of proposing to
sell the bulk of its assets, financial analysts say.
   The company said Wednesday that its board of directors had
authorized management to sell the assets if no agreement can be
reached on labor concessions with three holdout unions.
   Pan Am, the nation's eighth largest airline, also plans to
reduce its flight operations more than normal after the peak summer
travel season.
   ``It is a fact that Pan Am's (financial) condition is the worst
in the industry,'' said Julius Maldutis, an airline analyst for
investment firm Salomon Brothers Inc. ``There are some great risks
associated with this strategy, but (Pan Am) had no choice.''
   Among those risks, he said, are the possibility that potential
passengers could be scared away from Pan Am flights because of the
impending sales and that many frequent fliers on the airline could
stampede to cash in their travel awards.
   Pan Am had a net loss of $83.3 million in the first quarter and
is saddled with about $900 million in debt. The airline posted
staggering net losses of $265.3 million in 1987 and $462.8 million
in 1986.
   The two unions representing pilots and flight engineers agreed
in January to wage cuts and work rule changes that are to save Pan
Am $240 million over three years, but analysts have estimated the
airline needs total savings of around $540 million over that period
to ensure its financial recovery.
   The flight attendants, Teamsters and transport workers unions,
on the other hand, have resisted taking pay cuts.
   In exchange for the concessions from the pilots and flight
engineers, Pan Am undertook a major management shakeup in January
in which the chairman and other top executives were replaced.
   The plan to sell assets was widely viewed as a last-ditch
attempt to pressure the three recalcitrant unions as well as a
measure of Pan Am's financial desperation.
   ``I don't think (Pan Am Chairman Thomas G. Plaskett) had a lot
of choice,'' said John Pincavage, who follows the industry for
investment firm PaineWebber Inc. ``In many respects, it's a warning
shot.''
   Plaskett told airline employees about the asset sales in a
letter mailed Tuesday night.
   The board's decision authorized the sale of any of the assets of
Pan American World Airways, the company's main subsidiary,
``without limitation, including route segments and divisions,
maintenance and terminal facilities, aircraft, engines and other
equipment,'' Plaskett wrote.
   The only Pan Am assets that would not be considered for sale,
Plaskett said, are its profitable Northeast shuttle service and Pan
Am World Services, which provides ground services to other carriers
in airports around the world.
   If agreement was reached with the holdout unions, there is ``a
very good possibility'' that the assets might not be sold, Pan Am
spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said Wednesday.
   The company had no specific timetable for selling the assets,
she said.
   ``I'm taking the letter at face value; I presume that they're
serious'' about selling assets, said Margaret Brennan, the head of
the flight attendants union at Pan Am who also heads the Joint
Labor Council representing the five unions there.
   Brennan said the authorization to sell could be a tactic to
force the three unions into making concessions. She cautioned,
however, that ``I don't think they're going to accomplish anything
with (the flight attendants) like this.''
   William Genoese, director of the Teamsters union's Airline
Division, said he was considering calling a rally of his members to
protest the Pan Am move. ``They have to sit down with us,'' he said.
   The 4,500-member Teamsters union at Pan Am threatened a strike
against the carrier last winter and vowed ``guerrilla war'' tactics
including deliberate diversions of baggage.
   Plaskett said in his letter that as a first step in its new
plan, Pan Am will ``substantially reduce'' the level of its flight
operations in the fourth quarter, far beyond the normal seasonal
reduction following the summer peak.
   Pan Am also will close its flight service base in San Francisco
on Oct. 1, and will return two 747 aircraft to their lessors when
their leases expire at the end of the summer, he said.
   ``I am very disappointed that our inability to secure the cost
reductions we so desperately need to continue implementing our
growth plan has necessitated these and other planned actions,''
Plaskett wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
