<1ST_LINE>r f BC-DesertPartners-USG     06-09 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Desert Partners-USG,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Desert Partners Terminates Offer For USG</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desert Partners L.P., which recently lost a
proxy battle for six seats on USG Corp.'s board, on Thursday
formally terminated its $2.2 billion tender offer for the
Chicago-based building materials concern.
   Despite the move, Desert Partners, headed by Texas oilmen Cyril
Wagner, Jr. and Jack E. Brown, said it ``continues to believe that
it would be desirable for it to acquire control of USG.''
   The partnership had offered $42 a share in cash for up to 39
million of USG's 45.7 million common shares it did not already own.
Including debt securities, the deal carried a value of $2.2 billion.
   USG, which had resisted all takeover overtures, bounced back
with its own restructuring plan that includes paying shareholders
$37 a share in a cash dividend and notes valued at $5 per USG
share. The company estimated the plan will cost $2.2 billion.
   In a statement, Desert Partners said it will ``continue to
evaluate its ownership position and ... may at any time decide to
purchase additional shares.'' Conversely, the partnership also said
it might sell all or part of its stake.
   Last month USG shareholders backed the company's slate of
candidates by a 56-41 percent margin over those proposed by Desert
Partners.
</TEXT>
