<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade following some badly needed and
unexpectedly widespread rain in the Midwest.
   Showers brought slight relief Wednesday to much of Iowa,
Illinois and Indiana, which together produce most of the Midwest's
corn and soybeans.
   But predictions for another spell of hot, dry weather limited
the early rain-related losses, analysts said.
   ``I think the markets overdid it yesterday,'' said Joel Karlin,
an analyst in Chicago with Research Department Inc. ``Admittedly,
we did have about 40 percent rain coverage, particularly in Iowa,
but that will be mitigated by the fact we're supposed to have a
return to hot, dry conditions by this weekend.''
   The U.S. oat crop got no reprieve from the punishing weather,
however. Karlin said that unless it rains within the next week in
the northern Plains, ``you might as well kiss the oat and spring
wheat crops goodbye.''
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.70{ a bushel; corn was 7{ cents
lower to 2 cents higher with July at $2.45 a bushel; oats were 2
cents to 9{ cents higher with July at at $2.43 a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 8 cents lower with July at $8.53{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were sharply lower,
with some contracts down the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit, in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .27 cent lower to .10 cent higher with June at
72.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with August at 75.50 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to
1.15 cents lower with June at 50.75 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.77 cents to 2 cents lower with July at 50.87 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Wednesday.
