<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Trade Bjt   06-09 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Down For 13th Month In Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus fell 21 percent to $5.05
billion in May, the 13th straight month the surplus has decreased
from its level of a year earlier, the Finance Ministry said
Thursday.
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States fell 25.6 percent
to $3.30 billion from $4.44 billion in May 1987. It was also down
from $4.13 billion the previous month.
   Economists were divided over whether the trade deficit would
continue to shrink.
   ``In a word, I think we can say things have been moving in a
desirable direction,'' said Toshiaki Kakimoto, chief economist at
Sumitomo Bank Ltd.
   Imports are likely to continue to grow while the yen's
appreciation and the shift in production to overseas by Japanese
manufacturers will restrain exports, leading to a continued drop in
the trade surplus, Kakimoto said.
   But it is possible the trade surplus will not diminish further
in coming months, said Yoshihiro Furukane, senior economist at
Yamaichi Research Institute of Economics.
   Although imports are growing, exports are also up because
Japanese manufacturers have found ways to cope with the strength of
the yen, Furukane said.
   May's overall trade surplus was down from $6.42 billion in the
same month last year and from $6.77 billion in April, according to
figures the ministry released.
   Japan's trade surplus has shrunk in comparison with the same
month a year earlier since May 1987, reflecting the sharp rise in
the value of the yen and expanding domestic demand in the Japanese
economy.
   Imports surged 26.7 percent to $15.45 billion from $12.2 billion
in May 1987, although they dipped 1.7 percent from April's $15.7
billion.
   Exports also continued to show considerable growth, though the
pace of increase has varied from month to month recently.
   Exports were up 10.2 percent to $20.5 billion from $18.6 billion
in May 1987, but showed an 8.8 percent drop from $22.5 billion in
April of this year.
   Imports of manufactured goods continued to be strong, accounting
for 48.6 percent of the country's total imports in May. That was
down slightly from 49.9 percent in April.
   The Finance Ministry trade figures were calculated on a
customs-clearance basis, with shipping and insurance costs included
for imports but not for exports. Japan's trade surplus would have
been larger if the costs had been included in both categories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
