<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Hutton-Broker 2ndLd-Writethru   06-09 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hutton-Broker, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broker Pleads Guilty To Hutton Money Laundering Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to Brian, sted Brain</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former E.F. Hutton & Co. Inc. broker
has pleaded guilty to charges stemming from his role in a
money-laundering scheme conducted at the brokerage firm's
Providence office
   Brian J. Lareau pleaded guilty Wednesday to one count of
violating the Social Security Act and one money-laundering count
before U.S. District Court Judge Francis J. Boyle.
   Lareau, 46, of Jamestown, worked for the Hutton branch from 1980
to 1985. He admitted to laundering $183,950 from August 1982 to
October 1984.
   Federal authorities said Lareau, and another former broker,
since deceased, helped clients hide about $1.5 million in cash from
the Internal Revenue Service.
   According to court documents, Lareau created a fictitious
account and used it to conceal his customer's money from the
Securities and Exchange Commission and the IRS.
   The fake Social Security number was used on the account over a
four-year period every time Lareau and the client transacted
business, said Voorhees.
   Another former Hutton broker, Stephen S. Fusco, who died two
years ago of cancer, was also charged with being involved in the
office's scheme. Fusco was accused of helping members of organized
crime turn illegally earned money into legitimate income.
   The Social Securities count against Lareau is a federal felony,
punishable by maximum penalties of five years in prison and $6,000
in fines.
   The money-laundering count is a misdemeanor. It is a felony only
if more than $100,000 is laundered in any 12-month period. It
carries a maximum penalty of one year in prison and $1,000.
   Federal law enforcement officials said Lareau never laundered
more than $99,000 in any one-year period.
   Voorhees said the government agreed, in return for Lareau's
plea, to recommend he spend six months in jail and be placed on
probation for five years. Lareau also faces fines of up to $6,000
when he is sentenced July 22.
   E.F. Hutton plead guilty May 16 to two money-laundering charges
and one count of conspiracy. It was fined $1.01 million, the
largest fine ever imposed on a money-laundering case.
   Hutton was acquired last year by Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc.,
and the company is now known as Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
