<DOCNO> AP880609-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-09-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-US-France-Debt     06-09 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-France-Debt,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Studying French Debt Relief Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is examining a French
proposal to forgive some of the debts of the world's poorest
countries, the State Department said Thursday.
   The proposal was transmitted in a letter to President Ronald
Reagan by French President Francois Mitterrand, said deputy
spokesman Phyllis Oakley.
   The French government announced Wednesday that it would forgive
one-third of such debts to it and would advise other members of the
Paris Club _ which includes the major creditor governments _ to do
the same.
   The plan would not apply to the world's most indebted developing
nations, such as Brazil and Mexico, because they are not among the
poorest, although France indicated it believed ways also must be
found to help them.
   ``We are studying the French proposal very closely,'' said Mrs.
Oakley.

</TEXT>
