<HEAD>Dollar Firms, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher against most major
currencies in European trading Thursday. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar opened lower but
recovered later in the session.
   Frankfurt dealers predicted the dollar would not move much until
the release of the U.S. April trade figures on Tuesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8117 late Thursday, cheaper
for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.8175.
   Other late rates in Europe compared with late rates Wednesday:
1.7230 West German marks, up from 1.7183; 1.4370 Swiss francs, up
from 1.4350; 5.8155 French francs, up from 5.7923; 1.9330 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.9250; 1,280.50 Italian lire, up from 1,273.50;
and 1.2211 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2220.
   Earlier, in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 125.43 Japanese yen, up
from 125.32 Wednesday. In London late Thursday the dollar traded at
125.25 yen.
   Gold bullion prices fell by as much as $3 an ounce.
   The late London gold price was a bid $455.25 a troy ounce, down
from $458. The Zurich late price was a bid $455.50 an ounce, down
from $458.50.
   Dealer said trading was quiet, and they thought the price might
slip to around $452 an ounce over the next few days.
   Gold had closed earlier in Hong Kong at $456.59 an ounce bid,
down from $458.98.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $7.08 a troy ounce, down
from $7.15.
