<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-09 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Soar, Grains Advance On Weather Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean and oat futures prices soared and other
grain futures closed modestly higher Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade amid diminishing prospects for rain next week in the
Midwest.
   Soybeans gyrated wildly during the session as traders digested a
confusing mix of weather information. Prices opened slightly lower
in reaction to rains Wednesday in Grain Belt, fell sharply in
response to the National Weather Service's forecast for normal
precipitation next week, then skyrocketed in the afternoon after
private meteorologists predicted a hot, dry weekend followed by
drier-than-normal conditions next week, analysts said.
   Oat futures gained throughout the session as forecasts indicated
no improvement in the drought conditions plaguing the upper Midwest.
   ``They're saying a lot of the damage is irreversible,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to 5 cents higher with
July at $3.72 a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to 3 cents higher
with July at $2.53{ a bushel; oats were 11 cents to 15 cents higher
with July at $2.50 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 30 cents
higher with July at $8.86 a bushel.
</TEXT>
