<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Crops-Wheat 1stLd-Writethru f0151 06-09 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crops-Wheat, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0151,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Wheat Forecasts Down Amid Dry Weather and Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers are harvesting a winter wheat crop
estimated at 1.57 billion bushels, slightly larger than last year's
but 3 percent under a forecast of 1.62 billion bushels issued a
month ago, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   The 50 million bushel cutback in the forecast came amid an early
drought across the midcontinent.
   ``Inadequate moisture and disease plagued winter wheat in the
central and northern Great Plains during May,'' the department's
Agricultural Statistics Board said in its report.
   Some officials said satellite photos show streak mosaic disease
is taking a toll on soft red winter wheat in Kansas and that the
dry weather could worsen the situation there. But they said a
little rain could cut damage to a minimum in other parts of the
country.
   The new forecast compares with a 1987 winter wheat output of
1.56 billion bushels. Officials said average yield should by 39.4
bushels an acre, down 0.4 bushels an acre from the 1987 level and
1.3 bushels below the May estimate.
   Crop conditions vary, the department's Agricultural Statistics
Board said in its report. As of May 29, crop conditions were mostly
fair to good in the Corn Belt, Southeast and Pacific Northwest and
fair in the Plains States, it said.
   Development of the crop was average or better except in the
Pacific Northwest and Colorado, it said. The wheat was turning
color in Illinois, Kansas and Missouri and the harvest had moved
into Oklahoma and expanded across the Delta and Southeast.
   Farmers are expected to have about 39.8 million acres for
harvest this year, the same estimate the department issued last
month and 1 percent above the level for last season.
   Winter wheat is planted in the fall and harvested the following
summer. It makes up about three-fourths of total U.S. wheat
production.
   No 1988 production estimates for spring wheat, corn and other
spring-planted crops were included in the forecast. They will be
estimated by USDA later in the growing season.
   A separate supply and demand report from the department's
Economic Research Service did say that, despite the estimated 50
million-bushel cutback, the overall U.S. wheat crop should be above
last year's level. It said that was so because of projected spring
wheat production.
   It said, moreover, that flour and related food production would
be lower by perhaps 35 million bushels and the reduction should
offset somewhat the reduced supply of winter wheat. Thus it
projected only a slight reduction in the nation's wheat stockpile.
   The Kansas winter wheat crop, as usual the largest by far, was
estimated at 329 million bushels, down from 366.3 million in 1987.
The yield was put at 35 bushels per acre compared with 37 bushels
last year. The state's farmers also trimmed their acreage to 9.4
million acres from 9.9 million in 1987.
   Indicated production of winter wheat and average yields in 1988
by major producing states, based on June 1 prospects, included:
   Arkansas, 41,800,000 bushels and an average yield of 44 bushels
per acre; California, 35,640,000 and 81; Colorado, 86,950,000 and
37; Georgia, 19,780,000 and 43; Idaho, 56,880,000 and 72; Illinois,
61,600,000 and 55; Indiana, 34,300,000 and 49; Kansas, 329,000,000
and 35; Kentucky, 15,990,000 and 41; Michigan, 29,140,000 and 47;
Missouri, 65,800,000 and 47; Montana, 52,800,000 and 24; Nebraska,
86,100,000 and 42; North Carolina, 18,900,000 and 42; Ohio,
49,920,000 and 48; Oklahoma, 176,400,000 and 36; Oregon, 42,900,000
and 66; South Dakota, 46,500,000 and 30; Tennessee, 14,820,000 and
39; Texas, 92,800,000 and 29; Washington, 89,100,000 and 54.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880609-0301 </DOCNO>
