<HEAD>Campeau Selling Filene's Basement to Management-Led Investors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Federated Cuts Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. on Thursday announced it had
agreed to sell the Filene's Basement division of Federated
Department Stores Inc. to an investor group led by Filene's
management.
   Terms of the deal, which includes the sale of 22 women's
clothing stores in the Northeast, were not disclosed.
   Besides Filene's management, the investor group includes the
investment companies, Greylock, Oak Investment Partners and J.H.
Whitney, Campeau said in a statement.
   The sale was the first of a Federated specialty store division
since Campeau took control of Federated last month in a $6.6
billion tender offer. Campeau also plans to sell Federated's Main
Street and Children's Place divisions as well as its Gold Circle
discount store chain.
   Campeau also has sold four of Federated's department store
divisions. Foley's and Filene's were bought by May Department
Stores Inc. and the Bullock's and I. Magnin chains went to R.H.
Macy & Co. Inc., which lost Federated to Campeau in a bitter
takeover battle.
   Filene's department stores were separate from the Filene's
Basement specialty store chain.
   Campeau Chairman Robert Campeau said after he won his takeover
fight he planned to raise $4.4 billion through asset sales to help
finance the purchase of Federated. He also has sold the Brooks
Brothers chain from his Allied Stores Corp. to the British retailer
Marks & Spencer.
</TEXT>
