<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-09 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pork Futures Post Second Day Of Limit Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pork futures prices plummeted their daily limits Thursday for
the second consecutive session as traders wrestled with weak demand
for pork products and abundant supplies of pork bellies.
   On other markets, soybean and oat futures soared; precious
metals gained; energy futures fell and stock-index futures
retreated.
   The Commodity Research Bureau's index of 21 agricultural and
industrial commodities advanced 1.87 points to 258.20.
   Weak wholesale demand for pork products has slowed packer demand
for hogs, raising fears that a backlog of slaughter-ready animals
has developed, analysts said.
   ``You've got a lot of people who really believe we've got tons
and tons of pork coming down the road,'' said Thomas Morgan,
president of Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill.
``That's what's got the hog markets in a tizzy.''
   Meanwhile, supplies of frozen pork bellies, which are sliced to
make bacon, have reached near-record proportions. Pork belly
futures prices have fallen sharply this week and may have to come
down even more to stimulate demand, analysts said.
   ``I think they're going to be under a lot of pressure again
tomorrow,'' said Philip Stanley, an analyst with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in Chicago.
   The August hog contract plunged the 1.5-cent daily limit
Thursday, settling at 48.70 cents a pound. Most pork belly
contracts fell the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit.
   Analysts said cattle futures fell in sympathy with pork prices.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent to .47 cent lower with the contract
for delivery in June at 72.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27
cent lower to .22 cent higher with August at 75.30 cents a pound;
hogs were 1.50 cents lower to .23 cent higher with June at 51 cents
a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.50 cents to 2 cents lower with
July at 50.87 cents a pound.
   Soybean and oat futures prices soared while other grain futures
advanced modestly on the Chicago Board of Trade amid diminishing
prospects for rain next week in the Midwest.
   Soybeans gyrated wildly during the session as private
meteorologists reduced the amount of rain in their forecasts.
   Most oat contracts advanced the expanded daily limit of 15 cents
a bushel as forecasts indicated no improvement in the drought
conditions plaguing the upper Midwest.
   ``They're saying a lot of the damage is irreversible,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   Limits on oats, soybeans, soybean meal and corn were expanded by
50 percent Monday following two straight days of maximum
permissible gains. The limits will return to normal on Friday.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department issued its monthly
report on U.S. wheat production and grain supply and demand.
   The USDA reduced its 1988 wheat production estimate to 1.57
billion bushels from 1.62 billion bushels. But the estimate was
above most analysts' expectations and was pronounced slightly
bearish for futures prices.
   The USDA slightly increased its projections for soybean and corn
ending stocks for both the current marketing year and the 1988-89
year while reducing its projected wheat ending stocks for both
years.
   But Lespinasse noted the predictions were based on conditions
June 1 ``and a lot of (drought) damage has been done since June 1.''
   ``This report will soon be forgotten,'' he said. ``Everyone will
be concentrating on the weather again tomorrow.''
   Wheat settled 2 cents lower to 5 cents higher with July at $3.72
a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to 2} cents higher with July at
$2.53} a bushel; oats were 11 cents to 15 cents higher with July at
$2.50 a bushel; soybeans were 4{ cents to 30{ cents higher with
July at $8.86 a bushel.
   Precious metals futures advanced modestly on the Commodity
Exchange in New York in a reversal from the previous day's steep
losses.
   Gold settled $1 to $1.40 higher with August at $461.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 4.5 cents to 5.5 cents higher with July at $7.18
a troy ounce.
   Energy futures posted substantial losses on the New York
Mercantile Exchange on expecatations that OPEC oil ministers will
not make any headway on production cuts when they meet this weekend
in Vienna, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 25 cents to 30 cents
lower with July at $17.08 a barrel; heating oil was .78 cent to
1.03 cents lower with July at 44.90 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .64 cent to 1 cent lower with July at 49.70 cents a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures fell slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange with the contract for delivery in June down 1 point at
271.45.
</TEXT>
