<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GiantGroup     06-09 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Giant Group,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Group Ends Talks for Sale of Cement Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations for the sale of Giant
Group Ltd.'s cement businesses have collapsed, the company said
Thursday.
   Giant, which is controlled by investor Burt Sugarman, said it
was unable to reach final agreement with Environmental Treatment
and Technologies Corp. of Findlay, Ohio, but didn't elaborate on
why the talks faltered.
   The cement companies to be sold were Giant Cement Co. of
Harleyville, S.C., and Keystone Cement Co of Bath, Pa.
   No further explanation was given for collapse of the preliminary
agreement, which originally called for Environmental Treatment to
pay $110 million cash plus warrants allowing Giant to buy
Environmental Treatment stock.
   When the preliminary agreement was announced in mid-May,
Sugarman was waging what turned out to be an unsuccessful proxy
battle for control of Media General Corp. of Richmond, Va.
   There was speculation the sale of the cement companies was
intended to raise cash for Sugarman's offer for Media General stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
